<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Eritrean Evacuation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Evacuated foreigners tell of rising tension in Eritrea 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo available
By TOM COHEN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Weary from overnight travel and
concerned about friends left behind, almost 200 foreigners
evacuated from Eritrea arrived in Frankfurt before dawn Saturday.
	   The 194 evacuees included 129 Americans, many of them U.S.
government workers or Peace Corps volunteers in the East African
nation that is heading toward war with neighboring Ethiopia.
	   They described a rising tension in Eritrea, with army reservists
called up in recent weeks to bolster forces at the disputed border
with Ethiopia that is the focus of the conflict.
	   But only when they heard the blasts of bombs dropped by
Ethiopian jet fighters Friday did the evacuees feel any fear.
	   ``We heard the sound of planes, and the bombs going,'' said
Barbara Kelly, who worked with her husband, Mike, as a teacher for
Britain's Volunteer Service Overseas charity.
	   Outside the Ethiopian Embassy in Asmara, the Eritrean capital,
people cheered and blared car horns over the downing of two
Ethiopian jets by Eritrean forces, the evacuees said.
	   ``The cars were driving past it (the embassy) and honking their
horns,'' said Aaron Greenberg, 22, of New York city, a Peace Corps
volunteer in Eritrea for the past year. ``We didn't see anything.
We were told later a plane was shot down.''
	   Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. Before that,
Eritrean rebels were instrumental in helping the Ethiopian People's
Revolutionary Democratic Front overthrow a 17-year military regime
in July 1991.
	   Greenberg and others said Eritrean friends started heading for
the border with Ethiopia four weeks ago, facing the prospect of
fighting former allies.
	   ``When they started pulling people out to the border, you knew
something was going on,'' he said. But he described the atmosphere
as basically calm, with Eritreans expressing confidence about a
possible war.
	   ``They were saying if they (Ethiopians) want war, we'll give
them war,'' he said.
	   The flight chartered by the U.S. government left Asmara at 7
p.m. Friday night (1600 GMT) and arrived in Frankfurt at about 3:30
a.m. (0130 GMT Saturday) after a refueling stop in Cairo, Egypt.
	   Katharine Puffenberger, who works for the U.S. Agency for
International Development in Asmara, said there was no panic as
people prepared to evacuate.
	   ``We weren't afraid,'' said Puffenberger, of Ogden, Utah.
``There was nothing happening in Asmara.''
	   Josh Simko, 24, of Santa Barbara, California, said he worried
about what a possible war would do to the young country.
	   ``We have friends who are at the border, and some of our
students didn't finish'' their studies because of the conflict,
said Simko, a Peace Corps teacher.
	   (tsc)
</TEXT>
