w1997 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-AngryLawmakers     06-06 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Angry Lawmakers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Politicians criticize bribery investigation as going `too far' 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Their image sullied in the wake of yet another
bribery scandal, politicians in Japan's ruling party say it's time
to take firm action to punish wrongdoers.
	   Their target: the prosecutors who investigated the scandal.
	   Liberal Democratic Party lawmakers have taken the offensive
against the Tokyo Public Prosecutors Office, which they say went
``too far'' in this year's investigation into influence peddling by
officials, Japanese newspapers reported Saturday.
	   ``It's democratic for the legislative branch to take a firm
stand when the judicial branch goes too far,'' ruling party
lawmaker Tokuichiro Tamazawa was quoted as saying by the Asahi
newspaper.
	   In particular, the lawmakers are furious that their names
appeared in the press as the investigation proceeded. They accuse
prosecutors of leaking such details to win public support.
	   The scandal drove one lawmaker to commit suicide in March as
prosecutors sought his arrest for allegedly taking bribes from
Nikko Securities Co. Nikko's president later admitted the company
made illegal payoffs to the lawmaker, Shokei Arai.
	   Investigators also arrested five officials from the Finance
Ministry and central bank between January and March on suspicion of
giving favored treatment to banks and brokerages in exchange for
lavish entertainment. The arrests forced the resignation of the
finance minister and the head of the Bank of Japan.
	   The Liberal Democrats first won a majority in Japan's parliament
in 1955 and have been embroiled in successive bribery scandals ever
since. Most recently, the Recruit scandal in 1989 toppled the
cabinet of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, and party kingpin Shin
Kanemaru was arrested in 1993 on tax evasion charges. Prosecutors
unearthed more than dlrs 40 million worth of gold bars and stock
from his Tokyo apartment.
	    &UR; (mef)
</TEXT>
