<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Former President </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian rights watchdog ready to defend ex-president 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's official human rights
watchdog has said it was ready to defend former President Suharto
against calls for unlawful revenge.
	   The National Human Rights Commission said it would stand up for
Suharto's rights as a citizen and that any action taken against the
former autocrat should be done according to the law.
	   ``We have to be fair because our country is a lawful country,''
the official Antara news agency Saturday quoted Commission member
Bambang W. Soeharto as saying.
	   Suharto resigned on May 21 following a wave of riots and
protests that were triggered by the worst economic crisis in 30
years.
	   Since then, there have been calls for the former autocrat to be
put on trial.
	   Many want an investigation into the wealth of Suharto's family,
who made billions of dollars during his 32-year rule.
	   Some say the state should seize Suharto's fortune and use it to
help the nation overcome its acute economic problems.
	   At the height of student protests last month, demonstrators even
called for Suharto to be hanged.
	   Since then, the powerful military and some leading opposition
figures have called for restraint.
	   Bambang said proper legal processes should be followed.
	   ``If he does wrong or breaks the law, then we have to bring him
to court to prove his guilt,'' Bambang said of Suharto.
	   The National Human Rights Commission was appointed by Suharto's
old government but has a track record for independence.
</TEXT>
