w2008 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Nuclear     06-06 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Nuclear,0446 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minister: Sanctions will not slow Indian economic reforms 
</HEADLINE>
By NEELESH MISRA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India will not compromise either its
security or the six-year-old economic liberalization program under
pressure from sanctions imposed after its nuclear tests, its junior
foreign minister said Saturday.
	   The United States, Australia, Japan and other countries have cut
loans and all but humanitarian aid and imposed other punishments on
India and Pakistan for the series of tit-for-tat nuclear tests the
neighboring rivals conducted last month.
	   ``We intend to continue with our liberalization process, and we
realize there are costs but the country's security comes first,''
Vasundhara Raje Scindia said in an on-line chat organized by the
U.S. network MSNBC. Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee also
kept the foreign minister's portfolio, but Scindia is his top
foreign affairs aide.
	   Scindia's colleague, Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha, has said
the impact of the sanctions has been ``overplayed and highly
exaggerated.''
	   India said it was threatened by neighbors China, a declared
nuclear power, and Pakistan _ which until last month had kept
secret its nuclear capabiity. India and Pakistan now both claim to
be nuclear weapons states, but experts question whether either has
the capability to deliver a nuclear bomb to a target.
	   Meanwhile at the United Nations, the Security Council has
reached tentative agreement on a Japanese resolution urging India
and Pakistan to halt their nuclear weapons programs and denying
them status as nuclear states.
	   India accused the council of overstepping its authority. Its
envoy questioned in a letter to the council president why the
members were tolerating ``the continued retention of nuclear
weapons by the nuclear weapons states'' _ which are also the five
permanent members of the council.
	   ``Across the world people should think about disarming,''
Scindia was quoted as saying in an MSNBC transcript provided to The
Associated Press.
	   A South African user asked if India saw the tests as a victory
even though they led the five traditional nuclear powers to openly
discuss the situation in Kashmir, the territorial issue at the
heart of the Indo-Pakistan rivalry. India has long resisted
international pressure on the Kashmir issue, while Pakistan has
wanted outside mediation because it feels at a disadvantage in
one-on-one talks with its larger and more powerful neighbor.
	   ``Kashmir is a bilateral situation. There is no question of it
being internationalized. It is the business of India,'' Scindia
said.
</TEXT>
