<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Economic Slowdown </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: GDP growth expected at 6.5-6.8 percent 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ A senior Vietnamese official said his
country's economy is expected to grow at only 6.5 percent to 6.8
percent in the first six months of 1998, down from 9.1 percent the
same time last year, a newspaper reported Saturday.
	   Nguyen Tan Dung, first deputy prime minister and a member of the
powerful Politburo, was quoted as saying the country is coping with
problems much greater than foreseen earlier this year.
	   He blamed low economic efficiency and competitiveness, damage
from Typhoon Linda in 1997, the worst drought in a century and the
impact of the Asian financial crisis.
	   ``The bad impact of the regional crisis on our economy was not
within our prediction,'' Dung was quoted as saying by the Thanh
Nien newspaper.
	   ``Vietnam is not at the eye of the regional crisis and its
impact has not yet reversed our (economic) development, but it left
a relatively heavy impact on our economy,'' he said.
	   In an interview with the Labor newspaper, Deputy Prime Minister
Nguyen Cong Tan said unemployment is the government's biggest
concern.
	   He outlined several measures to revive lagging foreign
investment, including streamlining procedures. Many foreign
businessmen complain about Vietnam's red tape.
	   Dung said Typhoon Linda, which swept across the Mekong Delta
leaving more than 300 people dead and thousands missing last year,
and the drought have caused a combined dlrs 1 billion in damage.
	   Dung also said that over the last six months, the trade deficit
has risen by 20 percent and industries have laid off 250,000
workers due to shrinking production.
</TEXT>
