<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
King denies he is behind Constitutional Council rift 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ King Norodom Sihanouk denied
Saturday any role in a boycott at the country's highest legal
appeals body that could affect the credibility of upcoming
elections.
	   The inaugural meeting of the Constitutional Council, a
nine-member body charged with solving election-related disputes,
was stalled for the second time Friday when the king's three
appointees failed to show.
	   The three elder statesman appear to be boycotting the opening
meeting in protest of the make-up of the body, which is supposed to
be neutral but is heavily stacked in favor of Cambodian strongman
Hun Sen. Six members are affiliated to his Cambodian People's
Party.
	   In a faxed statement, the king strongly denied ``any
ill-intentioned allegations'' that he was behind the boycott.
	   Hun Sen ousted the king's son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, as his
co-premier in a bloody coup d'etat 11 months ago. He has sought new
elections to win back aid and legitimacy lost after the violent
takeover.
	   The Constitutional Council, charged with determining the
constitutionality of all laws, would be called on to resolve any
problems that arise with Cambodia's controversial electoral and
political parties laws.
	   The former chairman of the Supreme Court, Chan Sok, who also
sits on the body, warned Friday that a further deadlock could call
into question the credibility of elections scheduled for July. He
said Sihanouk might be asked to intervene if the stalemate
continues.
	   ``We are taking no decision now, but we will wait and see if
they (the three appointees) change their minds and return to the
meeting,'' Chan Sok said, adding that no date has been set for the
next session.
</TEXT>
