<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKorea-Parliamentary Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
North Korea gearing up for first parliamentary election in eight years 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ North Korea is establishing election
committees throughout the isolated communist state for its first
parliamentary election in eight years, the official news media
reported Saturday.
	   The election, slated for July 26, will choose deputies to the
Supreme People's Assembly, the North's rubber-stamp legislature,
whose major mission will likely be to elect leader Kim Jong Il as
president.
	   The 1994 death of Kim's father, longtime President Kim Il Sung,
left North Korea a headless state. The junior Kim, 56, has been in
firm control but has yet to become president.
	   ``Preparations for the election of deputies to the 10th Supreme
People's Assembly of (North Korea) are briskly going on in all
parts of the country,'' the North's official Korean Central News
Agency said.
	   Kim Jong Il currently leads North Korea as the supreme military
commander and general secretary of the ruling Workers' Party.
	   North Korea elected 687 deputies to its single chamber
parliament in 1990. A new election at the end of their four-year
term was canceled because of Kim Il Sung's death in 1994.
	   North Korea has since been operating without a legislative body.
	   In May, the North announced it will hold the new election on
July 26.
</TEXT>
