<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Foreign Workers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore survey says foreign workers welcomed by most 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Three-fourths of Singaporeans in a survey
supported the government's moves to welcome more skilled foreign
workers, a major newspaper reported Saturday.
	   Those in their 20s were most enthusiastic, and people in their
40s the most worried, according to the survey of 505 people by The
Straits Times. No margin of error was given.
	   The paper said that those who supported the government feel
foreigners bring economic benefits to the island nation of 3.1
million and make it more exciting.
	   The minority who oppose the plans told the surveyors they felt
foreigners bring economic and social problems.
	   Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong announced the policy last August,
saying Singapore needs foreign talent at all levels of the economy
because of the small local talent pool.
</TEXT>
