<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Military Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Indonesian police go on trial in killings of four student protesters comment from another defense lawyer. CORRECTS spelling of defendants' names. Some Indonesians use one name only. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES throughout with charges, case adjourned until Tuesday,
AP Photos staffing
By IRWAN FIRDAUS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Two police lieutenants accused in the
killing of four student protesters were arraigned in a military
court Saturday in what defense lawyers said was a hasty, misguided
attempt to satisfy public clamor for reform.
	   The May 12 shootings at Trisakti University in the capital,
Jakarta, sparked several days of deadly rioting that helped oust
former President Suharto, who had been facing growing challenges to
his rule amid the worst economic crisis in decades.
	   The two officers are among 18 policemen who face courts-martial
as the military responds to demands for accountability and
democracy under Indonesia's new president, B.J. Habibie.
	   In opening remarks, military prosecutor Col. Hadi Purnomo said
the two defendants caused the deaths of the students because they
had been undisciplined and unable to control their troops during
the rally against Suharto.
	   First Lt. Agus Tri Heryanto and Second Lt. Pariyo, who were
charged with disobeying orders and flouting proper procedures, are
likely to face dismissal and jail time if found guilty. The case
was adjourned until Tuesday.
	   Outside the courthouse, students from the university where the
victims were slain held up banners that read, ``Put the masterminds
of the killings on trial'' and ``Hey general, why are the
defendants just low-ranking officers?''
	   Some critics speculate that the students were gunned down on
orders from top military brass, possibly in an attempt to snuff out
near-daily student protests that were growing in size and
intensity.
	   ``The two defendants are people who have been sacrificed,''
defense lawyer Buyung Nasution told a packed courtroom. ``It is
possible they are not the real killers.''
	   Another defense lawyer, police Lt. Col. Suseno, said the
prosecutor accused his clients ``in order to make the students or
the people in this era of reform satisfied.''
	   The two uniformed officers sat impassively before a military
judge. Fellow officers on the benches periodically applauded
remarks by the defense attorney. Students outside listened to
loudspeakers.
</TEXT>
