<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-President </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korean president leaves for the United States 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ President Kim Dae-jung embarked
Saturday on a nine-day trip to the United States, where he will
seek more economic assistance and propose a new policy of
engagement toward North Korea.
	   Kim has said his talks with President Clinton in Washington on
June 9 will focus on international assistance to help rebuild South
Korea's battered economy and ways to lead communist North Korea to
peace talks with rival South Korea.
	   In the United States, Kim, a longtime opposition leader, will
receive a human rights award. He will also speak at Stanford and
Georgetown universities and meet with Secretary of Treasury Robert
Rubin as well as International Monetary Fund and World Bank
officials.
	   South Korea's economy was bailed out by the IMF in December.
	   Kim has focused his first 100 days in office on restructuring
the economy to woo back foreign investors whose flight aggravated
the country's financial turmoil late last year.
</TEXT>
