w2046 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-RugbyU-NewSout     06-06 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-New South Wales-Scotland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scots beat New South Wales 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Scotland continued its buildup for two
tests against Australia by beating an under strength New South
Wales team 34-10 at the Sydney Football Stadium on Saturday.
	   The Waratahs were missing their top players _ in action for
Australia in Saturday's test against England in Brisbane _ and were
hit hard early in the match.
	   The Scots, well led by veteran back Gregor Townsend and captain
Rob Wainwright played a tougher match than against New South Wales
Country midweek. Former Wallaby scrum half Steve Merrick described
the tourists as soft after that match.
	   Scotland started with a blaze of scoring Saturday, running in
three tries to take a 21-0 lead after just 16 minutes.
	   No. 8 Eric Peters and lock Stuart Grimes set up the first for
winger Shaun Longstaff after eight minutes. Four minutes later the
Scots grabbed a second when fly-half Townsend broke through the
defense and sent fullback Glenn Metcalfe over.
	   Townsend also engineered the third try, combining with Metcalfe
and Longstaff to put lock Scott Murray across the line.
	   Shell-shocked New South Wales recovered briefly as former
Springbok No.8 Tiaan Strauss and center Jason Jones-Hughes set up
Matt Dowling for a 65-meter dash to the try line.
	   Scotland led 21-5 at half-time and won comfortably in the end.
	   ``It's a big confidence boost for us,'' Townsend said. ``We had
a slow start to the tour but we're slowly building.''
	   Townsend said the Scottish scrum was the best he has seen it all
season while the attack was also impressive.
	   Scorers:
	   Scotland 34 (Shaun Longstaff, Glenn Metcalfe, Scott Murray,
Craig Joiner tries; Rowen Shepherd 4 goals, 2 penalty goals) def.
New South Wales 10 (Matt Williams, Brendan Williams tries).
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
