w2080 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Explosives     06-06 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Explosives </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Raids prompted by bombings, blasts yield 196 tons of explosives 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Police inspections prompted by a spate of
bombings have yielded some 196 tons of explosives and other
contraband and led to the closing of hundreds of factories and
shops, the state-run newspaper China Daily reported Saturday.
	   The nationwide crackdown on explosives that began at the end of
March was the result of a sharp rise in criminal and accidental
explosions across the country, the report said.
	   It said that 721 people were killed and 905 injured in some 466
explosions last year.
	   The problem was most severe in the mining and construction
industries, where safety standards are often ignored in the
transport, storage and use of explosives, the report added.
	   ``Management of explosives within these operations was slack and
many explosives slipped into the wrong hands,'' it said.
	   The report said that 577 explosives makers and 1,202 shops
selling explosives had been closed down, and 1,272 lawbreakers
punished after an inspection of some 17,000 places involved in the
explosives business.
	   In addition to explosives, police also confiscated 310,000
detonators and 300,000 meters (990,000 feet) of blasting fuses.
	   Police said an explosion in February on a public bus in the
central city of Wuhan that killed 16 people and injured 45 others
was caused by a homemade bomb.
	   Three people were arrested for planting a car bomb that exploded
on May 10, killing a bank executive, according to state media
reports. 	   
</TEXT>
