<HEADER>
w2089 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-AirlinePriva     06-06 0291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Airline Privatization </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Privatization of Thai Airways faces hurdles 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The privatization of state-owned Thai
Airways International still faces problems though the Cabinet is
expected to back a share sale next week.
	   Thai newspapers reported Saturday that the Finance Ministry is
being challenged by other government agencies over how many shares
should be offered to the carrier's foreign airline partners
compared to non-airline Thai investors.
	   The partial privatization of Thai Airways is a condition set by
the International Monetary Fund for the dlrs 17.2 billion bailout
it has arranged for Thailand's troubled economy.
	   Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai's Cabinet is expected to approve a
privatization plan Tuesday, but disputes have arisen over ministry
plans to reduce the government's stake to under 70 percent, the
minimum required under a 1954 law.
	   The plan would cut the government's stake from 97 percent to 68
percent, offering 380 million shares to Thai's partners in the Star
Alliance _ United, Lufthansa, Air Canada, SAS and Varig.
	   Transport, budget and airline officials want the 70 percent
minimum retained and object to ministry plans to limit the
offering, saying it will cheapen the share price.
	   Some shares should be offered to financial institutions as well
as Thai and foreign investors and airline employees, they said.
	   The Cabinet is also to rule on a proposed rehabilitation plan
under which the airline will switch its strategy toward European
and North American markets, away from crisis-stricken Asia.
	   The airline is also required to slash 11.9 billion baht (dlrs
297 million) from expenditures from the fiscal year ending Sept.
30.
</TEXT>
