<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Taiwan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China says site of fatal boat attack now safe for tourists 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ The government has launched a publicity campaign
intended to encourage tourists to visit a lake that was the site of
a 1994 attack that killed 32, including tourists from Taiwan.
	   In the past four years, the local government at Qiandao Lake has
set up a satellite telecommunications network, equipped tour boats
with alarm systems and telephones and assigned police to regular
patrols to prevent any further incidents, the newspaper China Daily
reported Saturday.
	   Any tourist who encounters trouble can dial ``110'' and a police
official will travel to his aid by motorboat within 10 minutes, the
report said.
	   Tourism around the lake dropped sharply after the March 31,
1994, attack said to have been staged by robbers who set fire to a
tour boat, killing its crew and passengers.
	   Qiandao, a man-made reservoir built in 1960 about 250 kilometers
southwest of Shanghai, is a popular sightseeing location because of
the 1,078 scenic islands that dot its clear waters, the report
added. 	   
</TEXT>
