<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Religion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese bishop arrested; government takes passport of 96-year-old cardinal 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ A bishop in the underground Roman Catholic church
has been arrested, according to a U.S.-based advocacy group for the
underground church.
	   Bishop Zhang Weizhu of Xianxian, in Hebei province near Beijing,
was detained on May 31, Pentacost Sunday, while traveling to his
village, Joseph Kung, director of the Cardinal Kung Foundation,
said in a statement received Saturday in Beijing.
	   It said no other details were available about Zhang's arrest.
	   Meanwhile, the group said the Chinese government had refused to
renew the passport of its namesake, 96-year-old Cardinal Ignatius
Kung Pin-mei.
	   Cardinal Kung, the bishop of Shanghai, was imprisoned in China
for more than 32 years and now lives in exile in the United States.
	   The cardinal recently submitted his passport to the Chinese
Consulate in New York, seeking to have it renewed. But the
consulate refused. It confiscated the document, leaving Kung
stateless, Joseph Kung said.
	   Official comment was not immediately available because
government offices were closed for the weekend.
	   The underground Roman Catholic church remains loyal to the
Vatican and rejects the state-approved Catholic church, autonomous
from Rome, that was set up by the government in the 1950s.
	   Like Cardinal Kung, many clerics of the underground church have
been imprisoned for refusing to participate in the official
Catholic church. 	   
</TEXT>
