<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands call for self-determination in East Timor capital 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ With political freedom flowering in the
rest of Indonesia, several thousand people gathered Saturday at a
forum in East Timor and called for a referendum on independence for
the former Portuguese colony.
	   Participants at the meeting in the local government office in
Dili, capital of disputed East Timor, also urged the release of
jailed rebel chief Xanana Gusmao.
	   Bowing to demands for democratic reform, the Indonesian
government has launched the phased release of political prisoners,
but the fate of Gusmao remains uncertain.
	   On Monday, authorities released four East Timorese activists who
had been jailed in September on charges of possessing bomb-making
materials.
	   Chances of a referendum on independence are remote, for now.
While new President B.J. Habibie has pledged to lead Indonesia
toward democracy, he has said that East Timor will remain part of
Indonesia.
	   Habibie took over from his autocratic mentor and predecessor,
Suharto, who quit May 21 amid Indonesia's worst economic and
political turmoil since the former army general rose to power in
the 1960s.
	   Suharto engineered Indonesia's invasion of East Timor in 1975
and declared the territory a province a year later. A small band of
separatist guerrillas continues to fight and the United Nations
does not recognize Indonesian authority there.
	   At the forum in Dili, Gov. Abilio Soares suggested that the
territory be made a special district with some autonomy, but the
vast majority of participants rejected his view, saying
self-determination was the best path.
</TEXT>
