r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-PlunderedArt     06-06 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Plundered Art,0452 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seventeen plundered Italian works identified in Germany 
</HEADLINE>
By DANIEL J. WAKIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Three years after Italy published and distributed a
catalog in an effort to find 1,500 works plundered by the Nazis or
lost in war, the first fruits have arrived.
	   The German government has acknowledged that 17 works reside in
its museums, including pieces purchased for Adolf Hitler and
Hermann Goering, the Italian diplomat in charge of the recuperation
effort said Friday.
	   Now, Italy must rely on the kindness of curators to get them
back.
	   Most of the identified statues and paintings were bought by
German agents or given as gifts. In most cases, trying to force
their return would be unproductive, said Mario Bondioli Osio, head
of a joint committee from the foreign and culture ministries.
	   ``We will rely on the professional correctness and sense of
honesty,'' of the curators, he said.
	   ``It is not a question of life and death to get them back. (The
Germans) are relaxed, perhaps a bit too much, and we are relaxed,
perhaps a bit too much.''
	   He said he is waiting to hear from the foreign ministry in
Germany to set up a meeting _ a contact that could pave the way to
discuss the matters with curators.
	   The identified works include the ``Portrait of Pier Maria
Rossi'' by the 16th century painter Parmigianino, which was sold to
Hitler's agents, and a 2nd century statue of Venus that Italo
Balbo, the Fascist aviation minister, gave Goering in 1940.
	   A German edition of the catalog, the result of more than 20
years of research, was distributed to more than 700 museums. The 17
works were identified by German curators in Hanover, Berlin,
Wurzburg and elsewhere.
	   Still missing is the sculpted mask of a faun by Michelangelo,
stolen from a castle near Arezzo in Tuscany by German troops and
art by Sandro Botticelli, Hans Holbein and Rembrandt.
	   Despite the few identifications so far, Bondioli Osio said he
was ``optimistic, but not enthusiastic'' that more will come to
light. Many on the list probably have been destroyed, he said.
Others may be in private hands.
	   Italy has a right to the pieces in Germany because they left the
country without export licenses, the diplomat said. He also cited
the Allies' London Declaration of 1943, which deemed null and void
all art acquisitions by the Nazis.
	   It's debatable, though, how much the Italians would want at
least one of the pieces, a statue of a male torso dated to the 2nd
century.
	   Bondioli Osio said it is a 20th century reproduction. He also
said the Parmigianino may not be an original.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Italy-Plundered Art; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
