<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethnic tension surfaces in Taipei's mayoral election 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Ethnic tension surfaced Saturday as two
prominent candidates prepared to begin their campaign for the
crucial Taipei mayoral election in December.
	   Former Justice Minister Ma Ying-jeou, who favors reunification
with China, has vowed not to stir up ethnic conflict since he
announced last week he will run against the incumbent
pro-independence Mayor Chen Shui-bian of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party.
	   But at a rally early this week, Ma criticized Chen for showing
his eagerness to formally break away from China by refusing to
hoist the national flag.
	   ``If I win the race, you will see our national flag hoisted at
the city hall,'' Ma said.
	   Ma, son of a ruling Nationalist official from central Chinese
Hunan province, vehemently backs the Nationalist doctrine of
reunification with China, from where his family fled after a civil
war ended in 1949.
	   In a rebuttal, Chen's aides on Saturday criticized Ma for his
inability to speak the Taiwanese dialect.
	   ``Ma Ying-jeou speaks perfect English but can hardly speak the
Taiwanese dialect although he has lived here for more than 40
years,'' Chen's top aide Ma Yung-cheng told reporters.
	   The Democratic Progressive Party advocates formal independence
from China.
	   Mayor Chen has removed from the city hall any symbols of ties
with China and the old authoritarian era, including portraits of
Sun Yat-sen, founder of modern China, and the late Nationalist
leader Gen. Chiang Kai-shek.
	   Chen was born in Taiwan like 70 percent of Taipei's population
of 2.6 million.
	   A survey released Saturday said 35.6 percent of Taipei citizens
feared the mayoral race could trigger ethnic conflicts.
	   Another 37 percent of the respondents said they did not believe
ethnic tension would be raised. The survey of 867 Taipei citizens
conducted June 1-4 by Nationalist city councillor Chen Shueh-fen
did not give a margin of error.
	   Mayoral elections in Taipei and the southern Kaohsiung city will
be held in conjuction with legislative elections.
	   Surveys indicated the mayoral races are even.	   
</TEXT>
