<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 5th Ld-Writethru,0894 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopian jets bomb airport outside Eritrean capital military-civilian, EDITS to conform; quote from American Peace Corps volunteer; UPDATES with German military plane en route to Asmara being diverted; minor editing. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: SUBS lead to clarify that airport is combined
AP Photos AMS101-108
By JULIA STEWART
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Ethiopian warplanes bombed a combined
military-civilian airport Saturday outside the Eritrean capital,
escalating a border dispute between the two East African nations.
	   Several bombs struck the civilian part of the airport, setting
off fires as foreigners were trying to leave the country.
Anti-aircraft guns fired on two Ethiopian warplanes, but neither
appeared to have been hit.
	   There was no immediate report of casualties.
	   It was the second day in a row that the airport was hit by
Ethiopian bombs. On Friday, Ethiopian MiG-23s bombed two hangars at
the military air base next to the civilian airport. A commercial
airliner on the tarmac was reported damaged. Eritrean guns then
shot down the two jets.
	   Witnesses saw several injured Eritreans on Friday being
transported in trucks, but it was not immediately possible to
determine the number of casualties or the fate of the Ethiopian
pilots.
	   Jubilant Eritreans poured into the streets of Asmara waving the
blue, green and red flags of their young nation after the Ethiopian
fighters were shot down.
	   ``The cars were driving past (the Ethiopian Embassy) and honking
their horns,'' said Aaron Greenberg, 22, an American Peace Corps
volunteer who arrived early Saturday on an evacuation flight to
Frankfurt, Germany.
	   In the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, the Foreign Ministry said
Friday's bombing was in retaliation for an Eritrean attack on
Mekele, 200 kilometers (125 miles) north of Addis. At least 44
Ethiopians were killed and 135 wounded in the Mekele attack, Radio
FANA, run by the Ethiopian ruling party, reported Saturday.
	   Eritrea and Ethiopia are at odds over a border region that is
claimed by both sides. Both nations _ two of the world's poorest _
have used aircraft, tanks and artillery supplied to Ethiopia by the
Soviet Union during the Cold War.
	   The escalating conflict prompted the U.S. State Department to
order nonessential staff out of Eritrea and urge other Americans to
leave.
	   Britain, the United Nations and the European Union were planning
evacuation flights for Saturday.
	   A German military plane en route to Asmara to evacuate German,
Swiss and other European nationals was diverted to a ``neighboring
country'' because of the airport attacks, a German foreign ministry
spokesman said Saturday.
	   A flight chartered by the U.S. government left Asmara Friday
night and arrived in Frankfurt early Saturday after a refueling
stop in Cairo, Egypt.
	   The plane carried 194 evacuees, including 129 Americans, many of
them U.S. government or Peace Corps volunteers in the East African
nation, said the U.S. Consulate in Frankfurt.
	   The evacuees after landing in Frankfurt described rising tension
in Eritrea, with army reservists called up in recent weeks to
bolster forces at the disputed border with Ethiopia. But only when
they heard the blasts of bombs dropped by Ethiopian warplanes
Friday did the evacuees feel any fear.
	   ``We heard the sound of planes, and the bombs going,'' said
evacuee Barbara Kelly, who worked with her husband, Mike, as a
teacher for Britain's Volunteer Service Overseas charity.
	   Ethiopian sources said fighting continued Friday for a third day
around the border town of Zala Ambassa, about 100 kilometers (60
miles) north of Mekele, where both sides traded tank, artillery and
mortar fire. Ethiopian fighters attacked Eritrean tanks that were
moving toward Adigrat, about 20 kilometers (10 miles) west.
	   The attacks came a day after Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi agreed to a U.S. and Rwandan proposal to end the border
conflict peacefully.
	   But Meles warned that his country's patience was wearing thin
because of Eritrea's refusal to withdraw from territory Ethiopia
claims it occupied a month ago.
	   The Eritrean government issued a statement Friday saying there
were ``still serious issues of detail and implementation to be
worked out'' with the proposal.
	   The U.S. State Department urged Ethiopia and Eritrea to cease
all hostilities while outside envoys seek a peaceful resolution of
the dispute.
	   At the United Nations in New York, the Security Council on
Friday urged an immediate cease-fire and Secretary-General Kofi
Annan appealed to both sides to ``give diplomacy a chance.''
	   ``The Security Council deplored this escalation and called for
an immediate cease-fire'' and ``urged Eritrea and Ethiopia to
affirm their commitment to resolve the dispute peacefully,''
council President Antonio Monteiro of Portugal said.
	   One of the recommendations of the U.S.-Rwandan proposal was that
Eritrea withdraw to positions held before May 6.
	   Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. Eritrean
rebels were instrumental in helping the Ethiopian People's
Revolutionary Democratic Front overthrow a 17-year military regime
in July 1991.
</TEXT>
