<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France strike enters sixth day; pilots pessimistic World Cup, latest negotiations suspended, CHANGES byline. 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: LEDES with prime minister saying strike won't disrupt the
AP Photos Planned
By DEBORAH SEWARD
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Saturday
said he did not think the Air France strike would disrupt the World
Cup but that he was worried about the future of the airline
company.
	   ``It's not the World Cup that concerns me, it's the recovery
underway of the company and its future,'' said Jospin as he went
into a meeting of the national council of the Socialist Party.
	   The World Cup will take place ``normally,'' Jospin said.
``French people don't need to take a plane to attend the World Cup.
Nor do Europeans, and we are going to find a lot of airline
companies to transport the rest at the expense of Air France.''
	   Jospin said the French government was ready to intervene to help
end the the strike and would play a role ``in the hours to come.''
	   Meanwhile, talks between Air France management and the
representatives of the striking pilots broke off Saturday shortly
before 8 a.m. (0600 GMT) after an entire night of negotiations.
	   The stumbling blocks remain planned salary cuts and a proposal
by Air France to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay
reductions.
	   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, the president of Air France, said the two
sides had worked out a way to end the conflict and talks were
simply suspended to give both parties time to reflect.
	   The pilots appeared more pessimistic.
	   ``It's so serious I prefer not to talk to you about it,'' said
Christian Paris, the spokesman for the SNPL, the main pilots'
union.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Saturday. Meanwhile, a train strike disrupted service
Saturday, although many lines were running as scheduled.
	   Top sports officials on Friday insisted that the June 10-July 12
World Cup would go ahead and that France would play the perfect
host.
	   ``I can assure you all 64 matches will be played and the French
will do everything possible to welcome the foreigners coming to
France,'' said Sepp Blatter, a senior soccer official and candidate
for the sport's top job _ head of the world governing body FIFA.
	   Michel Platini, former French soccer great and co-president of
the World Cup organizing committee, said five years of planning
would not be wrecked by labor disputes.
	   ``De Gaulle once said it was difficult to govern a country with
360 types of cheese. But we shall persevere,'' he said, referring
to former French leader Gen. Charles de Gaulle.
	   (dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
