<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Nuclear,0533 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistani prime minister seeking help to combat sanctions 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos ISL101
By ARTHUR MAX
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pinched by sanctions for his nuclear
ambitions, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was heading Saturday to the
Gulf region to ensure oil keeps flowing to Pakistan.
	   Officials said Sharif's mission to Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates was aimed at securing the credit needed to maintain
oil imports. Pakistan bought dlrs 1.2 billion of petroleum products
over nine months up to March, the latest figure available.
	   Speaking to a joint session of Parliament before his scheduled
departure, Sharif justified his decision to follow India's lead in
testing nuclear devices, saying Pakistan had taken its future in
its own hands.
	   ``The future of every Pakistani is now secure,'' he said. He
said Pakistan was forced to go nuclear when the international
community failed to tackle what he called India's aggressive
posture.
	   He repeated Pakistan's moves were defensive. ``We do not intend
to wipe out anyone from the face of the earth,'' he said.
	   Led by the United States, several countries imposed economic
sanctions against the two South Asian rivals designed to discourage
foreign investment and credit.
	   Islamabad expects to be squeezed by sanctions that will cut off
financing for some aid projects through the International Monetary
Fund, and by a lowering of its credit rating that will make
commercial borrowing more expensive.
	   The U.N. Security Council was expected to pass a resolution
urging the India and Pakistan to halt their nuclear weapons
programs, and denying them status as nuclear weapons states.
	   The resolution evolved from a meeting Thursday in Geneva by the
foreign ministers of the five permanent Security Council members _
the original nuclear weapons states.
	   Both Pakistan and India declined to address the specific demands
by the foreign ministers to refrain from turning their nuclear
capability into weapons, to end missile testing and to abide by the
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, which has been signed by 186 other
nations.
	   In its response Friday, Pakistan said it would ``not allow
itself to be placed in a position of strategic vulnerability or
inequality,''
	   While Pakistan welcomed the initiative of the five trying to
contain the nuclear threat on the subcontinent, India rejected the
offer of help from the United States, Britain, Russia, France.
	   ``There is no room for any outside involvement of any nature
whatsoever in this process,'' an Indian government statement said.
	   Both India and Pakistan said they have completed their series of
nuclear tests, and India announced a moratorium on future testing
which it was prepared to make binding through international
negotiations.
	   Pakistan has made no commitment against more.
	   The Frontier Post, citing defense sources, reported Saturday
that four tunnels at the test site in the Baluchistan desert remain
unused and ready for future tests. Six of the 10 tunnels dug near
the Iranian border were used to contain the explosions May 28 and
May 30, it said.
</TEXT>
