<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
As search for bodies ends, train crash rescuers face the tragedy their search for bodies, special commission sealing final section of crash site for its investigation. Fixes spelling throughout of Wissmann. HBG108,105,107 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING
Eds: UPDATES throughout with death toll at 102, rescuers winding up
AP Photos ESC101-102,107,111, TLK108,109, MUN101, FRA108,
By TONY CZUCZKA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ESCHEDE, Germany (AP) _ Rescuers wound up their search Saturday
for victims in postwar Germany's deadliest train accident,
delicately digging the last of the bodies from a sandbank by hand.
	   A special commission sealed the final part of the accident site
for its investigation into the cause of Wednesday's high-speed
train derailment that killed 102 people in northern Germany.
	   Investigators so far have focused on a wheel failure as the
likely cause.
	   Rescuers used their hands to sift through sand at the scene to
avoid any further damage to already mangled bodies. Four additional
bodies were found early Saturday, bringing the total number
recovered to 97. Five people have died in hospital.
	   While doctors working round the clock will continue to identify
the victims over the weekend, the rescuers _ soldiers, firefighters
and Red Cross volunteers _ should be able to get some needed rest.
But rest will also bring reflection, time to consider the grim
impact of what they've been doing.
	   ``I've never had to deal with so many dead people,'' said Dirk
Winkler, a 25-year-old soldier whose tank battalion has been using
its vehicles to pull back the wreckage of InterCity Express 884.
	   Investigators say a wheel had broken on the first passenger car.
Two minutes later, the derailed train started breaking apart and
crashed into supports of an overpass.
	   After recalling for inspections all the ICE trains of the type
that crashed, the German Rail company ordered trains returning to
circulation to run slower _ top speed of 160 kilometers (100 miles)
per hour, rather than the usual maximum 280 kilometers (175 miles).
	   Transportation Minister Matthias Wissmann rejected a long-term
speed limit for the trains. The daily Neuen Osnabrucker Zeitung
quoted him Saturday as saying that the trains and tracks had been
designed for the higher speeds.
	   But Wissmann said in an interview with Focus magazine that the
ministry and the Deutsche Bahn railroad were considering a security
system that would warn of wheel breaks and derailments.
	   When the train hit the bridge near Eschede, it was going 200
kilometers (125 miles). With a huge yellow crane, rescuers on
Friday lifted the last fragment of the collapsed bridge from the
top of the smashed train. The cable creaked from the weight.
	   All the bodies found under the wreckage were taken to a hospital
morgue in Hanover, 50 kilometers (30 miles) to the south. In teams,
doctors catalog distinguishing features _ teeth, scars, moles,
facial hair, jewelry. Then they match their records with
information from relatives. It's difficult, because so many bodies
were mangled, and by Friday only 19 victims had been identified.
	   ``We don't want any relatives to have to go from body to body.
because it's unbearable. It's arms and legs and heads. It's
awful,'' said Christian Jung, spokesman for the Hanover medical
school hospital.
	   Accounting of the victims has been difficult partly because,
unlike in an airline disaster, there are no passenger lists on
ICEs. People may buy a ticket on board, so authorities don't even
know how many passengers they're trying to account for.
	   Wissmann also ruled out the introduction of passenger lists as
inpractical, according to Neuen Osnabrucker Zeitung.
	   Rescuers, like the doctors, have worked almost continuously
since arriving at the scene midday Wednesday. During a break on
Friday, they seemed both dazed and animated, pumped up from stress
and on automatic-pilot to cope with it.
	   Some described little tricks _ everyday chit-chat at the site,
silly jokes on the way home in the car. Anything to distract the
mind from what the hands have been doing, and the eyes seeing.
	   ``We have to be strong,'' said Birgit Aust, 25, a housewife,
mother of three and Red Cross volunteer.
	   ``The worst moment was when I got there and saw the bridge on
top of the train. Then I shut off. You have to suppress all that
right now. Otherwise, you can't keep going.''
	   Aust said she expected to work through the weekend, recovering
the remains of the dead and comforting the victims' relatives.
	   Next week _ when the gravity hits _ she plans to seek comfort
herself, through counseling.
	   (tc-aet-im)
</TEXT>
