</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake,0600 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poor coordination, too few aircraft, hamper relief to quake victims 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Stands for Faisabad-dated story on digest
AP Photos
By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ROSTAQ, Afghanistan (AP) _ Their villages in ruins, dispirited
Afghans complained Saturday about the slow pace of international
aid, as more aftershocks sent people scurrying in panic into the
open.
	   In the week since a massive quake devastated a 700-square-mile
(1,750-square-kilometer) region of northern Afghanistan, few relief
flights have reached this miserable region that was struck twice in
four months.
	   Estimates say up to 5,000 people died from the May 30 quake,
more than twice as many fatalities as in the February disaster.
	   ``People have forgotten us,'' said Mullah Suban Qulle, the
deputy governor of Rostaq. ``The help is limited and it's too
late.''
	   The latest aftershock Saturday morning sent shudders under feet,
rattled walls in Rostaq and sent clouds of dust spiraling from the
mountainsides.
	   Stunned townspeople tumbled into the streets, misery and fear
written on their faces.
	   Dozens villages in the Rostaq were annihilated in the February
quake, when relief efforts were stymied by deep snow and freezing
temperatures.
	   ``It is the second time these people have suffered. They cannot
stay in their villages any more. They are hungry, and there are no
facilities to take care of them,'' the deputy governor told the
first journalist to reach the town since the quake.
	   Qulle charged that the United Nations and non-governmental
organizations involved in the relief were poorly coordinated, which
was costing lives.
	   In Faisabad, the headquarters for the relief operation, food
distribution and evacuation of the injured resumed Saturday after
being interrupted by heavy rains. Faisabad is 70 kilometers (40
miles) over rugged mountains from Rostaq.
	   But there were conflicting demands for the three helicopters and
meager fuel the United Nations and Red Cross have been able to
muster at the airstrip.
	   The helicopters are the sole means to deliver food, carry
doctors to treat the injured and evacuate the serious hurt.
	   One of the helicopters leased from Tajikistan was used to fly
journalists to the Tajik capital of Dushanbe instead of for aid
flights.
	   The scarce fuel came under more pressure when three Pakistani
helicopters that had brought rice to Faisabad demanded refueling
from U.N. stocks at the airstrip.
	   ``I'm afraid it's a lack of coordination between the (U.N.)
people here and in Islamabad, said Ayaz Wazir, the director of
Pakistan's Foreign Ministry. He said he was assured in the
Pakistani capital that enough fuel was available.
	   One helicopter reached the village of Angaryan, 30 kilometers
(18 miles) west of Faisabad, where it was approached by a
distraught Moqim Ahmad who had lost all four of his children.
	   ``When I left early in the morning, everything was fine. After
the earthquake, I came back and the house had collapsed. I looked
for two days and gave up. Everybody here gave up.'' From his
village of 1,100 people, 30 died and 25 are missing.
	   Doctors in Faisabad said they were worried about the spread of
disease among survivors whose homes were destroyed and who have no
food or drinking water.
	   Panna Erasmus, a Faisabad-based specialist in maternal and child
care, expressed concern that respiratory diseases and diarrhea
could worsen. Tuberculosis is already common in the area where
people live in close quarters and have poor hygiene.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Afghanistan-Quake; CT:i; 
