<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Reporters </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Trial of BBC reporters opens in Yemen 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ The trial of three British Broadcasting
Corp. television journalists charged with filming without
government permission opened Saturday with a judge hearing the
charges against the men, court officials said.
	   The three men appeared in court with their lawyer, al-Sheik
Tareq Abdullah, said the officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
	   BBC producer Robin Barnwell, reporter Ragi Ommar and cameraman
Frank Smith were charged with breaking Yemen's press law by filming
without permission in a remote area.
	   The men are accused of failing to obtain permission from
authorities to travel to areas in western Yemen where kidnappings
have taken place.
	   The law, however, requires only that resident journalists inform
authorities of their movements.
	   The journalists were arrested after returning to the capital
San`a after spending a week with the Bani Dhabyan tribe near Marib,
170 kilometers (105 miles) northeast of San`a.
	   The Bani Dhabyan have carried out numerous kidnappings,
including the seizure of a British teacher, David Mitchell, his
wife Caroline, and their 14-year old son, Ben.
	   Armed tribesmen who rule over large parts of Yemen have
kidnapped foreigners and demanded concessions from the government
in return for their release. The hostages are usually well treated.
 &UR; str-fsa-lm 	   
</TEXT>
