<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians urge swift Israeli acceptance of U.S. proposal 
</HEADLINE>
By IBRAHIM BARZAK
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ A senior Palestinian official said
Saturday ``the clock is ticking very fast'' on Israeli acceptance
of a U.S.-authored troop-pullback plan.
	   Signs have been growing that the government of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is close to accepting the U.S. plan, which would
leave 40 percent of the West Bank under full or partial Palestinian
control and restrict Jewish settlement expansion.
	   U.S. officials expect a decision from Israel within days. The
Palestinians have already accepted the initiative, which has been
widely reported but not formally unveiled.
	   The Palestinian Cabinet, meeting late Friday night in Gaza, was
briefed on two days of talks in London this week by Palestinian
negotiators and U.S. envoy Dennis Ross.
	   Israel army radio had said Ross asked the two Palestinians,
Arafat deputy Mahmoud Abbas and Parliament Speaker Ahmed Qureia, to
accept some changes in the original U.S. proposal.
	   But after the Cabinet meeting, Palestinians said no changes were
in the works now, and that the ball was in the court of Israel and
the Clinton administration.
	   ``We accepted the (U.S.) initiative, trying to be helpful in
getting the peace process back on track,'' said Cabinet minister
Hanan Ashrawi. ``We are not willing in any way to renegotiate the
initiative ... I think the clock is ticking very fast.''
	   Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat urged Israel to swiftly
accept the American initiative. Otherwise, he said, ``we will
continue to see this government's policy of stealing (land) and
wasting time.''
	   Meanwhile, Jewish settler leaders have intensified a campaign to
scuttle any pullback. Far-right lawmakers have said that if
Netanyahu agrees to a withdrawal, they would try to bring him down
at the next possible opportunity by voting against the government
in a no-confidence motion.
	   Israeli media speculated Friday that faced with defections by
the far right, Netanyahu would soon try to form a national unity
government with the opposition Labor Party as a junior partner.
Such a coalition would have to be formed immediately after any
parliament vote on a troop withdrawal.
 &UR; (ib-im-lk)
</TEXT>
