<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Airline Strike, 1st-Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines fires officers of pilots' union 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with union vowing to continue strike new 5th-8th graf
AP Photos Available
<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine Airlines on Saturday fired
the 29 officers of its striking pilots' union and told other
members to return to work by the next day or face dismissal.
	   In a statement, the airlines said it sent a letter to the
officers of the Airline Pilots Association of the Philippines
telling them, ``you have lost your employment status with PAL,
effective today, for having organized, staged, led and knowingly
participated in an illegal act.''
	   The airline also ordered the rest of the 620-member union to
report for work by Sunday or face dismissal. The union went on
strike Friday to protest an early retirement policy.
	   The airline cited two orders by the Department of Labor and
Employment prohibiting the union from ``aggravating the situation''
at the struggling airline.
	   ``With this kind of management, the only recourse is to continue
of the strike,'' union spokesman Florendo Umali said. ``To
capitulate now would be the end of the union.''
	   Umali said the management ``pre-empted and even usurped'' the
authority of the labor secretary in declaring the strike illegal.
	   Secretary Crescenciano Trajano told representatives of the union
and management in a telephone conference earlier in the morning
that the determination of the legality of the strike falls under
his authority and will require a hearing.
	   Umali said a conciliation meeting late Saturday has been
scheduled, but he expressed pessimism over its outcome.
	   The union went on strike to protest a new policy of early
retirement for pilots who have reached 20 years of service or flown
20,000 hours, regardless of age.
	   This policy puts about 200 pilots in danger of being
``retired,'' the union said.
	   Over the past four years, the airline has incurred annual losses
ranging from 451.4 million pesos (dlrs 11.3 million) to 2.5 billion
pesos (dlrs 62.5 million), in part because of large debts, an aging
fleet and Asia's currency crisis.
	   The airline says it faces an ``uncertain future,'' and announced
plans earlier this year to cut expenses by as much as 40 percent by
slashing flights and sharply reducing its work force. The airline
hasn't disclosed an estimate for its manpower reduction, but
employees fear it could be as much as 30 percent.
	   The strike canceled all Philippine Airlines international
flights except one to Hong Kong Saturday afternoon. The airline
operated only 13 domestic flights out of Manila, stranding hundreds
of passengers.
	   More than 500 passengers were stranded at the Kai Tak airport in
Hong Kong early Saturday as two fully-booked flights for Manila and
central Cebu City were canceled.
	   The airline said it would refund tickets paid in cash and send
international passengers to other airlines.
</TEXT>
