<SLUG> BC-Ghana-Parliament Fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ghana's parliament chamber damaged by fire 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ACCRA, Ghana (AP) _ The main hall of Ghana's parliament building
was damaged by a fire that may have been triggered by a faulty
wiring in the press gallery, the parliamentary security force said
Saturday.
	   The fire late Thursday night destroyed furniture, wooden
paneling and parts of the building's electrical system, said
security guard Nicholas Opoku, who was on duty at the time of the
fire.
	   ``Two of us quickly reached for fire extinguishers while we
asked our third colleague to call the fire service,'' Opoku said.
	   Much of the building's main chamber is covered with a thick
layer of black soot, he said.
	   News of the fire was only made public Saturday, as members of
parliament convened a special meeting to discuss alternative
locations to conduct business.
	   A panel of government ministers and members of parliament are
expected to decide by Monday whether recess the current legislative
session or move to an new location on a temporary basis.
	   A full assessment of the damage is expected by mid-week, said
Parliamentary Affairs Minister J.H. Owusu Acheampong.
