<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Nuclear, 1st Ld,0317 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistani prime minister seeking help to combat sanctions 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Sharif call on Indian premier to hold talks
AP Photos ISL101
By ARTHUR MAX
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pinched by sanctions for his nuclear
ambitions, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was heading Saturday to the
Gulf region to ensure oil keeps flowing to Pakistan.
	   Officials said Sharif's mission to Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates was aimed at securing credit needed to maintain oil
imports. Pakistan bought dlrs 1.2 billion of petroleum products
over nine months up to March, the latest figure available.
	   Speaking to a joint session of Parliament before his scheduled
departure, Sharif renewed a proposal to his Indian counterpart,
Atal Bihari Vajpayee, to abandon the arms race and hold talks on
their problems.
	   ``Pakistan has already offered to India a meaningful and
purposeful dialogue, and we still offer the same,'' he said.
	   The two men are due to attend a regional summit in Sri Lanka
next month, where they will have their first chance to meet
privately since the each authorized nuclear tests.
	   Sharif called on Vajpayee to discuss the dispute over Kashmir,
which both countries claim and which is divided between them.
Kashmir was the flash point of two Indo-Pakistan wars, and the deep
divisions have sabotaged all previous attempts to negotiate an end
to 50 years of hostility.
	   Sharif said Kashmir will continue receiving moral and political
support from Pakistan until Kashmiris are given self-determination.
India accuses Pakistan of providing military aid to separatist
guerrillas, and fighting a proxy war of terrorism.
	   Sharif justified his decision to follow India's lead in testing
nuclear devices, saying Pakistan had taken its future in its own
hands.
