</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Imelda Marcos </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ramos orders withdrawal of recommendation to overturn Marcos conviction 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President Fidel Ramos on Saturday
ordered the justice secretary to withdraw a recommendation by the
government's chief prosecutor to overturn the graft conviction of
the widow of the late dictator Ferdinand Marcos.
	   Solicitor General Romeo de la Cruz, commenting on an appeal by
Imelda Marcos of her 1993 graft conviction, had said there was no
strong evidence against her.
	   Ramos ordered Justice Secretary Silvestre Bello to withdraw de
la Cruz's motion and restudy it.
	   Mrs. Marcos was sentenced to up to 12 years in prison and is
appealing the verdict with the Supreme Court.
	   Ramos on Friday accepted de la Cruz's resignation and made it
effective Monday rather than on June 30 as the prosecutor had
requested.
	   The President said de la Cruz's actions ``indicate that the
political will of this administration is weakening, that's why I
fired him.''
	   President-elect Joseph Estrada has indicated he favors a pardon
or dismissal of the case against Mrs. Marcos, and some analysts
speculate that de la Cruz's abrupt recommendation to overturn the
conviction was an attempt to stay on as solicitor general in
Estrada's administration.
	   The case is the only one in which Mrs. Marcos, 68, has been
convicted, although she faces numerous other criminal and civil
cases related to the 20-year rule of her husband.
	   She and her late husband have been accused of stealing billions
of dollars during his presidency. They were ousted in a 1986
``people power'' revolt and Marcos died three years later in exile
in Hawaii.
	   Mrs. Marcos was convicted of having granted leases on
government-owned land at improperly low rates to the Philippine
General Hospital Foundation, which she headed. The land was then
sublet to another company at much higher rates.
	   Mrs. Marcos insists she did not personally benefit from the
deal, and prosecutors did not challenge this, but they maintained
that the foundation should have been charged more.
	   A five-judge Supreme Court panel upheld her conviction in
January, but ruled that she could appeal one more time to the
entire court before going to prison. It sentenced her to nine to 12
years in prison and ordered her to pay 189 million pesos (dlrs 4.9
million) in damages to the government.
</TEXT>
