<HEADLINE>
Paramilitary to guard Bangladesh power stations during World Cup edits. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS lede to remove second reference to guard. Minor
<TEXT>
	   DHAKA , Bangladesh (AP) _ Paramilitary forces will guard
Bangladeshi power stations during the World Cup to prevent attacks
by angry soccer fans in the event of power outages, a senior
official said Saturday.
	   Soldiers and police will take positions around all major power
stations 12 hours before the June 10 inauguration of the World Cup
in France, Nuruddin Mohammad Kamal, chairman of the state-owned
Power Development Board told reporters.
	   The nation's major cities, including Dhaka, Chittagong, Khulna
and Rajshahi, face regular power outages and citizens have often
staged violent demonstrations at power stations.
	   Bangladesh, which needs over 2,100 megawatts of electricity each
year, generates only 1,700 megawatts.
	   Bangladesh did not qualify for the World Cup.
