<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-England-Drinks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Third England player in drinking controversy 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ On the eve of the World Cup, a third England
player was caught up Saturday in reports he was out drinking late,
defying orders from England coach Glenn Hoddle.
	   News reports said Darren Anderton was involved in a nightclub
brawl in the southern town of Bournemouth Wednesday. Anderton
denied he took part in the fight, although a friend was reported to
have been punched in the face.
	   The reports Saturday came just a day after Hoddle held a
closed-door meeting with striker Teddy Sheringham.
	   Sheringham's photo was splashed across papers Friday, showing
him with a cigarette in the mouth and his arm draped a young woman
at a bar on Portugal's Algarve coast. Accompanying stories said he
had been partying and drinking until dawn.
	   The incidents put Hoddle on a spot.
	   After breaking training camp in Spain on Sunday, Hoddle reminded
players they were ``on England duty'' and ask them to return home
for a quiet few days before training resumed.
	   Hoddle dismissed midfielder Paul Gascoigne from the team Sunday,
arguing he lacked fitness. Hoddle was also reportedly angered by
Gascoigne's late-night partying and drinking.
	   Hoddle was to meet again Saturday with Sheringham with some
newspapers calling for him to be dropped from the England side.
	   On Friday, Sir Bobby Charlton _ a member of England's 1966 World
Cup-winning side _ lambasted Sheringham for his lack of discipline
and suggested he had made England the laughingstock of world
soccer.
	   ``You are the focus of the whole country and if the players
don't have the common sense to behave themselves and act in a
reasonable manner it is absolutely nonsensical to think we have a
chance of winning it,'' Charlton said.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-England-Drinks; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
