<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan,0289 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Japanese team adjusting to warmer French camp 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos
By YURI KAGEYAMA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ The Japanese team is struggling to
adjust to the more humid, warmer weather at the southeastern resort
that will serve as its World Cup base training camp.
	   Coach Takeshi Okada moved up Saturday's afternoon practice to
the middle of the afternoon to allow his players to get used to the
heat.
	   ``I'm not used to this yet,'' said midfielder Hiroshi Nanami,
25, sweating after the team's light jog Saturday morning. ``I'll be
OK in about three days. It's getting there.''
	   Usually at about 25 degrees Centigrade (77 degrees Fahrenheit),
the weather in Aix-les-Bains is similar to Tokyo's at this time of
the year.
	   But it was exceptionally warm Friday, the day the team arrived,
hitting about 30 degrees C (86 F).
	   The players have been spoiled by the cooler winds at their
previous camp in Nyon, Switzerland, where they trained for about a
week.
	   ``I was a little surprised because it was so terribly hot
yesterday,'' said striker Masashi Nakayama. ``But I think I'll
adjust little by little.''
	   Careful to allot plenty of time for stretching after his run, he
was the last player to come off the field.
	   ``I get yelled at these days if I don't stretch. I've reached
that age, I guess,'' said Nakayama, who at 30 is one of the oldest
players on the team.
	   Okada said he will not go easy on the players.
	   ``We have to think about what lies ahead,'' he said. ``It's best
for the players to keep moving.''
	   The opener for Japan's World Cup debut is against Argentina June
14.
	   (yk-sl)
</TEXT>
