<SLUG> BC-Albania-King Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Trial opens against would-be king Leka in absentia 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ A trial in absentia opened here Friday
against would-be king Leka, who is charged with organizing an armed
rebellion against the election commission following the June 1997
ballot, court officials said Saturday.
	   Leka Zogu returned to Albania in 1997 from Johannesburg, South
Africa, where he is a businessmen. He left on a private jet after
refusing a state prosecutor's summons to discuss a July 3 shootout
that left one man dead.
	   The clash occurred when monarchists staged a demonstration
against what they alleged were rigged results in the defeat of a
referendum asking Albanians if they wanted to restore the monarchy.
Violence erupted after Leka joined the protest. He and some of his
companions were armed.
	   Leka, whose army officer father became Albania's king in 1928,
appeared at the rally dressed in camouflage and armed with a pistol
and an Uzi submachine gun. He then led 300 supporters to the
election commission's headquarters.
	   However, they failed to enter the election commission building.
Leka and his supporters fled after a wild shootout in which one man
was killed.
	   The court has a list of 61 people scheduled to testify, mainly
policemen involved in the shootout.
	   Leka was an infant when his father fled Albania's Italian
invaders in 1939.
	   (ac/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
