<SLUG> BC-Britain-Eritrea, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign Office advises Britons to leave Eritrea Eritrea 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES in grafs 8-9 with quotes from Britons returning from
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Britain said Saturday it is having difficulty
getting a plane into Eritrea to evacuate Britons and other
foreigners who want to escape fighting in the East African nation.
	   ``Obviously this is a war zone and it proved just not possible
for safety reasons to get that plane in,'' Foreign Office Minister
Tony Lloyd told BBC Radio 4. ``We are actually seeking the
opportunity to get a plane in as quickly as we can.''
	   The Foreign Office on Friday advised about 120 British citizens
in Eritrea to leave as soon as possible because of a worsening
border conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia.
	   ``We are working closely with our European Union partners and
the Canadians and Americans to make the necessary provision for
flights out of the capital Asmara as soon as possible,'' a Foreign
Office spokesman said, speaking with customary anonymity.
	   Forty eight Britons left Eritrea Friday night on a U.S. aircraft
which landed in Frankfurt early Saturday. The Foreign Office said
the Britons, mainly working for the non-governmental organization
Voluntary Service Overseas, then flew to London.
	   Britain is still trying to evacuate between 60 and 80 people
from Britain, the European Union and Commonwealth nations, Lloyd
said.
	   For the second day on Saturday, Ethiopian warplanes bombed
airports outside the Eritrean capital. The civilian airport was
struck by several bombs, setting off bursts of fire as foreigners
were trying to leave the country. The military airport was also
bombed.
	   ``We had seen tanks driving through the streets and we saw the
MiGs bombing the airport which was frightening,'' said Jenny
Tinker, 26, from Reading, who has been teaching in Eritrea for two
years and was among the 48 Britons who returned to London on
Saturday.
	   ``The Eritreans are used to it,'' said Debbie McGrath, who also
worked in the education field in Eritrea. ``They have had 30 years
of fighting. People stood out and watched for the MiGs as they went
over and clapped when one was shot down.''
