w2215 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia 6thLd-Writethru   06-06 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopian jets bomb airport, outskirts of Eritrean capital outskirts of capital as well; says one Ethiopian jet shot down; difficulty getting planes in to evacuate foreigners; Ethiopia says victims in Mekele bombing civilians; minor editing; CLARIFIES that both countries in the Horn of Africa, and are at odds over at least six parts of their common border; no pickup 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Eritrean government saying Ethiopian jets bombed
AP Photos AMS101-108
By JULIA STEWART
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Ethiopian warplanes bombed a combined
military-civilian airport and the outskirts of the Eritrean capital
Saturday, escalating a border dispute between the two nations in
the Horn of Africa.
	   Several bombs struck the civilian part of the airport, setting
off fires as foreigners were trying to leave the country.
Anti-aircraft guns fired on two Ethiopian warplanes, but neither
appeared to have been hit.
	   Reports said the fuel depot on the military side of the airport
was also hit.
	   The Eritrean Foreign Ministry said the MiG fighter-bombers also
struck the southern outskirts of Asmara and that Eritrean gunners
shot one of them down.
	   The ministry said no information was yet available on
casualties.
	   It was the second day in a row that the airport was hit by
Ethiopian bombs. Initial reports said two Ethiopian Migs had been
shot down Friday, but Eritrea later said only one had been hit.
	   A source familiar with the Eritrean Air Force, who asked not to
be further identified, said it was clear Ethiopia was trying to
wipe out Eritrea's small air force.
	   Because of the airport attacks, Britain and Germany were having
difficulty Saturday trying to send aircraft to evacuate their
nationals from Eritrea.
	   Asmara residents again poured into the streets Saturday to
celebrate the downing of the second aircraft.
	   Aaron Greenberg, 22, an American Peace Corps volunteer among 129
Americans and 65 other evacuees who arrived early Saturday in
Frankfurt, Germany on a charter flight from Asmara said residents
drove by the Ethiopian Embassy Friday honking their car horns and
cheering.
	   The escalating conflict prompted the U.S. State Department to
order nonessential staff and dependents out of Eritrea and urge
other Americans to leave.
	   Ethiopia said Friday's attack was in retaliation an Eritrean
attack on Mekele, 200 kilometers (125 miles) north of Addis. At
least 44 Ethiopians civilians were killed and 135 wounded in the
Mekele attack, according to Radio Fana of the Ethiopian People's
Revolutionary Democratic Front.
	   But reports from Mekele said the Eritreans did not strike until
6 p.m. (1500gmt) Friday, almost four hours after the attack on
Asmara airport.
	   Eritrea and Ethiopia, among the world's poorest nations, are at
odds over at least six areas along their common border which was
traced by Italy after it conquered Eritrea in 1885.
	   Both armies have been trading artillery and mortar fire in the
contested areas with weapons supplied to Ethiopia by the Soviet
Union during the Cold War.
	   The first airstrikes came a day after Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi agreed to a U.S. and Rwandan proposal to end the
border conflict peacefully.
	   But Meles warned that his country's patience was wearing thin
because of Eritrea's refusal to withdraw from territory Ethiopia
claims it occupied a month ago.
	   The Eritrean government issued a statement Friday saying there
were ``still serious issues of detail and implementation to be
worked out'' with the proposal.
	   The U.S. State Department urged Ethiopia and Eritrea to cease
all hostilities while outside envoys seek a peaceful resolution of
the dispute.
	   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs Susan Rice
was in the West African Nation of Burkina Faso Saturday where
foreign ministers from the Organization of African Unity were
meeting in Ouagadougu prior to Monday's summit.
	   The Ethio-Eritrean conflict was expected to feature high on the
agenda.
	   At the United Nations in New York, the Security Council on
Friday urged an immediate cease-fire and Secretary-General Kofi
Annan appealed to both sides to ``give diplomacy a chance.''
	   ``The Security Council deplored this escalation and called for
an immediate cease-fire'' and ``urged Eritrea and Ethiopia to
affirm their commitment to resolve the dispute peacefully,''
council President Antonio Monteiro of Portugal said.
	   One of the recommendations of the U.S.-Rwandan proposal was that
Eritrea withdraw to positions held before May 6.
	   Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. Eritrean
rebels were instrumental in helping the EPRDF overthrow a 17-year
military regime in July 1991.
	   (pvs/sl)	   
</TEXT>
