</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Habibie </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New leader says probe into Suharto regime corruption must be lawful 
</HEADLINE>
Ap Photos JAK106-7
Eds: INCORPORATES BC-Indonesia-Former President
By GEOFF SPENCER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Fearing that demands for swift action
against ex-President Suharto could degenerate into a lynching,
Indonesia's new leader insisted Saturday that an inquiry into
corruption under the old autocrat proceed lawfully.
	   In a wide-ranging two and half hour presentation to Indonesian
media executives, Habibie also outlined an ``accelerated
evolution'' reform program to end the nation's political turmoil
and worsening economic crisis.
	   In his most specific reference yet to a timetable for change,
Habibie said electoral reforms would be in place by August this
year and parliamentary and presidential elections held before
December 1999.
	   A new Cabinet would then be formed at the start of 2000. He did
not specify if he would run for office, but later described himself
as ``an integrated part of the Indonesian people.''
	   He said all future presidents should be limited to only two
five-year terms in office.
	   Suharto ruled for 32 years. He resigned on May 21 in favor of
Habibie following a wave of riots and protests that were triggered
by the worst economic crisis in 30 years. At least 1,188 died in
the violence that scarred Jakarta and other cities.
	   Since then, many have called for Suharto to face trial for
corruption and abuse of power. Some want the state to seize
billions of dollars amassed by his super-rich family and use it to
help the nation overcome its acute economic problems.
	   At the height of student protests last month, demonstrators even
called for Suharto to be hanged for his alleged misdeeds.
	   They also called for Habibie to step down.
	   ``I ask the people of the Republic of Indonesia to concentrate
on the future. It doesn't mean that corruption and nepotism and so
on will be forgotten. I ask them to leave it to the legal
process,'' Habibie said.
	   ``I am not going to introduce, just like 200 years ago in Texas,
where people would take their own justice and hang somebody, and
afterwards, after he is dead, find out that he is innocent.''
	   Habibie said a proper and lawful corruption inquiry was ``in the
pipeline.''
	   He called on Indonesians to wait for its outcome, saying
patience was part of the Indonesian culture.
	   The powerful military and some leading opposition figures have
also called for restraint.
	   Indonesia's National Human Rights Commission said it would stand
up for Suharto's rights as a citizen.
	   Habibie also called on Indonesia's indigenous, mainly Muslim,
majority not to persecute the nation's ethnic Chinese minority.
	   During last month's rioting many Indonesian-born Chinese were
targeted by mobs. Although they make up only a tiny fraction of
Indonesia's 202 million people, they dominate trade and commerce.
Thousands of Chinese homes and shops were looted and burned. Tens
of thousand of Chinese have left the country.
	   Only two weeks in the job, Habibie has instituted several major
reforms, including the holding of new elections next year.
	   On Friday the government announced it had lifted draconian
controls used by Suharto to suppress press freedoms.
	   He has released four political prisoners and has promised to
free more soon.
	   A range of economic reforms have also been put into place.
	   A team from the International Monetary Fund is due to arrive in
Jakarta next week to asses how to restart a dlrs 43 billion
economic rescue package that was derailed by political events.
	   Habibie said that Indonesia's would cooperate with the IMF.
	   ``We do not have a problems,'' he said in reference to relations
to the Washington-based Fund.
	   Last week hundreds of students staged noisy demonstrations
outside of the U.S. Embassy in Jakarta and the U.S. Consulate in
the second city of Surabaya, claiming that Washington was
interfering in Indonesia's internal affairs.
	   Some accused the Clinton administration of trying to delay loan
payments to Indonesia from the IMF and of funding groups to
undermine the government.
	   Habibie flatly rejected the claim, saying that the United States
and other industrialized powers belonging to the G-7 group of
nations wanted to help Indonesia.
</TEXT>
