<HEADLINE>
Iranian spiritual leader sick, but illness is minor 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iranian spiritual leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei is suffering from a minor illness and there is no cause
for concern, his office said in a statement Saturday.
	   At a ceremony Thursday marking the anniversary of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's death, Khamenei, 58, gave a 15-minute speech in
an unusually quiet voice and said his doctors would not allow him
to talk longer.
	   In previous speeches on the anniversary of the death of
Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary patriarch, Khamenei, who succeeded
him, has spoken emotionally for nearly an hour.
	   ``We would like to clarify that (the illness) is only minor.
According to physicians in charge . . . there is no cause for
concern,'' said the statement carried by state-run Tehran radio.
	   Journalists who cover Khamenei on a daily basis said he had a
bad cold but the ailment was not serious.
