<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Mexico-Sinking Cathedral,0779 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Engineers beginning to straighten Mexico City's sagging cathedral 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo MO101, Graphic CATHEDRAL MEND
By ISAAC A. LEVI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ After centuries of sinking into moist clay,
Mexico City's cathedral is finally being set straight by experts
who are trying to save the largest church in the Americas.
	   The imposing stone building with twin bell towers overlooking
the vast Zocalo square will never stop sinking, but the experts
hope that with its tilt lessened the cathedral won't crumble.
	   In a project that began a decade ago, workers have been
painstakingly removing soil from under the structure's northern
side, which was once more than 8 feet (2-1/2 meters) higher than
the other end. Bit by bit, the high side has come down a little
over three feet (one meter) _ leaving the church not completely
level, but good enough to prevent collapse.
	   ``We are achieving our goal so the structure can now sink more
evenly,'' said Sergio Zaldivar, an architect who heads a government
restoration team of 230 geophysicists, engineers and other experts.
	   ``After that we can start mending the cracks in the walls, the
floor, and repairing other parts of the structure,'' Zaldivar added
in an interview. ``Even so, the foundations will have to be watched
year after year and maybe further corrected.''
	   The Metropolitan Cathedral, 363 feet (111 meters) by 215 feet
(66 meters) and weighing 127,000 metric tons, was in trouble from
the day construction began in 1573 atop an Aztec ceremonial center
that included at least one pyramid.
	   Roman Catholic priests accompanying the Spanish conquerors
regularly built churches atop Indian ceremonial sites in an effort
to convert the Aztecs and end practices like sacrificing humans
alive by cutting their hearts out.
	   The Aztecs themselves had run into trouble building the
ceremonial center, which also kept sinking. They had to tamp down
the extremely soft soil of what _ like the rest of the Valley of
Mexico _ were lake beds and marshes drained over the centuries.
	   In the 240 years that the cathedral was under construction
before its consecration in 1813, architects made continual
adjustments to compensate for sinking. Work stopped when a huge
flood in 1629 that lasted nearly eight years forced half of Mexico
City's population to move to neighboring Puebla.
	   The cathedral was erected on a masonry platform about four feet
(a meter) thick that rests on a mass of short wooden pilings.
	   In addition to its historical importance, the building is unique
because of its various architectural styles _ a harmonious blend of
Gothic, baroque and others. It also houses priceless art treasures.
	   Not only the cathedral is sinking. Most of Mexico City, which
sprawls over a bowl-shaped valley 7,250 feet (2,200 meters) above
sea level, is slowly subsiding because 80 percent of its water
comes from wells that tap aquifers under the city. Although rains
are heavy during the rainy season, it isn't enough to replenish the
aquifers, so the ground is compacting.
	   The city has sunk about 24 feet (seven meters) this century,
and, like the cathedral, none of it evenly. The sinking worsened
considerably after 1934, when a population boom began that has
boosted the city from 435,000 people in 1910 to an estimated 18
million today.
	   The cathedral was already in crisis when an 8.1-magnitude
earthquake devastated Mexico City on Sept. 19, 1985, killing 10,000
people. The 6-foot-thick (two-meter-thick), mostly sandstone walls
withstood the shocks _ as they had countless big quakes before _
but sustained terrific stress.
	   More walls cracked and a fissure on the floor ran almost all the
way down the middle of the church. Interior columns tilted, arches
flattened and the floor humped.
	   Mexico's Education Department soon decided to spend dlrs 2
million to dlrs 3 million annually to save the cathedral.
	   After much study, Zaldivar and his team came up with a plan for
lowering the cathedral's back side.
	   Under the building, crews drilled 32 concrete-lined holes about
10 feet (3 meters) in diameter to depths of 60 (18) to 75 feet
(23). Workers then drilled unlined, three-inch-wide
(eight-centimeter-wide) holes out horizontally to draw out slowly
and carefully tons of muddy clay.
	   ``It took almost a decade but we did it,'' Zaldivar said.
	   ``Now we have to repair the rest inside,'' he added, pointing to
green metal scaffolding that covers the cathedral's inner walls.
	   They also plan to clean the outer walls, which are covered with
grime from decades of smog and pigeon droppings. 	   
</TEXT>
