<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0624 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Ethiopian warplanes bombed a combined
military-civilian airport and the outskirts of the Eritrean capital
Saturday, escalating a border dispute between the Horn of Africa
nations. Several bombs struck the airport, setting off fires as
foreigners were trying to leave the country. Anti-aircraft guns
fired on two Ethiopian warplanes, but neither appeared to have been
hit. The Eritrean Foreign Ministry said the MiG fighter-bombers
also struck the southern outskirts of Asmara and that Eritrean
gunners shot one of them down. The ministry said no information was
yet available on casualties. (ERITREA-ETHIOPIA)
	   ESCHEDE, Germany (AP) _ Rescuers wound up their search Saturday
for victims in postwar Germany's deadliest train accident,
delicately digging the last of the bodies from a sandbank by hand.
A commission sealed part of the accident site for its investigation
of the cause of Wednesday's high-speed train derailment that killed
102 people in northern Germany. Investigators have focused on a
wheel failure as the likely cause. Four additional bodies were
found early Saturday, bringing the total recovered to 97. Five
people have died in hospital. (GERMANY-TRAIN DERAILS)
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Fearing that demands for swift action
against ex-President Suharto could degenerate into a lynching,
Indonesia's new leader insisted Saturday that an inquiry into
corruption under the old autocrat proceed lawfully. In a
presentation to Indonesian media executives, Habibie also outlined
an ``accelerated evolution'' reform program to end the nation's
political turmoil and worsening economic crisis. In his most
specific reference yet to a timetable for change, Habibie said
electoral reforms would be in place by August and parliamentary and
presidential elections held before December 1999.
(INDONESIA-HABIBIE)
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pinched by sanctions for his nuclear
ambitions, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was heading to the Gulf
region Saturday to ensure that oil keeps flowing to Pakistan.
Officials said Sharif's mission to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates was to secure credit needed to maintain oil imports.
Pakistan bought dlrs 1.2 billion of petroleum products over nine
months up to March, the latest figure available. Speaking to a
joint session of Parliament before his scheduled departure, Sharif
renewed a proposal to his Indian counterpart, Atal Bihari Vajpayee,
to abandon the arms race and hold talks. The two are to attend a
regional summit in Sri Lanka next month, where they will have their
first chance to meet privately since each authorized nuclear tests.
(PAKISTAN-NUCLEAR)
	   LONDON (AP) _ Several of Britain's national newspapers reacted
Saturday with anger at critical remarks made about Princess Diana's
mother by Mohamed Al Fayed, whose son Dodi died in the Paris car
crash that killed the princess. Al Fayed said Friday that Frances
Shand Kydd was ``a bad mother,'' accused her of ``snobbery'' and
said Diana ``did not give a damn about her.'' The Sun, Britain's
biggest-selling daily tabloid, called Al Fayed a ``heartless
creep.'' ``Fayed Savages Diana's Mother,'' said the headline in the
Daily Mail, Britain's top selling mid-market tabloid. Al Fayed
spoke after he and Mrs. Shand Kydd attended a meeting in Paris
called by French Judge Herve Stephan, who is investigating the
deadly crash. Al Fayed said he was offended that Shand Kydd refused
to speak to him. (BRITAIN-DIANA-EL FAYED)
</TEXT>
