<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-IMF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia's president says he's committed to IMF reform 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Indonesia-Habibie
With AP Photos JAK106-7
By GEOFF SPENCER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's new President B.J. Habibie
said Saturday he remained committed to carrying out tough reforms
under a dlrs 43 billion International Monetary Fund rescue package.
	   Habibie's comments came two days before an IMF team was due to
arrive in Jakarta to help put the battered economy back on track.
	   The president, who has been in office for only 14 days,
identified currency stability and the control of soaring inflation
as key immediate goals for Indonesia.
	   ``We have a program with the IMF and we are going to follow that
program and make the best of that,'' Habibie said in reply to a
question from The Associated Press at gathering of media executives
at Jakarta's State Palace.
	   ``We do not have a problem,'' he said of relations between his
new government and the Washington-based Fund.
	   Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous nation, has been the
hardest hit by Asia's financial meltdown.
	   Habibie became head of state on May 21 when former President
Suharto quit after a wave of protests and riots swept several
cities, including the capital.
	   Several attempts to implement the IMF package stalled under
Suharto who was accused of tryiong to protect business empires
built by his family and friends under his patronnage.
	   The economic crisis has seen massive rises in inflation and mass
unemployment.
	   Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, has lost about 80 percent of
its value against the U.S. dollar, bringing most trade and
production to a standstill, and making many foreign debt-ladened
companies and banks insolvent.
	   Habibie said Indonesia urgently needs to stabilize the rupiah
and to rein in the runaway inflation rate, which some predict could
top 85 percent, or even 100 percent, by the end of the year.
	   He said once these goals were in place the government could
address the question of the rupiah's low value against the U.S.
dollar.
	   Before the economic crisis hit last July, one dollar was worth
2,400 rupiahs. Last week it was trading at around 11,500 rupiahs,
with no immediate sign of recovery.
	   ``When the rupiah is stabilized and inflation is controlled, we
can adjust the exchange rate,'' Habibie said.
	   Habibie also defended a decision to save the country's largest
privately-owned bank after a prolonged run by nervous depositors.
	   Bank Central Asia, or BCA, is controlled by one of Suharto's
close business associates, Liem Sioe Liong, Indonesia's richest
man, and part-owned by two of Suharto's children.
	   Last week the bank was placed under the supervision of the
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency, which is looking after dozens
of other troubled financial institutions.
	   Habibie said this was not taken to help the bank's owners, but
to safeguard the savings of millions of Indonesians.
	   He said BCA was important to Indonesia's economy and its
possible demise could have caused a ``snowball effect'' on the rest
of the troubled banking sector.
	   Habibie, a German-educated engineer, also said an expert from
the Bundesbank, Germany's central bank, would be stationed in
Jakarta for one year to advise on how to reform Indonesia's central
bank in line with the IMF program.
</TEXT>
