u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Somalia-Kidnapping     06-06 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Somalia-Kidnapping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Frenchmen abducted off northern Somalia coast 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOGADISHU, Somalia (AP) _ Somali gunmen are holding two French
nationals for ransom after seizing them and their sailboat in the
Gulf of Aden off northern Somalia, one of the kidnappers said
Saturday.
	   Gunmen loyal to the Somali Salvation Democratic Front said the
men were seizied when their sailboat came too close to fishing
waters controlled by the group.
	   In a separate incident Friday, gunmen abducted a Somali employed
by the European Union.
	   Abdalla Musa Abdi, a former employee of the U.S. embassy, was
abducted following prayers at a mosque in northern Mogadishu, an
area controlled by faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid. The reason
for the kidnapping and Abdi's whereabouts were not clear.
	   The French hostages, who were not identified, are being held in
the northeastern Somali coastal town of Bossaso. Sources said they
were being held in a small room in a house and were being
adequately fed and treated.
	   ``There will be no other way out but a huge ransom to be paid in
exchange for the release of the French men,'' said Saeed Baniadam,
a leader of the abductors. He did not elaborate.
	   The kidnappers, who spoke with reporters in Mogadishu by high
frequency radio, said the hostages told them their boat was headed
from the French port of Marseille to the island of Madagascar off
the southeastern African coast.
	   The abductors said the French vessel had been three kilometers
(1.8 miles) from the SSDF-controlled fishing waters when gunmen in
a speedboat forced them to shore.
	   Foreign seafaring vessels are a profitable source of revenue for
the gunmen from the SSDF, one of a more than a dozen factions
controlling parts of Somalia.
	   Somalia has been without a central government since faction
leaders combined to oust President Siad Barre in 1991, then turned
on each other, turning the counry into armed fiefdoms.
	   Kidnappings are a danger for foreigners in and around Somalia.
In November, further west along Somalia's northern coast, five
international aid workers were seized on the way to a barbeque on a
yacht. They were later released unharmed.
	   In April, eight Red Cross workers and two pilots were taken
hostage in Mogadishu. They were later released after extended
negotiations.
	    &UR; (aan/dmc)	   
</TEXT>
