<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Military Thefts,0414 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Third arrest in South Africa military weapons heist 
</HEADLINE>
By PAT REBER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ A third suspect was arrested
Saturday in connection with the theft of South African military
ammunition, capping a week of saber-rattling by white and black
politicians.
	   The 42-year-old man arrested in Bloemfontein is not a member of
the military, said spokeswoman Superintendent Johlene van der
Merwe.
	   Earlier in the week, police arrested a sergeant connected to an
army base in Bloemfontein, 400 kilometers (240 miles) southwest of
Johannesburg, and his brother, a farm foreman.
	   The three are suspected of involvement in Monday's theft of
200,000 rounds of ammunition from a truck carrying it off the base.
The bodies of the two truck drivers were found in a river.
	   The suspects were also believed to have been involved in last
month's theft of 117 weapons, including mortars and rocket
launchers, from the same base. Most of the weapons have been
recovered, and six suspects were arrested in May.
	   Suspicion has focused on right-wing elements in the military
seeking weapons for a campaign to destabilize the country in the
run-up to next year's national election, just the second all-race
polling since South Africa dismantled its apartheid regime in 1994.
	   Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils told Parliament last week
that some of the arrested men had right-wing connections.
	   On Friday, a group calling itself the Boere Weerstandsbewging,
or Boer's Resistance Movement, claimed the theft was done by Boers
_ a political reference to descendants of original Dutch settlers
who want a separate homeland.
	   In a statement faxed to Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, the BWB
warned that fears he expressed earlier this week about whites
taking up arms ``should be taken seriously.''
	   Mbeki, the likely successor to President Nelson Mandela in next
year's elections, said recently that privileged whites have not
done enough to help the poor blacks that are the country's
majority.
	   On Wednesday in Parliament, a conservative Freedom Front Party
member said that Mbeki and the ruling African National Congress
were determined to disempower all Afrikaners _ white descendants of
settlers who speak Afrikaans.
	   ``If this ANC government wants confrontation, so be it. We are
ready to take up that challenge,'' said Corne Mulder.
</TEXT>
