<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More shelling, more dead in Kosovo 
</HEADLINE>
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Dozens of houses were aflame and
Serb gunners kept shelling villages in Kosovo, where another four
people were killed in fighting, ethnic Albanian and Serb sources
said Saturday.
	   The Kosovo Information Center close to the Albanian leadership
said fighting continued Saturday in the Decani area, some 70
kilometers (45 miles) west of provincial capital Pristina. The
villages of Shaptej, Gramocel and Babaloc were targeted by the
Serbs' heavy artillery.
	   One three-year old child, identified as Leutrim Aga, was killed
sleeping in his bed in Gramocel and three more ethnic Albanians
were wounded in that village. Another ethnic Albanian was found
dead in nearby Babaloc.
	   Dozens of houses in the region were burning, the Kosovo
Information Center said. It also claimed that Serbian forces were a
shelling border strip west of Djakovica, 75 kilometers (47 miles)
southwest of Pristina and that police reinforcements were sent in.
	   Serbian sources said two men were killed in a border clash
between Serb-led Yugoslav army troops and an armed group attempting
to illegally enter the province from Macedonia Saturday. They were
the first dead at the Macedonian border.
	   The clash occurred in the early morning near Brod outpost, 85
kilometers (53.1 miles) south of Pristina, reported the
pro-government Media Center in Pristina. The identity of the two
killed was not reported.
	   A Serb policemen was also reported to have died in the Belgrade
military hospital of injuries sustained in previous fighting in
Kosovo.
	   Speaking to reporters on Brioni island, Croatia, Ilir Meta,
Albania's state secretary for European integration, said the
situation in Kosovo was getting ``more and more explosive'' each
day.
	   He repeated his government's calls for outside assistance to
cope with the continuing influx of Kosovo refugees.
	   ``If this situation is not stopped immediately, in the coming
hours and days, it can bring an unforeseen catastrophe not only for
the Albanians or Serbs but for the whole region,'' Meta said.
	   ``We consider that enhancement of NATO presence in the region
can help the strengthening of the security,'' he added.
	   Meanwhile, German foreign ministry official Wolfgang Ischinger,
touring the Balkans, met with ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova
in the provincial capital Pristina.
	   Ischinger was later scheduled to travel to Belgrade for meetings
with top government officials. On Friday, he visited neighboring
Macedonia where he called the expulsions of Kosovo Albanians
``unprecedented,'' saying the international community ``cannot shut
its eyes before that problem.''
	   He added international pressure on Belgrade government must
continue.
	   On Friday, the United Nations, in an unusually strong statement,
accused Serbian forces of atrocities in Kosovo where more than 250
people have died since March 1, in escalating clashes between
government forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of
the Albanian independence movement.
	   In the Decani offensive this week, ethnic Albanian sources
earlier reported 50 dead, 200 missing and several villages
destroyed. There were also unconfirmed reports of a mass grave
containing 300 bodies.
	   A statement by Serbian police issued late Friday, contradicted
by the subsequent Albanian account, indicated the latest offensive
had ended, with the ``terrorist gangs'' who tried to block the key
north-south Pec-Decani-Djakovica road being ``destroyed.''
	   Most of western Kosovo remained sealed-off Saturday, and it was
impossible to verify the conflicting reports.
	   More than 10,000 Kososo Albanian refugees fled to northern
Albania this week, the largest exodus since ethnic tensions erupted
into large-scale violence in March. Thousands more are in
neighboring Montenegro, which with Serbia, forms present-day
Yugoslavia.
	   (ih/str/kk/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
