<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Neutrino, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Neutrino researchers say their project threatened by budget cuts 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS lede to add description of neutrino; CORRECTS typo in
graf 3
By TODD ZAUN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The team of physicists who stunned the scientific
world with evidence Friday that the tiny particles known as
neutrinos have mass, now says government budget cuts threaten to
halt their experiments.
	   The group of a 120 scientists from around the world, known as
the Super-Kamiokande Collaboration, has appealed to the Japanese
government to reconsider planned 15 percent cuts in its
contribution to the project both this year and next.
	   The budget cuts may force the scientists to stop the experiment
for 2 months this year and four months next year, the group said in
a statement received Saturday by The Associated Press.
	   The physicists warned the government against implementing
across-the-board cuts ``without consideration of the relative
scientific importance of the projects or the devastating impact
that such cut may have.''
	   On Friday, the group said it had found evidence the neutrino, a
tiny and elusive subatomic particle, has mass.
	   The discovery forces a revision of a decades-old theory of the
fundamental structure of matter. It may also compel scientists to
confront the possibility that neutrinos make up a significant chunk
of the ``dark matter'' that they believe exists but have so far
been unable to observe.
	   Neutrinos are one of nature's basic building blocks. They have
no charge and are so small that they were previously thought to
have no mass at all.
	   Neutrinos produced by nuclear fusion at the sun's core are being
constantly hurled toward the earth at the speed of light. Trillions
of them pass through the earth and on into the cosmos every second.
	   To detect the particles, Japan, with some funding from the
United States, built a 50,000 ton water tank one kilometer (half a
mile) down a mine shaft in the central Japan city of Takayama.
	   The apparatus doesn't actually allow scientists to capture
neutrinos or even see them but it can detect and measure the debris
left by collisions between neutrinos and subatomic particles in the
water.
	   The physicists said data collected over the last two years shows
that neutrinos ``oscillate'' or change type as they pass through
the earth, something that only things with mass do.
	   The scientists don't know how much mass a neutrino has, but
suspect they are many billions of times lighter than an electron,
the particle with the smallest known mass.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Japan-Neutrino, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
