<HEADLINE>
More shelling, more dead in Kosovo 
</HEADLINE>
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Dozens of houses were aflame and
Serb gunners kept shelling villages in Kosovo, where another four
people were killed in fighting, ethnic Albanian and Serb sources
said Saturday.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, which close to the ethnic
Albanian leadership in the Serb province, said fighting continued
Saturday in the Decani area, about 70 kilometers (45 miles) west of
provincial capital Pristina. The villages of Shaptej, Gramocel and
Babaloc were targeted by the Serbs' heavy artillery.
	   A 3-year-old child, identified as Leutrim Aga, was killed as he
slept in his bed in Gramocel and three other ethnic Albanians were
wounded in that village. Another ethnic Albanian was found dead in
nearby Babaloc.
	   Dozens of houses in the region were burning, the Kosovo
Information Center said. It also claimed that Serbian forces were
shelling border a strip west of Djakovica, 75 kilometers (47 miles)
southwest of Pristina, and that police reinforcements were sent in.
	   Serbian sources said two men were killed in a border clash
between Serb-led Yugoslav army troops and an armed group attempting
to illegally enter the province from Macedonia on Saturday. They
are the first dead at the Macedonian border.
	   The clash occurred in the early morning near the Brod outpost,
85 kilometers (53 miles) south of Pristina, the pro-government
Media Center in Pristina said. The identity of the two killed was
not reported.
	   A Serb policemen was also reported to have died in the Belgrade
military hospital of injuries sustained in previous fighting in
Kosovo.
	   Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people
and demand independence from Serbia, the larger of two republics
remaining in Yugoslavia. More than 250 people have died since March
1 in escalating clashes between government forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the armed wing of the Albanian independence
movement. Serbian troops are trying to quash the separatist
movement. More than 10,000 Kososo Albanian refugees fled to
northern Albania this week, the largest exodus since ethnic
tensions erupted into large-scale violence in March. Thousands more
are in neighboring Montenegro, which with Serbia, forms present-day
Yugoslavia.
	   Speaking to reporters on Brioni island, Croatia, Ilir Meta,
Albania's state secretary for European integration, said the
situation in Kosovo was getting ``more and more explosive'' each
day.
	   He repeated his government's calls for outside assistance to
cope with the continuing influx of Kosovo refugees.
	   ``If this situation is not stopped immediately, in the coming
hours and days, it can bring an unforeseen catastrophe not only for
the Albanians or Serbs but for the whole region,'' Meta said.
	   ``We consider that enhancement of NATO presence in the region
can help the strengthening of the security,'' he added.
	   Meanwhile, German foreign ministry official Wolfgang Ischinger,
touring the Balkans, met with ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova
in Pristina.
	   Ischinger was scheduled to travel on to Belgrade for meetings
with top government officials. On Friday, he visited neighboring
Macedonia, where he called the expulsions of Kosovo Albanians
``unprecedented,'' saying the international community ``cannot shut
its eyes before that problem.''
	   He added that international pressure on Belgrade government must
continue.
	   On Friday, the United Nations, in an unusually strong statement,
accused Serbian forces of atrocities in Kosovo.
	   In the Decani offensive this week, ethnic Albanian sources
earlier reported 50 dead, 200 missing and several villages
destroyed. There were also unconfirmed reports of a mass grave
containing 300 bodies.
	   A statement by Serbian police issued late Friday contradicted by
the subsequent Albanian account, indicated the latest offensive had
ended, with the ``terrorist gangs'' who tried to block the key
north-south Pec-Decani-Djakovica road ``destroyed.''
	   Most of western Kosovo remained sealed-off Saturday, and it was
impossible to verify the conflicting reports.
</TEXT>
