<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belgium-Generale Bank, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Generale Bank board chooses Fortis over ABN Amro takeover bid 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: CORRECTS name of Dutch bank in 2nd, 3rd grafs
<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The board of Belgium's Generale Bank on
Saturday declared hostile a dlrs 12 billion takeover bid from the
Dutch bank ABN Amro and moved instead to accept a rival offer from
the Belgium-Dutch financial group Fortis.
	   The decision came after an 14-hour board meeting that ended at
dawn. The Generale board voted 18 to 7 against the ABN Amro bid
with one abstention.
	   To protect Belgium's largest bank from the ABN Amro takeover,
the board voted 17 to 9 to increase Generale's capital by 10
percent. The capital increase was wholly subscribed and paid up by
Fortis at a cost of 47.4 billion francs (dlrs 1.295 billion).
	   Fortis increased its bid for Generale late Friday to 28,675
francs (dlrs 783) per share, a premium of 7.2 percent over the ABN
Amro bid. Fortis already controls 35.4 percent of Generale's
existing shares.
	   ``We have spent many months analyzing the synergies and benefits
of a combination ... we are wholly confident that these benefits
justify our offer in full,'' Fortis Chairman Maurice Lippens said
in a statement.
	   The Fortis-Generale group will be the 15th largest European
financial institution by market capitalization, Fortis said.
 &UR; (pa) 	   
</TEXT>
