<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Norway-Solskjaer,0522 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Manchester United forward is back in form after ankle injury AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
By STEPHAN NASSTROM
<TEXT>
	   LA BAULE, France (AP) _ Sitting on Manchester United's bench
didn't help striker Ole Gunnar Solskjaer's chances of making
Norway's World Cup team.
	   ``I understood that I had to play well in the last two games
before the World Cup,'' Solskjaer said as the Norwegians continued
their preparations Saturday for next week's Group A opener against
Morocco.
	   ``I had to improve and impress my coach (Egil Olsen).
	   Solskjaer did, netting twice in a 6-0 rout of Saudi Arabia in
Norway last week. It was his eighth goal in only 13 national team
appearances and his third of the year. He salvaged a 2-2 draw with
a goal against Belgium in late March.
	   It didn't look like he would make it to the squad after a
disappointing season in the Premier League with United.
	   ``The season started off very badly because I got an ankle
injury and I struggled for two or three months,'' Solskjaer said.
	   ``I didn't play many matches after the Monaco (Champions League)
game in March. I just had to keep my mood up.''
	   Solskjaer, 25, isn't sure if Olsen picked him for the squad
because of his two goals last week or because the coach knows his
capability now that he's finally healthy.
	   ``Maybe he suspects me to play well in big tournaments,''
Solskjaer said. ``I don't know. But I know I'm a much better player
that I've been showing in the last three or four months. My form is
improving all the time and I'm looking forward to the first game.''
	   In its final three exhibitions, the Norwegians beat fellow World
Cup sides Denmark, Mexico and Saudi Arabia by a combined 13-2!
They've won nine and drawn five since losing 1-0 away to Australia
early in 1997.
	   ``It's a very big tournament for Norway, just the third time
we've been in the World Cup,'' Solskjaer said. ``It's the biggest
event in Norway this summer. Everybody's watching us and the
expectations are high. But so are the expectations for the players.
But to win the World Cup, we have to be very, very, very lucky.''
	   Solskjaer's favorite is defending champion Brazil, Norway's last
opponent in Group A. The other one is Scotland.
	   ``I think Brazil has the best team in the world,'' Solskjaer
said. ``When it comes to the big tournaments they always seem to
get going again. It will be a very difficult game for us.''
	   Brazil has never defeated Norway. Despite Ronaldo on the team,
Brazil lost the latest match 4-2 in Oslo last year.
	   ``But just wait,'' Solskjaer said. ``We've played two games in
the last 10 years. But they were just friendlies and this is the
World Cup -- two big differences.
	   ``When we played them last year it looked like they were not 100
percent focused. But we know they're going to be 100 percent this
time. You always want to challenge yourself and play against the
best and Brazil is the best team. If I score against Brazil I will
remember it all my life.
	   (sn-rjm)	   
</TEXT>
