<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Genocide </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
35 people sentenced to life in prison in mass genocide trial 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ A court has convicted 35 people on charges
of genocide and sentenced them to life in prison at the conclusion
of a mass trial in connection with the 1994 slaughter, Radio Rwanda
said Saturday.
	   The court in northeastern Byumba opened a mass trial of 51
defendants in March to accelerate efforts to speed up judicial
proceedings for 130,000 people packed into Rwandan jails in
connection with the genocide.
	   On Friday, the court convicted 38 defendants, sentencing 35 to
life in prison and three to lesser terms. Nine were acquitted, and
four defendants died prison.
	   The 38 were convicted of taking part in, but not organizing, the
90-day slaughter of more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and moderate
Hutus organized by the former Hutu extremist government.
	   The killings ended when Tutsi soldiers ousted the government in
July 1994.
	   Since the first genocide trial in December 1996, Rwandan courts
have convicted more than 350 people. A third were sentenced to
death, most others received prison sentences and a small number
were acquitted.
	   On April 24, the first 22 convicts were executed by firing
squad.
	   Justice officials say they believe the executions prompted more
than 2,000 prisoners to confess to crimes in exchange for leniency.
	   Under a 1996 genocide law, those who confess can have their
sentences reduced if they implicate and help convict the organizers
and leaders of genocide _ most of them former Hutu authorities.
	   On Thursday, a court in Butare, 75 kilometers (45 miles) south
of Kigali, convicted and sentenced to death two former university
professors. They were accused of leading the massacres of Tutsis at
the University of Butare.
	   (hh/dmc)	   
</TEXT>
