<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-England-Drinks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Sheringham apologizes for late-night drinking 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: LEADS with Sheringham apologizing, adds quotes
Pvs: London
<TEXT>
	   BISHAM ABBEY, England (AP) _ England striker Teddy Sheringham
apologized Saturday for a late-night drinking spree at a Portuguese
nightclub, which openly defied instructions of coach Glenn Hoddle.
	   Hoddle, under some pressure to drop Sheringham, said there was
no similarity between this case and that of Paul Gascoigne. Hoddle
cut Gascoigne last weekend, distressed by his late-night habits and
lack of fitness.
	   ``I've been proud to be a professional footballer for 15
years,'' said Sheringham, speaking in a subdued tone at the team's
training site in southern England.
	   ``I've played 33 times for England and been very proud to do so.
I care about what I do and I want to continue playing for England.
	   ``I have explained what happened in Portugal to Glenn Hoddle. I
now want to put this matter behind me and the England team as
quickly as possible. I intend to learn from the experience.''
	   Sheringham's photo was splashed across papers Friday, showing
him with a cigarette in the mouth and his arm draped a young woman
in a bar on Portugal's Algarve coast. Accompanying stories said he
had been partying and drinking until dawn.
	   After breaking training camp in Spain last weekend, Hoddle
reminded players they were ``on England duty'' and ask them to
return home for a quiet few days before training resumed.
	   The incident put Hoddle on the spot, particularly since
Sheringham is regarded as a much less-talented player than
Gascoigne.
	   ``This is unlike the Paul Gascoigne case,'' Hoddle said. ``I'm
sure people will say they are being treated differently but with
Paul it wasn't a case of a drinking situation but about his
fitness.''
	   On Friday, Sir Bobby Charlton _ a member of England's 1966 World
Cup-winning side _ lambasted Sheringham for his lack of discipline
and suggested he had made England the laughingstock of world
soccer.
	   ``You are the focus of the whole country and if the players
don't have the common sense to behave themselves and act in a
reasonable manner it is absolutely nonsensical to think we have a
chance of winning it,'' Charlton said.
	   Just as the Sheringham and Gascoigne cases were clearing up,
England was rocked Saturday by the antics of a third England
player.
	   News reports said Darren Anderton was involved Wednesday in a
nightclub brawl in the southern town of Bournemouth. Anderton
denied he took part in the fight, although the tabloid Sun reported
a friend was punched in the face.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
