<SLUG> BC-Britain-Vintage Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Test pilot dies in vintage jet crash 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A test pilot died when a vintage jet aircraft he
was flying crashed during a practice flight, police said Saturday.
	   John Davies, 42, made several mayday calls before his Hawker
Hunter jet, a front-line Royal Air Force fighter during the 1950s
and 1960s, crashed nose-down during an emergency landing Friday at
Dunsfold Aerodrome near Godalming, about 30 miles (48 kms)
southwest of London.
	   Davies was found 40 feet (12 meters) from the wreckage wearing a
parachute and pronounced dead at the scene.
	   Davies joined British Aerospace in 1989 and recently became
chief test pilot for its regional aircraft.
	   A company spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, called
him ``a highly professional and widely respected pilot.''
	   He said a flying display at Dunsfold scheduled for Saturday had
been canceled.
	   (eml)
