</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seles faces Sanchez Vicario in final 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES in first 5 grafs with rain delaying play.
By JOCELYN NOVECK
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Spanish players have always excelled on clay
courts. This year, they have a chance to prove that in grand style,
with a sweep of the men's and women's French Open titles.
	   Arantxa Sanchez Vicario gets the first shot. She won two of her
three Grand Slam titles here, and is very comfortable on the red
clay of Roland Garros.
	   But she's up against someone who's done even better here. Monica
Seles won three times, from 1990-92. Then came the horrible
stabbing by a crazed fan in 1993, which kept her off the tour for
2{ years.
	   Now, she's turned adversity into her ally. Her father's death
May 14 seems to have given her new reason to excel; she says her
dad would have wanted her to play here, and she's looking like the
old Monica again.
	   Saturday's final was delayed indefinitely by a rainstorm.
	   Seles shook up the tournament Thursday when she ousted
top-seeded Martina Hingis, the overwhelming favorite, in the
semifinals.
	   Even more daunting for Sanchez Vicario, Seles is 14-2 against
the Spaniard, including a 6-3, 6-4 win in the 1991 final.
	   Then, Seles' father was watching from the players' box. This
year, she is wearing his ring on a chain around her neck.
	   Whatever happens on the women's side, the men's champion will be
a guy from Barcelona.
	   Carlos Moya went out with buddy Felix Mantilla for ice cream
before clobbering him in the semifinals. Now Moya is making dinner
plans with another close friend, Alex Corretja, whom he'll face in
an all-Spanish men's final on Sunday.
	   ``Maybe we can have dinner together. That's the most important
thing, we're going to be friends even if I win or if he wins,''
Corretja said. ``We have to find our game on the court, and then
just enjoy the party.''
	   Moya, Mantilla and Corretja all live in Barcelona and hang out
together on the road.
	   On a muggy center court Friday, Corretja defeated local hero
Cedric Pioline of France 6-3, 6-4, 6-2 to join Moya in the final.
Moya won 5-7, 6-2, 6-4, 6-2 over Mantilla, yet another Spaniard.
	   It will be the second all-Spanish men's final in five years at
the French Open. Sergi Bruguera defeated Alberto Berasategui for
the 1994 title.
	   ``Alex is a close friend of mine,'' Moya said. ``But when you
get on the court, you fight like crazy, you run, you do everything,
you try to step on him if necessary.''
	   Pioline, hoping to become the first Frenchman to win at Roland
Garros since Yannick Noah in 1983, played three five-setters in
reaching the semifinals and appeared drained.
	   ``I felt I did everything a bit slowly. On top of that, you're
not as focused when you're tired. You don't make the right
decisions,'' he said.
	   Corretja noticed.
	   ``I saw that Cedric was not feeling so well, he was struggling
on the court,''
	   Moya mixed powerful groundstrokes with delicate drop shots to
throw off Mantilla, who preferred to rally patiently from the
baseline. Moya also served 10 aces.
	   The Spaniards split the first two sets and Mantilla took a 4-1
lead in the third. But Moya won the next five games, losing just
five points.
	   ``I just decided to take more risks than I was taking before,''
Moya said. ``I decided there had to be a change, otherwise that set
was for him. Two sets to one down, it's tough to come back.''
	   Moya got to match point with a 127-mph serve, then hit a 122-mph
service winner to finish off the 2-hour, 42-minute match. He hit a
ball into the stands, then tossed his white bandana to fans.
	   Moya was runnerup at the 1997 Australian Open, but said he will
be less awed in a final this time.
	   ``In Australia, just to be in the final was a surprise for me.
But here is different.
	   ``I don't want to lose in the final again.''
</TEXT>
