<SLUG> BC-Italy-Prada-Gucci </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Italy fashion company Prada acquires slice of Gucci 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Designer Miuccia Prada has bought a 5
percent share of fashion company Gucci, Italian news reports said
Saturday.
	   No one could be reached at either Prada or Gucci to comment on
the reports carried by Italian news agencies.
	   The ANSA news agency quoted Prada's husband Patrizio Bertilli,
who is Prada's managing director, as saying the operation reflected
the ``diversification strategy'' in the fashion business.
	   ANSA said the operation was valued at dlrs 142 million.
	   The share acquisition appeared to have been unwanted by Gucci.
	   ``Gucci Group announces today that it was informed about the
purchase by the Prada group of 5 percent of Gucci shares,'' a Gucci
statement said, according to ANSA. ``Gucci Group points out that
this investment was not solicited by Gucci and, what's more,
declares that there is no accord or negotiations, under way or
foreseen, with Prada.''
	   Gucci Group shares are quoted on stock exchanges in New York and
Amsterdam.
	   Gucci, whose shoes, bags and other products carry the
distinctive double-G logo, was once a family company.
	   Maurizio Gucci, grandson of the company founder, was the last
family member to sell his shares. He sold his stake to the
Bahrain-based Investcorp in 1993, two years before he was shot to
death in Milan.
	   His ex-wife is among five people on trial here for the slaying.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
