<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Croats-Documents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnian Croat drivers ask for new documents their leaders rejected 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSTAR, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ An association of Bosnian
Croat truck drivers from this southwestern city on Saturday called
for internationally-recognized car documents and license plates
their leaders had rejected.
	   Carlos Westendorp, the top international official in Bosnia,
imposed new, common Bosnian documents, after Muslims, Croats and
Serbs failed to agree on them.
	   The new documents are written in both Latin and Cyrillic
alphabet, and the new common car plates are designed in a way that
makes it impossible to recognize from which region the car comes.
	   Westendorp said the citizens with old documents and license
plates will not be able to travel abroad as of June 1.
	   Bosnian Croat leaders bluntly refused the new documents,
claiming they could not accept the Cyrillic script.
	   But the move obviously affected Croats engaged in trade, the
most profitable activity in post-war Bosnia.
	   ``If our (local) governments do not want or cannot act according
to the internal community's rules, then they should compensate for
our losses,'' the Mostar truck drivers said in their open letter to
their leaders, as reported by the Croatian state news agency HINA.
	   They said they cannot travel abroad and if their leaders do not
meet their demands, thy would apply methods ``used by drivers all
around the world.'' They apparently meant road blockades.
	   (sv/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
