<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Chess </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polgar hopes to wipe smile off Karpov's face in battle of the sexes 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Eight speed matches start Tuesday
between Judit Polgar, the world's top female player, and disputed
World Chess Champion Anatoly Karpov, Judit's father Laszlo Polgar
said Saturday.
	   The matches will take place June 9-12 at a Budapest hotel.
	   Polgar, affectionately known in Hungary as ``Papa Polgar,'' was
his usual noncommittal self: ``The match can go one of three
ways.''
	   Judit, 21, was more upbeat in a television interview Friday
evening, in which she was shown pursuing a variety of physical
sports, like tennis.
	   When asked what sort of man Karpov is, she said ``He smiles a
lot,'' but hastened to add ``when things go his way.''
	   ``I hope they won't next week,'' she added with a smile.
	   Karpov is the reigning champion of the World Chess Federation,
known by its French acronym FIDE, although fellow Russian Garry
Kasparov is considered the true world champion.
	   Karpov defended his title against India's Viswanathan Anand in
January.
	   Laszlo Polgar recalled that when he was training his three
daughters - Zsofia, 23, and Zsuzsa, 29, are the other two - to be
chess geniuses, ``people like Karpov had a 100-member team behind
them, something we could never afford.''
	   Now computerized chess has pretty well leveled the field, Polgar
added.
	   (ab/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
