<HEADLINE>
Israeli, Egyptian peace activists meet 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Amid stalled peace talks, Israeli and
Egyptian activists met Saturday to discuss ways of building a
grass-roots peace campaign.
	   The Israeli delegates were from Peace Now, Israel's largest
peace group, which has thousand of members. The Egyptians
represented the Egyptian Peace Movement, a small group that
features several prominent writers and intellectuals.
	   The two groups are trying to hammer out a document that will
``clearly define the aims of ... peace and the mechanism to achieve
it,'' the London-based Al-Hayat newspaper quoted Lotfi el-Khouli of
the Egyptian group as saying.
	   Palestinian and Israeli peace talks stalled after Israel refused
to accept a U.S. proposal for a further 13.1 percent Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank. The Palestinians have accepted the
proposal.
	   The Peace Now delegation arrived in Cairo Friday night.
