<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Reporters, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC reporters plead innocent to illegal filming in Yemen overline 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with pleas, further charges; ADDS byline; CHANGES
By AHMAD AL-HAJ
<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Three British Broadcasting Corp. television
journalists pleaded not guilty here Saturday to a charge of filming
without government permission.
	   The journalists, who came to Yemen to report on kidnapping, also
pleaded innocent to charges of filming military installations and
importing a satellite telephone without informing the authorities.
	   BBC producer Robin Barnwell, reporter Rageh Omaar and cameraman
Frank Smith appeared in court with their lawyer, al-Sheik Tareq
Abdullah.
	   After a short hearing, the judge adjourned the case to Sunday.
	   The journalists were arrested May 26 when they returned to the
capital, San`a, after spending a week with the Bani Dhabyan tribe
near Marib, 170 kilometers (105 miles) northeast of San`a.
	   The Bani Dhabyan have carried out numerous kidnappings,
including the seizure in April of a British teacher, David
Mitchell, his wife Caroline, and their 14-year old son, Ben. The
Mitchells were released unharmed after two weeks.
	   The prosecutor told the court the journalists had hung ``Do Not
Disturb'' signs on their San`a hotel doors to trick the authorities
into thinking they had not left town.
	   He said they had traveled to parts of western Yemen where
kidnappings have taken place, despite being refused permission by
the government. As such they had violated the law by illegally
entering an area and gathering information.
	   The prosecutor handed into the court six video cassettes
confiscated from the BBC team.
	   During the past few years, armed tribesmen, who rule over large
parts of Yemen, have kidnapped numerous foreigners. They demand
concessions from the government in return for the hostages, who are
usually released unharmed.
 &UR; str-fsa-jbm
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yemen-Reporters, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
