w2341 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AirFrance-Strike 2ndLd-Writethru   06-06 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France strike enters sixth day; pilots pessimistic suspended, smaller union pessimistic. 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: LEDES with new quotes, Air France president saying talks only
AP Photos Planned
By DEBORAH SEWARD
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Saturday
said the government was prepared to intervene in the Air France
strike, which is now in its sixth day and could tarnish the World
Cup.
	   Air France President Jean-Cyril Spinetta said talks that lasted
all night without reaching agreement had been ``suspended.'' The
pilots indicated that new talks could take place Monday.
	   The strike has embarrassed France ahead of the World Cup, which
opens Wednesday.
	   ``It's not the World Cup that concerns me, it's the recovery
underway of the company and its future,'' Jospin told reporters
before a meeting of the national council of the Socialist Party.
	   Air France is in the midst of a major restructuring process and
needs to make pay cuts to free up capital to modernize the company
and its fleet of planes.
	   The World Cup will take place ``normally,'' Jospin said.
``French people don't need to take a plane to attend the World Cup.
Nor do Europeans, and we are going to find a lot of airline
companies to transport the rest at the expense of Air France.''
	   Air France is the official World Cup carrier and is committed to
transporting the teams from one venue to another. The company has
said it will meet that obligation.
	   Jospin said the French government was ready to intervene to help
end the the strike and would play a role ``in the hours to come.''
There have been suggestions the government may name a mediator, but
Jospin did not elaborate.
	   Talks between Air France management and the representatives of
the striking pilots broke off Saturday shortly before 8 a.m. (0600
GMT) after an entire night of negotiations.
	   The stumbling blocks remain planned salary cuts and a proposal
by Air France to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay
reductions, as well as a two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots
earn less.
	   Spinetta, the president of Air France, said the two sides had
worked out a way to end the conflict and talks were simply
suspended to give both parties time to reflect.
	   Spinetta said there had been ``very positive advances'' in the
discussions which ``have only been suspended.''
	   The pilots appeared more pessimistic.
	   ``It's so serious I prefer not to talk to you about it,'' said
Christian Paris, the spokesman for the SNPL, the main pilots'
union. However, SNPL President Jean-Charles Corbet indicated new
talks could eventually take place Monday.
	   Etienne Lichtenberger, president of the SPAC, one of the smaller
unions, said Air France's proposals were ``insufficient'' and that
it was ``out of the question'' to sign an agreement this weekend.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Saturday. Meanwhile, a train strike disrupted service
Saturday, although many lines were running as scheduled.
	   Top sports officials on Friday insisted that the June 10-July 12
World Cup would go ahead and that France would play the perfect
host.
	   ``I can assure you all 64 matches will be played and the French
will do everything possible to welcome the foreigners coming to
France,'' said Sepp Blatter, a senior soccer official and candidate
for the sport's top job _ head of the world governing body FIFA.
	   Michel Platini, former French soccer great and co-president of
the World Cup organizing committee, said five years of planning
would not be wrecked by labor disputes.
	   ``De Gaulle once said it was difficult to govern a country with
360 types of cheese. But we shall persevere,'' he said, referring
to former French leader Gen. Charles de Gaulle.
	   (dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
