<HEADLINE>
One killed, 12 wounded in four explosions in Hyderabad 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ A vegetable vendor selling his goods
from an open cart was killed Saturday and 12 people were wounded in
a series of explosions in the Pakistani city of Hyderabad, police
said.
	   No one claimed responsibility, but police said they suspected
extremists from a Sindh nationalist movement who had called a
general strike to protest the attempted assassination of their
leader two days earlier.
	   Five hand grenades or small bombs exploded in several areas of
the city. A 60-year-old man selling vegetables in the open-air
market was the only fatality. Four others were wounded by the same
device, said police officials on customary condition of anonymity.
	   A total of eight others were wounded in the other four attacks.
	   Activists of the Jeay Sindh movement, which wants more autonomy
and economic development for the Sindh province, also demonstrated
and burned tires in Karachi, the provincial capital, 180 kilometers
(110 miles) to the southwest of Hyderabad.
