<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belgium-Generale Bank, 2nd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Generale Bank board chooses Fortis over ABN Amro takeover bid 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with more details, quotes from Generale spokeswoman
<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The board of Belgium's Generale Bank NV
voted Saturday to declare hostile a dlrs 12 billion takeover bid
from the Dutch bank ABN Amro Holding NV and accept a rival offer
from the Belgium-Dutch financial group Fortis AG.
	   The decision came after an 14-hour board meeting that ended at
dawn. The Generale board voted 18 to 7 against the ABN Amro bid
with one abstention.
	   To protect Belgium's largest bank from the ABN Amro takeover,
the board voted 17 to 9 to exercise a ``poison-pill'' option that
increases Generale's capital by 10 percent.
	   The capital increase was wholly subscribed and paid up by Fortis
at a cost of 47.4 billion francs (dlrs 1.295 billion).
	   Fortis increased its bid for Generale 16 percent late Friday to
28,675 francs (dlrs 783) per share, a premium of 7.2 percent over
the ABN Amro bid.
	   Fortis already controls 35.4 percent of Generale shares and its
stake will rise to 42 percent with the capital increase.
	   ``We have spent many months analyzing the synergies and benefits
of a combination ... we are wholly confident that these benefits
justify our offer in full,'' Fortis Chairman Maurice Lippens said
in a statement.
	   The Fortis-Generale group will be the 15th largest European
financial institution by market capitalization, Fortis said.
	   Roughly half of the remaining Generale Bank shares are owned by
the public and half by institutional investors, said Generale
spokeswoman Kathleen Steel.
	   She said Fortis will have to pay a total of around 500 billion
francs (dlrs 13.7 billion) to buy all the remaining shares.
	   She said the board members turned against ABN Amro's bid because
they were concerned a takeover by the Dutch bank would lead to the
dismantling of Generale.
	   ``The said ABN's assurances that it would create a European
decision-making center in Brussels aren't sufficient to protect the
integrity of Generale Bank,'' she said.
 &UR; (pa)
</TEXT>
