<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Reporters, 1st Ld-Writethru,0319 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC reporters plead innocent to illegal filming in Yemen 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with pleas, edits. ADDS byline.
By AHMAD AL-HAJ
<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Three British Broadcasting Corp. TV
journalists pleaded not guilty in Yemen on Saturday to a charge of
filming without government permission.
	   The journalists, who came to Yemen to report on kidnapping, also
pleaded innocent to charges of filming military installations and
importing a satellite telephone without informing authorities.
	   BBC producer Robin Barnwell, reporter Rageh Omaar and cameraman
Frank Smith appeared in court with their lawyer, al-Sheik Tareq
Abdullah.
	   The judge adjourned the case until Sunday after a short hearing.
	   The journalists were arrested May 26 when they returned to the
capital, San`a, after spending a week with the Bani Dhabyan tribe
near Marib, 170 kilometers (105 miles) northeast of San`a.
	   The Bani Dhabyan have carried out numerous kidnappings,
including the April seizing of a British teacher, his wife, and
their 14-year old son. They were released unharmed after two weeks.
	   The prosecutor told the court the journalists hung ``Do Not
Disturb'' signs on their San`a hotel-room doors to trick
authorities into thinking they were still in town.
	   He said they traveled to parts of western Yemen where
kidnappings have taken place despite being refused permission by
the government. As such, they violated the law by illegally
entering an area and gathering information, he said.
	   The prosecutor handed into the court six video cassettes
confiscated from the BBC team.
	   During the past few years, armed tribesmen who rule over large
parts of Yemen have kidnapped numerous foreigners. They demand
concessions from the government in return for the hostages, who are
usually released unharmed.
</TEXT>
