<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Sri Lanka-New Zealand, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sri Lanka spinners put team on course to victory BY CALLISTUS DAVY 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with New Zealand second innings. No Pickup.
AP Photo Planned
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   GALLE, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lanka's spinners put their side on
course to a possible victory over New Zealand in the second cricket
test at the Galle cricket stadium on Saturday.
	   After taking a first innings lead of 130 runs, Sri Lanka plucked
five quick wickets to leave New Zealand on a shaky 94 for 5 with
Adam Parore and Chris Cairns struggling at the crease on 25 and 16
respectively.
	   Left-arm spinner Niroshan Bandaratilleke accounted for three of
the wickets _ Bryan Young (11), Mathew Horne (3) and Craig Mcmillan
(1) _ on a pitch that offered plenty of turn and bounce.
	   Young was caught by Hashan Tillekaratne at mid off after Horne
was adjudged leg-before. Mcmillan was caught by Sanath Jayasuriya
at slip.
	   Stephen Fleming looked as if he could cope with the turn and
bounce as the dug in for 115 minutes. But with his score on 10, he
was ruled out leg-before offering no stroke to a ball from
off-spinner Muttiah Muralitheran that bounced and straightened.
	   Nathan Astle faced 70 balls before he played a ball from
Aravinda De Silva onto his stumps for 13.
	   New Zealand earlier managed to restrict Sri Lanka from the
overnight 197 for 3 to a total of 323, but could not prevent Mahela
Jayawardena from making his maiden test century (167).
	   Jayawardena defied New Zealand for 335 minutes and was adjudged
leg-before off Chris Harris after 18 hits to the ropes.
	   Sri Lanka's hopes of making a bigger first innings total was
thwarted by quick dismissals of Arjuna Ranatunga and Romesh
Kaluwitharana.
	   (str/aks)
</TEXT>
