</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Central European and Balkan countries condemn Kosovo violence 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BRIONI, Croatia (AP) _ A group of 16 central European and Balkan
countries on Saturday condemned violence and all forms of terrorism
in the embattled southern Serbian province of Kosovo.
	   They also called for an ``immediate halt to violence that is
escalating,'' urged political dialogue between the Serbian
government and ethnic Albanians and expressed concern over the
``recent increase in the use of force by the Yugoslav
authorities.''
	   The group, called Central European Initiative, met amid reports
of more shelling and casualties in Kosovo.
	   More than 250 people have died since March 1 in worsening
clashes between government forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army,
the armed wing of the Albanian independence movement.
	   The Central European Initiative was formed in 1989 to boost
cooperation between its member countries. Yugoslavia, now composed
of Serbia and Montenegro, is not a member. Italy and Austria are
the only European Union members in it.
	   The countries' foreign affairs ministers debated for hours on
whether to describe the Kosovo conflict as violence or Serb
``ethnic cleansing,'' a term coined during the Bosnian war to
describe the mass expulsion of ethnic minorities.
	   They eventually decided to use both terms in their statement.
	   Albania, the poorest European country now accommodating
thousands of Kosovo refugees, is also a member of the group.
	   Its minister for European integrations, Ilir Meta, called on the
West to act toughly against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
``in order to push him to stop his strategy of ethnic cleansing''
of Albanians in Kosovo.
	   ``If this situation is not stopped immediately, in the coming
hours and days, it can bring an unforeseen catastrophe not only for
the Albanians or Serbs but for the whole region,'' Meta said.
	   He said that an increased NATO presence in the region would
improve the security.
	   Austria's Foreign Minister, Wolfgang Schuessel, said he would
ask Europe to increase its aid to Albania.
	   Schuessel, who met Milosevic in Belgrade on Friday, said the
latest Kosovo developments are ``clear evidence that it is a well
planned action and offensive by (Serbian) special forces, police
and the army.''
	   Speaking for neutral Austria, which is not a member of the North
Atlantic Alliance, he seemed to be reluctant to support an
intervention by NATO.
	   (str/sv/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
