w2378 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mozambique-SouthAfric     06-06 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mozambique-South Africa,0457 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Southern African commercial corridor to boost development 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   RESSANO GARCIA, Mozambique (AP) _ Two African leaders launched a
transport project Saturday that is expected to be a linchpin for
development in once strife-torn southern Africa.
	   South African President Nelson Mandela and Mozambique President
Joaquim Chissano dedicated construction for a toll road that will
connect the region's industrial heartland around Johannesburg with
one of the world's poorest nations.
	   The 2 billion rand (dlrs 400 million) toll road, expected to be
finished in three years, is being built by a private binational
company, Trans African Concessions, that will collect tolls for 30
years, then turn it over to the governments.
	   ``We are saying to the world that Africa is not only a zone of
instability, but rather one of economic progress and development,''
Chissano said to the audience of more than 1,000 gathered at the
remote border post of Ressano Garcia.
	   The 350 kilometer (217 mile) project is part of the Maputo
Development Corridor, which includes the upgrading of the port in
Mozambique's capital city to accommodate larger ships and increased
trade.
	   The toll road will improve the current stretch between Witbank
in South Africa _ 125 kilometers (78 miles) east of Johannesburg _
to Maputo on the Indian Ocean.
	   Mozambique offers harbor access to landlocked Zimbabwe, Malawi,
Zambia and Swaziland, and extra capacity for goods that now move
through overcrowded South African ports.
	   The corridor will provide the finishing stretch for the newly
opened Trans Kalahari Highway through Namibia and Botswana that
will eventually tie together Atlantic and Indian Ocean ports,
providing a much shorter route to European and American markets.
	   The projects open up economic opportunities for the southern
African region emerging from the stagnation of the apartheid era
that ended in 1994 with South Africa's first all-race elections.
	   ``As we co-operated in our struggle for liberation, as we stood
together against oppression and violence, so we now take hands to
improve the lives of our people,'' Mandela said.
	   South African Transport Minister Mac Maharaj said the corridor
had already attracted project proposals worth more than 35 billion
rand (dlrs 7 billion).
	   Two projects for Mozambique include a dlrs 1.1 billion aluminum
smelter project expected to begin production in 2000; and an iron
and steel plant that will use waste magnetite transported by slurry
pipe or rail from South Africa. Energy for the steel plant will
come from Mozambique's Pande gas fields, being developed by the
American company Enron.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mozambique-South Africa; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
