<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Cautious Spanish,0403 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Spaniards weary of dismissing Nigeria despite 5-1 thrashing 
</HEADLINE>
By CIARAN GILES
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   CHANTILLY, France (AP) _ A third consecutive defeat for Nigeria
should augur well for the team's first World Cup opponent, Spain,
but Javier Clemente's Iberian crew are taking the African side's
woes with caution and believe the team cannot be dismissed yet.
	   ``They're just preparatory games, the World Cup is different,''
Spanish defender Abelardo Fernandez said Saturday after the squad's
training session. ``In the cup everyone is much more motivated and
eager.''
	   Up to now Spain has feared Nigeria, the 1994 Olympic champion,
more than its other Group D opponents Bulgaria and Paraguay.
	   But although the Super Eagles have had their wings severely
clipped in exhibition games by a 1-0 defeat against Germany
followed by a 3-0 drubbing by Yugoslavia and Friday's 5-1 trouncing
by the Netherlands, the Spaniards are wary.
	   ``I think they're still a strong team, despite the goals and the
defeats,'' added Abelardo. ``They're going to cause a lot of
problems, that's for sure.''
	   Spanish coach Javier Clemente was equally dismissive of the
Nigerians' defeat saying such results ``don't count.''
	   As the June 13 game against Nigeria gets nearer, Clemente looks
to be slowly stepping up the pressure on his players. On Saturday,
the 22-man squad was put through a tough, fast-paced two-hour
exercise and playing session in hot and humid conditions at their
base just north of Paris.
	   Veteran keeper Andoni Zubizarreta was back between the posts
indicating that his recovery from a muscle injury is on track.
	   The session was attended by some 200 spectators while the
presence of some 100 journalists from a wide variety of countries
appeared to be a sign that more is expected of Spain in this its
11th World Cup appearance.
	   ``We have the team to achieve something big now,'' said
Abelardo. ``All we need is that little bit of luck to get that step
further and consecrate Spain, in results and titles, among the
greats.''
	   Despite being ranked among the world's leading soccer nations,
at international level the side has only won the European
championship in 1964 and the Olympic gold in 1992. The furthest it
has reached in the World Cup was fourth place in 1950.
	   (cg-sl)
</TEXT>
