<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open-Women-Running, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sanchez Vicario leads Seles after first set in women's final 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Updates with Sanchez Vicario winning first set
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Arantxa Sanchez Vicario took the lead over Monica
Seles by capturing the first set tiebreaker 7-6 (7-5) Saturday at
the French Open
	   Seles served for the first set at 5-3 but failed, missing an
easy overhead that could have given her set point.
	   Yet Sanchez Vicario battled back to win the tiebreaker 7-5.
	   A heavy rain began falling a half hour before the start and
delayed the match about 40 minutes.
	   Once it began, Seles jumped to a 2-0 lead, breaking Sanchez
Vicario in the second game behind hit some driving winners and a
smash of a weak defensive lob.
	   The fourth-seeded Sanchez Vicario took the break back in the
next game and evened it at 2-2.
	   Sanchez Vicario was scrambling to get the ball back in the
points but Seles was not pounding the groundstrokes with the same
accuracy as she did in pounding top-seeded Martina Hingis in the
semifinals.
	   The pair held to make it 3-3 and Seles won her next service at
love to go up 4-3 then took a 5-3 lead and served for the set.
	   At 30-30, Seles had a chance to get to set point at but sent a
smash into the net to give Sanchez Vicario a break point.
	   Sanchez Vicario came back to win the game, and held to make it
5-5. She forced a tiebreaker at 6-6 with Seles starting to make
unforced errors, four in the 12th game.
	   In the tiebreaker, Seles got in trouble with two drop shots
failing to put her down 1-4.
	   After Sanchez Vicario went up 5-1, Seles came back to even it at
5-5.
	   A service return into the net by Seles gave Sanchez Vicario a
set point and another unforced error by Seles gave the Spainiard
the first set.
	   Seles ended the 51-minute first set with 26 unforced errors,
Sanchez Vicario had just 13.
	   Seles was seeking her fourth French Open title, Sanchez Vicario
her third.
	   Seles won three times from 1990-92. Then she was stabbed by a
crazed fan in 1993. She returned two and a half years later, and
took her ninth Grand Slam title at the Australian Open in 1996.
	   Entering the match, she was 14-2 against Sanchez Vicario,
including a 6-3, 6-4 win in the 1991 final.
	   Then, Seles' father was watching from the players' box. This
time, she'll be wearing his ring on a chain around her neck.
	   Sanchez Vicario took the French Open titles in 1989 and 1994 and
also captured the U.S. Open in 1994.
	   (sz-jn)
</TEXT>
