<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leading party congress: full steam ahead with coalition talks 
</HEADLINE>
By ALEX BANDY
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ The winner of last month's elections
got a resounding endorsement from his party's congress Saturday to
negotiate with a populist party in order to form Hungary's next
government.
	   ``The election results made a coalition unavoidable,'' Viktor
Orban, the head of the Young Democrats-Civic Party, told party
delegates in a Budapest sports.
	   With 393 voting in favor, two against and two abstentions, they
authorized leaders to start negotiations with the Independent
Smallholders Party.
	   ``We are happy with the decision and hope the two delegations
will do everything in their power to have a government as soon as
possible,'' Zsolt Lanyi, the Smallholders' vice-president, told the
state news agency MTI after the vote.
	   The center-right Young Democrats-Civic Party won 147 seats in
the elections, well short of a majority in the 386-seat parliament.
	   Since Orban's other allies, the Hungarian Democratic Forum, only
have 18 seats, the Smallholders Party is pivotal for his governing
coalition.
	   Some in Orban's party had second thoughts.
	   ``It's impossible to govern with the Smallholders, but we must
try, because we have no choice,'' said Peter Toelgyessy, a leading
member in the Orban party.
	   It is not going to be a placid marriage.
	   Orban, a bright, 35-year-old law graduate is known for his quick
mind and rapid-fire talk. He will have to stand his ground against
Small Holders' leader Jozsef Torgyan, a 65-year-old former lawyer,
who is Hungary's most colorful politician, but something of a loose
cannon.
	   Orban has emphasized his party will retain the portfolios of
finance and a new big ministry in charge of the economy.
	   Those tapped for these posts agree on the need to pursue a
strict fiscal policy, something very hard to reconcile with the
Smallholders' budget-busting election promises.
	   (ab/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
