<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Lebanon-Aoun </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Exiled general says Cabinet ministers tried to assassinate him 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo SYD101
By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Exiled Lebanese Gen. Michel Aoun said
Saturday he is reluctant to go home because three current Cabinet
ministers once conspired to assassinate him.
	   Aoun would not name the alleged assassins in the Cabinet of
President Elias Hrawi. He said he would like to carry on his
crusade against Syrian domination once it becomes safe for him to
return to Lebanon.
	   Aoun said the attempts on his life occurred during his 1988-90
tenure as an interim prime minister, when he launched a doomed
``war of liberation'' against Syria's 40,000 forces in Lebanon and
then took on powerful right-wing Christian militiamen.
	   ``I had a close shave. Three ministers right now, three separate
ministers were behind these attempts on my life,'' Aoun said in an
exclusive interview with The Associated Press.
	   ``You don't know if they are going to kill you, to put you in
jail, or to `have an accident,''' he said.
	   His political downfall came in a 1990 Syrian army offensive that
ended the civil war. He sought asylum in the French Embassy and
then fled to France, where he has lived ever since.
	   Aoun said he would like to go home to promote his cause but
insisted he would never again seek public office.
	   Though Aoun has not seen his homeland since 1990, the Maronite
Catholic general still inspires strong passions in Lebanon.
	   Late last year, a Lebanese government ban on a TV interview with
Aoun led to clashes between his supporters and security forces
outside the television station in Beirut.
	   Though most of his partisans are Christian, he also has Muslim
and Druse backers who see him as a potential national savior.
	   Aoun made it clear Saturday that his long campaign to end
Syria's domination has merely shifted to the political front _ he
has abandoned his combat fatigues for a gray flannel suit.
	   ``The main part of our struggle is to liberate the country,''
Aoun said. ``Before the liberation of the country, no reform is
possible.''
	   Making his first foreign visit since going into exile, Aoun is
spending two weeks in Australia rallying the huge expatriate
Lebanese community here and lecturing on the Mideast crisis.
	   Hundreds of Lebanese Australians cheered him on his arrival at
Sydney's airport Saturday afternoon, waving signs and posters of
him. 	   
</TEXT>
