<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
Eds: Contains items on Egypt and Kuwait
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egyptian geologists have discovered in the
Gulf of Suez what they say is Egypt's largest oil deposit, the
leading newspaper Al Ahram reported Saturday.
	   The deposit will have an estimated output of 19,500 barrels per
day, Al-Ahram said.
	   It lies about 18 kilometers (11 miles) off the coast of Ras
Gharib, which is 250 kilometers (156 miles) southeast of Cairo.
	   The largest deposit currently being exploited in Egypt has an
output of 10,000 barrels per day.
	   The find is expected to boost Egypt's output, which currently
stands at 850,000 barrels of oil per day. The country exports about
half of this amount.
	   ____
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Kuwait will not announce any further oil cuts in
production before Gulf ministers meet in the Saudi Arabian capital
of Riyadh later this month, Oil Minister Sheik Saud al-Sabah said
in remarks published Saturday.
	   Sheik Sabah said Kuwait would not ``take any steps'' regarding
production cuts before the Gulf Cooperation Council meeting on June
16, the newspaper Al-Anba reported. The GCC groups Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and the United Arab Emirates.
	   Sheik Saud welcomed the latest pledges to cut output by the
so-called ``Riyadh Pact'' producers. Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and
Mexico announced Thursday that they would cut a combined 450,000
barrels per day of their output on July 1 in order to boost
depressed prices.
	   This would be in addition to earlier voluntary cutbacks agreed
by Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and non-OPEC
countries in March. Those cuts totaled around 1.5 million barrels
per day.
	   However, the market remains skeptical about the impact of the
latest cuts. It is widely expected that additional cuts from Kuwait
and United Arab Emirates will be announced soon to support the
Riyadh Pact move.
	   Kuwait, which has an OPEC production quota of 2.19 million
barrels a day, cut back by 125,000 barrels per day on April 1.
	   ____
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ A parliamentary panel has slashed the deficit in
the proposed 1998-99 budget by some 400 million dinars (dlrs 1.30
billion), reducing it to 1.33 billion dinars (dlrs 4.34 billion),
Al-Watan daily reported Saturday.
	   The head of the parliament's financial and economic committee,
Ahmed al-Nassar, told the newspaper the cuts were made from
military spending and money earmarked for transportation equipment
and services.
	   The 50-seat legislature has to vote on the budget before the
beginning of the fiscal year that starts July 1.
	   The budget forecasts revenues of 3.12 billion dinars (dlrs 10.19
billion), mostly from oil calculated at dlrs 12 a barrel.
	   Al-Nassar said the budget did not include taxes and fees for
services the government wants to introduce as part of a plan to
reform the economy, which is dependent on oil and government
spending. Lawmakers have criticized the measures.
	   The government had originally estimated the expenditure at 4.86
billion dinars (dlrs 15.88 billion).
 &UR; de-mae-jbm
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Middle East Business Briefs; CT:f; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
