<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru,0556 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRECEDE Rostaq Standoff with planes over fuel illustrates quake rescue problems 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: NEW thruout; changes byline
AP Photos FDB104-106
By JUDITH INGRAM
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan _ Pakistan tried Saturday to exact a heavy
price for delivering relief supplies to earthquake-stricken
northern Afghanistan, where up to 5,000 people were killed: enough
fuel to get its three helicopters back home.
	   The hours-long standoff between Pakistani and U.N. officials at
the Faisabad airstrip illustrated the competition for scarce
supplies that has plagued the relief operation from the start,
slowing aid and prolonging the misery of the tens of thousands of
survivors.
	   The United Nations and Red Cross have been able to muster only
three small helicopters to shuttle aid to the estimated 100 damaged
villages. The mountainous area is remote, and many roads were
damaged or destroyed in the May 29 quake, which local officials
estimate killed up to 5,000 people.
	   That paltry fleet and a severe shortage of aircraft fuel set the
aid effort back several days.
	   Now there is enough fuel to keep the three helicopters ferrying
back and forth all day long. But earlier Saturday. three Pakistani
helicopters delivered their goods and demanded a fill-up nearly
equal to the entire U.N. store, about 5,000 liters.
	   Ayaz Wazir, director of Pakistan's Ministry of Foreign Affairs,
said he had been promised the fuel by the U.N. office in Islamabad.
Asked by reporters why he didn't donate the helicopters to the aid
effort instead of taking them back to Pakistan, he said, ``First
give us the fuel. Then we'll give you an answer.''
	   The United Nations prevailed, persuading the Pakistanis to
siphon fuel from an Afghan military plane parked on the airstrip.
	   Meanwhile, the U.N. and Red Cross helicopters resumed delivery
of wheat, oil and plastic sheeting to the worst-hit villages.
	   But the deliveries were still behind survivors' needs. As of
Saturday, a full week after the earthquake, they had reached only
31 villages.
	   Survivors have besieged arriving helicopters, asking for food,
water and material to build shelters. In the hard-hit area of
Rostaq, villagers kicked bags of wheat, saying they were inadequate
to feed the hungry survivors.
	   An aid official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
humanitarian effort was being hindered by companies trying to
charge exorbitant prices for planes or helicopters _ dlrs 7,000 an
hour in one case _ and crews refusing to fly in Afghanistan, which
they consider a war zone.
	   In Aspakhan, a village reached Saturday, three woman crouched
atop a tangle of broken sticks and dried mud, just above what used
to be the window of their house. Hiding their faces with their
veils and sheltering two nursing babies from the dust of the ruined
village, they watched warily as an aid worker approach.
	   ``We have been waiting for you,'' said a woman known only as
Farishtana, as a couple of toddlers peeked from behind her
shoulder.
	   ``All we've had to eat is tea and a little bread. The vegetables
are there _ under that wall,'' she said, pointing down the ravine
below the village. ``Our animals are all dead.''
</TEXT>
