<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Scotland,0265 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Boyd sees Brazil game as chance for Scottish redemption 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   AVIGNON, France (AP) _ Scotland, which hasn't made a splash on
the international scene in decades, is looking for a little
redemption at the World Cup.
	   It could come in a hurry. The Scots play defending champion
Brazil in the tournament's opening match on Wednesday.
	   ``We probably wanted to avoid Brazil, but since they came out of
the hat, we have been up for it,'' defender Tom Boyd said at
Saturday's training session. ``To be honest, I think we've got a
good chance and if we play at our best, we can certainly take
something.''
	   Scotland is one of the oldest soccer-playing nations in the
world, but it has never made it past the first round in seven
previous appearances at the World Cup, and its storied club teams
such as Rangers and Celtic have met with little success in recent
European competitions.
	   ``In recent years, it has been nothing short of deplorable,''
Boyd said. ``There is a gulf between international and club level,
that is without question. You just have to look at the results we
have had in Europe.''
	   Boyd expects this team, which won seven of 10 games in
qualifying, will be different. Even if Scotland loses to Brazil, it
can advance from Group A with victories over Norway and Morocco.
	   ``As a nation getting all the best players together, we have
performed,'' Boyd said. ``We're leading the way, and hopefully the
clubs can follow _ we can spark them to improve by doing well
here.''
</TEXT>
