<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open-Women-Running, 3rd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seles evens final in second set 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with second set
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Monica Seles evened the French Open women's final
against Arantxa Sanchez Vicario Saturday, routing the Spaniard 6-0.
	   After losing a tight first set, 7-6 (7-5), Seles came into the
second set a new player. Gone were the errors that hampered her in
the first.
	   She broke Sanchez Vicario three times, jumping to a 5-0 lead in
just 18 minutes.
	   At that point, with Seles about to serve for the set, Sanchez
Vicario elected to take a bathroom break, and Seles decided to
follow.
	   When the players came back, Seles was still on target, hitting
two winners on the line for a 40-0 lead. She closed out the set
with an ace _ the first of the match.
	   It was a contrast to the first set, when Seles had served for
the set at 5-3 but missed an easy overhead that could have given
her set point.
	   Sanchez Vicario battled back to win the tiebreaker, 7-5, after a
hard-fought set in which both players lost their serve twice.
	   A heavy rain began falling a half hour before the start and
delayed the match about 40 minutes.
	   Once it began, Seles jumped to a 2-0 lead, breaking Sanchez
Vicario in the second game behind some driving winners and a smash
of a weak defensive lob.
	   The fourth-seeded Sanchez Vicario took the break back in the
next game and evened it at 2-2.
	   Throughout, Sanchez Vicario scrambled well to get the ball back.
Seles was not pounding the groundstrokes with the same accuracy as
she did in beating top-seeded Martina Hingis in the semifinals.
	   Both held serve to make it 3-3, and Seles won her next service
at love to go up 4-3. She then took a 5-3 lead and served for the
set.
	   At 30-30, Seles had a chance to get to set point, but sent a
smash into the net to give Sanchez Vicario a break point.
	   The Spaniard came back to win the game, and held to make it 5-5.
She forced a tiebreaker at 6-6 with Seles starting to make unforced
errors _ four in the 12th game.
	   In the tiebreaker, Seles got into trouble, missing two drop
shots to put her down 1-4.
	   But after Sanchez Vicario went up 5-1, Seles came back to even
it at 5-5.
	   A service return into the net by Seles gave Sanchez Vicario a
set point, and another unforced error gave the Spaniard the first
set.
	   Seles ended the 51-minute first set with 26 unforced errors.
Sanchez Vicario had just 13.
	   Seles was seeking her fourth French Open title, Sanchez Vicario
her third.
	   Seles won three times from 1990-92. Then she was stabbed by a
crazed fan in 1993. She returned two and a half years later, and
took her ninth Grand Slam title at the Australian Open in 1996.
	   Entering the match, she was 14-2 against Sanchez Vicario,
including a 6-3, 6-4 win in the 1991 final.
	   Then, Seles' father was watching from the players' box. This
time, she was wearing his ring on a chain around her neck.
	   Sanchez Vicario took the French Open titles in 1989 and 1994 and
also captured the U.S. Open in 1994.
	   (sz-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
