</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Mafia Bombings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
14 life sentences, 12 other convictions in Uffizi and other car bombings 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   FLORENCE, Italy (AP) _ Twenty-four mobsters, including top Cosa
Nostra bosses, were convicted Saturday of a rash of 1993 car
bombings that claimed 10 lives, damaged the Uffizi Gallery here,
two churches in Rome and an art gallery in Milan.
	   The court agreed with prosecutors that 14 of the 26 defendants
deserved Italy's stiffest punishment, life in prison. Among those
getting life sentences were top mob bosses Leoluca Bagarella and
Filippo Graviano, as well as fugitive Bernardo Provenzano, the man
many investigators believe may run Cosa Nostra from his hideouts.
	   The bombings were allegedly carried out to avenge the arrest in
Palermo in January 1993 of Salvatore Riina, the reputed ``boss of
bosses,'' who had been a fugitive for more than 20 years.
	   Riina, who is already serving several life sentences, will be
tried separately for the bombings. Prosecutors alleged that the
Mafia decided to target places of art and religion since culture is
Italy's biggest resource.
	   In May 1993, a car bomb blast narrowly missed an Italian talk
show host, who had denounced the Mafia, as he was leaving his
studio in Rome. A few days later, a car bomb went off in Florence,
killing five people in apartments near the Uffizi and seriously
damaging the museum and more than 200 works of art.
	   In July 1993, on the same night, a blast in Milan near a modern
art gallery killed five people, and two separate car bombings in
Rome devastated San Giorgio Velabro church in the historic center
and heavily damaged St. John Lateran basilica.
	   A 20-year-sentence was handed down to Giovanni Brusca, a Mafioso
who has been trying to convince authorities to let him join a
witness protection program in exchange for testimony in this and
other cases.
	   Other sentences ranged from 12 to 28 years in prison.
	   Two defendants were acquitted.
	   The convictions of the mob bosses of the bombings ``is a sign
that the Mafia then had taken on a terroristic dimension,'' said
Prosecutor Pierluigi Vigna.
	   The reading of the verdicts was interrupted for more than an
hour when tecnical problems cut off a video connection from the
courtroom to several Italian prisons where the defendants are
serving out other sentences.
	   Italian defendants don't have to be in court for their trials
and can be tried while fugitive.
	   (fd) 	   
</TEXT>
