<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain denies plans it plans to legalize the Irish Republican Army 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ The British government denied
Saturday that it plans to lift an 80-year ban on the Irish
Republican Army under new legislation providing for the release of
paramilitary prisoners.
	   Pro-British Protestant politicians opposed to the Northern
Ireland peace agreement claimed after Friday's publication of the
bill that it opened the way for legalizing membership of the IRA.
Victims of IRA bombings and their relatives also voiced dismay.
	   ``It's absolutely disgusting. It's beyond belief,'' said Jim
Dixon, who was injured in an IRA bombing in Enniskillen in 1987 and
is now a candidate for the new Northern Ireland Assembly on a
``voice for victims'' ticket. He warned that the IRA has said
clearly it will resume fighting ``if they don't get what they
want.''
	   Responding to the criticism, Northern Ireland Secretary Mo
Mowlam, the chief British official in the province, issued a
statement Saturday saying: ``Reports that I am preparing to make
the IRA a legal organization are absolutely untrue.''
	   Under the bill published Friday, up to 400 prisoners belonging
to the IRA and pro-British Protestant paramilitary groups could be
released by mid-2000 - but only if the groups maintain cease-fires
and cooperate with a commission charged with supervising the
handover of weapons.
	   ``The Northern Ireland Bill simply provides a means for
specifying organizations whose supporters will not benefit from
early releases,'' Mowlam said.
	   But Unionist opponents of the peace agreement described the
legislation as a ``legal muddle'' and said they believe it clears
the way for the IRA to be declared legal.
	   ``The IRA is proscribed, yet in this legislation they would not
be deemed a terrorist organization,'' said Peter Robinson, deputy
leader of the hard-line Protestant Democratic Unionist Party.
	   ``We will be putting down a series of amendments to try and
tighten this up and make more rigorous the terms which define a
terrorist organization,'' he said.
	   Early releases are a key provision of the peace agreement which
approved in a May 22 referendum. It provides for this British
province to have a Protestant-Catholic power-sharing assembly and
formal links with the Irish Republic.
	   The bill stipulates that each prisoner's case will be reviewed
individually, that prisoners deemed still dangerous to the public
would be kept inside, and that those released will be jailed again
if they commit new violence. Publishing the bill is the first step
toward introduction in Parliament.
	   The IRA and two Protestant-based groups, the Ulster Defense
Association and Ulster Volunteer Force, have maintained cease-fires
and their political allies endorsed the agreement.
	   Members of dissident groups that have not declared cease-fires,
including the Irish National Liberation Army and Loyalist Volunteer
Force, are not eligible for parole.
	   The province's largest Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists,
whose support was vital for the agreement, said it accepted the
wording of the bill, but would suggest some amendments in the House
of Commons ``to try to make it watertight.''
	   (eml)
</TEXT>
