<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Horse Racing-English Derby, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
High-Rise wins English Derby 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   EPSOM, England (AP) _ High-Rise with Olivier Peslier aboard won
the English Derby Saturday, beating City Honours by a nose with
third place to Border Arrow.
	   High-Rise _ an unbeaten colt _ went off as a 20-1 shot in the
mile-and-a-half race with City Honours 12-1 and Border Arrow 25-1.
Outsider Sunshine Street, who led for much of the early going,
finished fourth at 150-1.
	   It was the talented French jockey's fourth ride in the English
Derby and his first victory. He was the first French rider in 35
years to win England's most important flat race.
	   The favorites in the 15-horse field all faltered including Cape
Verdi, who was trying to become the first filly since 1916 to win
this race.
	   Cape Verdi went off as an 11-4 favorite but finished ninth.
	   Also back in the pack were other pre-race favorites like Greek
Dance (fifth), Second Empire (eighth), and King of Kings (15th).
	   ``I knew he was very well _ he had been working incredibly
well,'' said High-Rise trainer Luca Cumani. ``He is an unbeaten
horse and you must give him credit for that.
	   ``The immediate plan in my opinion ought to be to go for the
Irish Derby. A mile and a half suits him very well.''
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
