<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Tour of Italy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pantani wins time trial, virtually clinching Giro 
</HEADLINE>
EDs: will be updated
<TEXT>
	   LUGANO, Switzerland (AP) _ Marco Pantani virtually clinched the
1998 Tour of Italy Saturday after surprising even his biggest
supporters by finishing ahead of Russian Pavel Tonkov in the
individual time trial.
	   Tonkov, who trailed Pantani by 1-minute, 28-seconds going into
the Giro's penultimate stage, was largely expected to defeat
Pantani in Saturday's time trial. In a slightly longer time trial
last week, Tonkov beat Pantani by over two minutes.
	   But, charged up by the prospect of winning his first Giro,
Pantani burst out of the start and rode powerfully throughout the
34-kilometer (21-mile) race, gaining another 5 seconds on Tonkov.
The Italian now has a 1-minute, 33-second advantage over Tonkov.
	   ``I was extremely concentrated from the start,'' said an
exuberant Pantani. ``I warmed up well -- better than in other
occasions -- and then I gave everything I had.''
	   It is next to impossible for Tonkov, the 1996 Giro winner, to
catch Pantani in Sunday's final stage, a mostly flat 173-kilometer
(107-mile) ride from Lugano, Switzerland to Milan, Italy.
	   Pantani, 28, who was sidelined for the entire 1996 season with a
broken leg, took over the leader's pink jersey on Tuesday and has
held it ever since.
	   (vg)
</TEXT>
