<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Havelange,0443 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: FIFA president hopes for joint Korean team for next World Cup With Sports-Soccer-FIFA Meetings AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
By LARRY SIDDONS
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A united Korean team should be fielded for the next
World Cup and a mammoth stadium in North Korea's capital used for
some of the games, the outgoing president of soccer's world body
said Saturday.
	   FIFA head Joao Havelange said a joint North-South team had been
a success at the last under-16 world championships in Portugal and
that a similar effort for the World Cup would fulfill one of the
goals of his long-running presidency.
	   ``My idea is to unite the two countries on the sports field for
the World Cup in 2002,'' Havelange said at a news conference.
	   He said he had visited Pyongyang, North Korea's capital, four
times and seen the construction of a 100,000-seat stadium there.
	   ``With a united team, perhaps that stadium could be used for
some matches,'' Havelange said.
	   South Korea and Japan were picked by FIFA to co-host the 2002
World Cup, the first time soccer's world championship will be held
in two nations.
	   Havelange, who steps down from the FIFA presidency after 24
years at the end of this year's World Cup, also said he hoped to
eventually help stage an exhibition match between Israel and
Palestine in New York.
	   That idea was broached to him four years ago by Vice President
Al Gore, Havelange said, but it remained one of the unfulfilled
goals of his tenure despite repeated efforts and three meetings
with Palestine leader Yassar Arafat.
	   ``I would like to help prepare a match in New York City between
the two national sides,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, that has not
been possible.''
	   North and South Korea remain technically at war and eye each
other across the world's most heavily armed border. They
traditionally have fielded separate teams for international sports
events and South Korea's soccer team is competing in the World Cup
for the fourth consecutive tournament. North Korea did not qualify.
	   When the International Olympic Committee awarded 1988 Summer
Games to the South Korean capital of Seoul, North Korea demanded
that it share in the host role. Almost two years of negotiations
failed to resolve the dispute and the North boycotted the Seoul
Olympics.
	   North Korea, the last Stalinist state, has been wracked by
famine in recent years and is receiving various types of foreign
aid. The new president of South Korea, Kim Dae-jung, has called for
a softer approach to the North by the United States and other
Western nations.
</TEXT>
