<SLUG> BC-Emirates-Pakistan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistani Prime Minister arrives in Emirates on Gulf tour 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif arrived here Saturday for talks on the consequences of
the Indian and Pakistani nuclear tests, the official Emirates News
Agency reported.
	   Sharif, accompanied by Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and
Petroleum Minister Chaudhry Nisar Ali Khan, is expected to meet
Emirates President Sheik Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, the agency
said.
	   Pakistani diplomats said Sharif would head later Saturday for
Saudi Arabia. He is expected to hold talks with King Fahd and Crown
Prince Abdullah on Sunday in the Red Sea port of Jiddah, said the
Pakistani consul general in the city, Omar Khan Ali Shersay.
	   Sharif's mission to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates
was aimed at securing the required credit to maintain oil imports,
government officials in Islamabad said.
	   Pakistan bought dlrs 1.2 billion of petroleum products from Gulf
states during the nine months up to March.
	   India exploded five nuclear devices last month. Pakistan replied
with six nuclear tests, despite warnings from the U.N. Security
Council, the United States and other nations.
	   Led by the United States, several countries imposed economic
sanctions against the two South Asian rivals. The embargo is
designed to hinder foreign investment and credit.
	   Islamabad expects the sanctions to cut off financing for aid
projects from the International Monetary Fund, and to lower
Pakistan's credit rating, making borrowing more expensive. Oil
concessions from the oil-rich Gulf could help offset the effect of
the sanctions.
	   Last week, both Saudi Arabia and the Emirates expressed
understanding for Islamabad's view that its nuclear tests were a
means to preserve its security and territorial integrity. However,
both countries also said the tests increased tension in the region.
	   Sharif is expected to return to Pakistan Sunday.
 &UR; fsa-jbm
</TEXT>
