<SLUG> BC-Europe-Eritrea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
European Union deplores bombings by Ethiopia and Eritrea, calls for ceasefire 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The European Union on Saturday deplored the
``serious escalation'' in the conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea
and called for an immediate ceasefire.
	   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, whose country holds the
rotating EU presidency, said the 15 member states were ``extremely
concerned'' at the increased attacks. The EU ``particularly
deplores'' Ethiopia's bombing of Eritrea's main airport at Asmara
and Eritrea's bombing of the Ethiopian town of Mekelle on Friday
and Saturday, he said in a statement.
	   ``We urge both parties to agree a ceasefire and to resume
cooperation with the facilitators who are working to find a
peaceful negotiated settlement. We remind both parties of the
potential consequences this dispute has for future regional
stability,'' Cook said.
	   Britain and other EU members are supporting U.S. and Rwandan
efforts to broker a peace deal between the warring countries.
Britain and other countries have been unable to evacuate their
nationals from Eritrea becausing of the bombings.
	   ``These unnecessary developments threaten the lives of innocent
civilians and jeopardize plans for the evacuation of foreign
nationals, including EU citizens and other foreign nationals, who
wish to leave,'' Cook noted.
	   (eml)
</TEXT>
