<SLUG> BC-France-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former French defense minister appeals for conservative unity 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Former Defense Minister Charles Millon appealed
Saturday for French conservatives to unite in order to fight both
the left and the far right National Front.
	   Speaking at the first national convention of his new movement
called ``The Right,'' Million said no racists, antismemites or
xenophobes would be accepted into his movement.
	   French conservatives were badly shaken following local elections
this spring when a handful of them, including Millon, accepted the
backing of the far right in order to win regional presidencies.
	   Millon decided to form The Right after the Union for French
Democracy (UDF) party to which he belonged expelled him and others
who won regional presidencies National Front backing.
	   The UDF and the Rally for the Republic, the party of President
Jacques Chirac, recently decided to join forces in a new movement
called the Alliance.
	   The National Front has sapped the strength of traditional
conservatives in regional years. And the conservatives themselves
have lost the last legislative and regional elections to the left.
	   Both The Right and the Alliance are expected to hold political
conventions early this fall to work out their programs and
electoral strategies.
	   (parf-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
