<SLUG> BC-UN-India-Pakistan, 4th Ld,0181 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council considers resolution against South Asia nuclear programs later in the day 
</HEADLINE>
URGENT
Eds: LEADS with council reaching final agreement, vote set for
By ROBERT H. REID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Hoping to curb a dangerous arms race in
South Asia, the U.N. Security Council agreed Saturday on a Japanese
resolution urging India and Pakistan to halt their nuclear weapons
programs and denying them status as nuclear states.
	   Council ambassadors met privately Saturday morning for final
consultations. Council President Antonio Monteiro then scheduled a
formal meeting later in the day to take a vote.
	   That signaled the 15 members' agreement to the text, which was
tentatively accepted late Friday. Council ambassadors forwarded the
text to their capitals overnight and then reconvened to report
their instructions.
	   ``By their actions, India and Pakistan have seriously threatened
their global non-proliferation regime,'' British Ambassador John
Weston said.
	    &UR; But India, 3rd graf
