<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France,0414 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: France still looking striker who can score 
</HEADLINE>
By MARIUS TURULA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ France is still at a loss as to how it
will score at the World Cup. The latest hope is David Trezeguet,
only 20 years old and largely untested at the international level.
	   At the end of yet another frustrating exhibition match,
Trezeguet came on as a late substitute and scored the lone goal in
Friday's 1-0 win over Finland, further underlining the inefficiency
of starting forwards Stephane Guivarc'h and Christophe Dugarry.
	   ``(Trezeguet) is always good when he comes into a game as a
substitute,'' coach Aime Jacquet said Saturday. ``When the
opponents are a bit tired, it is always easier to play.''
	   France plays its World Cup opener against South Africa on Friday
and Trezeguet could well be France's best bet.
	   Guivarc'h has hit only one goal in his seven internationals and
Jacquet admitted that the French league's top scorer did not move
well against Finland. Guivarc'h also failed to set up a good
partnership with Zinedine Zidane and Youri Djorkaeff, an essential
link if France is to get on the scoresheet.
	   Jacquet used the backbone of his starting World Cup lineup
Friday and hoped the strike force would click. It didn't.
	   ``Our efficiency in front of goal is our big problem,'' said
captain Didier Deschamps.
	   ``Trezeguet the Savior,'' headlined L'Equipe sports daily
Saturday. It was his first goal for France in five appearances this
year, all of them from the substitutes bench. He had been hampered
by a thigh injury early on in France's preparation campaign and
hasn't had too much match rhythm recently.
	   But Trezeguet had a great season with Monaco, which rode his
goals into the semifinals of the European Champions Cup. Trezeguet
was born in France, but moved to Argentina at the age of 2 and even
made his debut in the Argentine league at 16 before returning to
France.
	   His rise could well be the demise of Dugarry, the Marseille
striker who long looked a longshot to make it on the French squad.
	   After a game of futility, Dugarry missed an open shot on goal
from 10 meters out just before being replaced the second half.
	   ``When it's really important, I won't miss a shot like that,''
Dugarry said.
	   But, Saturday, the big question was whether he would get another
shot in the World Cup.
</TEXT>
