w2477 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Albania-GunsandPoliti     06-06 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Guns and Politics,0819 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Once disgraced Albanian leader finds opportunity in Kosovo crisis 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo
AP Photo BAJ101
By BRIAN MURPHY
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ An orgy of arms looting last year began
former Albanian President Sali Berisha's tumble from power. The
weapons _ and the fighting in Kosovo where many of them are being
used _ could now figure in his strategy for a political comeback.
	   Berisha's power base in northern Albania is the conduit for
automatic rifles, mortars and other guerrilla-type weapons reaching
ethnic Albanian separatists in the neighboring Serbian province of
Kosovo. The arms are lugged across the rugged border on rutted
roads or overland by mule.
	   Some diplomats are drawing a clearer link between the convoys
and Berisha's own battles against Prime Minister Fatos Nano.
	   The arms traffic puts needed money in the pockets of Berisha's
hard-core political backers while making Nano's government appear
unable to control the northeastern frontier, diplomats said.
	   At the same time, Berisha can portray himself as a champion of
Albanian nationalism and the outgunned Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   Internal unrest in Albania, touched off by Kosovo, could offer
Berisha and his allies the footholds they need to climb back toward
power, diplomats speculated.
	   This is an alarming prospect for many European leaders, who have
repeatedly urged Berisha to end anti-government ``agitation'' since
his election defeat in June 1997.
	   ``No one is saying _ yet _ that Berisha is orchestrating the
arms trafficking,'' said a Balkan diplomat who spoke on condition
of anonymity. ``But he's certainly not doing anything to discourage
it. It's to his advantage.''
	   At a meeting of opposition parties on Friday, Berisha called
Nano's government an ``enemy of the Albanian nation'' _ a reference
to ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and elsewhere in the Balkans. He
called the Serb forces ``barbarians'' and the rebels ``blessed.''
	   Such rhetoric further alienates Berisha from the West, where
political and military leaders have expressed resolve not to allow
the Kosovo conflict to escalate. About 10,000 refugees have fled to
Albania to escape a Serb offensive opened last week.
	   Fighting in Kosovo since March has claimed at least 250 lives.
But refugees have given unconfirmed reports of a mass grave with
300 bodies, according to the Belgrade-based Beta news agency.
	   ``Berisha is playing a dangerous game,'' said a Western
diplomat. ``If he is seen as encouraging the (Kosovo Liberation
Army), then he can become something of a pariah.''
	   The diplomat added that there are indications that the arms
trafficking is becoming more consolidated and moving away from a
``bazaar of freelancers.'' Also, the amount of weapons crossing the
border appears to have increased significantly since the Kosovo
rebels ``have grown in support so quickly,'' the diplomat said.
	   Some Kosovo separatist bands are now outfitted with looted
Albanian army uniforms, giving at least the appearance of greater
unity among the ragtag units.
	   ``Signals are showing that a new Bosnia is coming up,'' Ilir
Meta, Albania's state secretary for European integration, said at
an international conference in Brioni, Croatia.
	   In the Albanian capital, Tirana, Nano has felt the pressure. He
has been forced to fend off Berisha's political attacks while
trying to cope with the refugee dilemma.
	   Nano appealed to opposition parties on Saturday ``to stop using
this critical situation for electoral intentions.''
	   He allocated more than dlrs 300,000 from Albanian meager
treasury reserves to help Albanian families housing refugees. He
also urged at least dlrs 20 million in international aid.
	   Yet the main thrust of the Albanian effort is to secure a
commitment for an international force, possibly under NATO command,
to watch the border. This could not only curb the arms and refugee
flow, but give Nano an important political buffer: he wouldn't have
to use Albanian forces against Albanian arms smugglers.
	   ``We need international assistance ... especially on stopping
all the types of (arms) smuggling,'' said Nano, who estimated that
2,000 tons of looted military shells and other explosives are
stashed around Albania.
	   Hundreds of thousands of guns and other military equipment were
taken in the anarchy in early 1997 following the collapse of dodgy
investment schemes that cost many Albanians their entire savings.
Berisha's government was widely blamed for permitting the financial
meltdown.
	   But the Kosovo conflict has given him a new political rallying
cry.
	   ``No government, no matter how bad it is, steps down on its own
unless we make it do so,'' said Genc Pollo, the Democratic Party
deputy chairman.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Albania-Guns and Politics; CT:i; 
