<SLUG> BC-Nicaragua-Police Attack,0213 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Attack on Nicaragua police spokesman; drug plane scandal could be linked 
</HEADLINE>
By RODOLFO GARCIA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ Gunmen fired shots at the new
spokesman for Nicaragua's national police Saturday, wounding his
10-year-old son in an attack that police said could be linked to a
drug-smuggling scandal.
	   Carlos Bendana, who has been on the job for only two days, was
suspended last month from his job as Nicaragua's go-between with
Interpol after a scandal involving a stolen plane used by drug
smugglers as well as by the president and vice president.
	   Eduardo Cuadra Ferrey, second-in-command of the national police
force, said, ``We aren't discounting the possibility that the
attack on Bendana could be a conspiracy of international drug
smugglers.''
	   Bendana's son suffered a minor wound to his head. Three men were
arrested.
	   The Learjet 35A stolen in Florida had apparently been registered
in Nicaragua with the help of government officials and used to
transport drugs. Nicaraguan leaders were offered free use of it as
a way of diverting suspicion. Traces of cocaine were later found
inside. At least eight officials were dismissed and six people were
charged.
</TEXT>
