<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Bike Racer Slain,0283 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Teen-age BMX champ killed for his bicycle 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ A 14-year-old champion cross-country
bicycle racer with dreams of racing internationally was killed with
a gunshot to the chest by a gang of youths who stole his bike and
sneakers, the boy's father said.
	   William Alexander Jimenez, a favorite to win next month's
national BMX cycling championship in Medellin, was returning to his
home in Cali on Thursday night after visiting his girlfriend when
he was accosted by the youths.
	   The six assailants demanded Jimenez's bicycle and sneakers. When
he refused, one youth shot Jimenez in the heart. The assailants
took the bike, removed Jimenez's sneakers and left him bleeding in
the street. The bike racer died before reaching the hospital.
	   Jimenez's father, Flavio, said his son wasn't much of a student
but was totally dedicated to bike racing.
	   ``He fixed bicycles, painted them and with the money he earned
bought his uniforms,'' Flavio Jimenez told the Bogota newspaper El
Espectador between sobs. And though William had once broken a leg
racing on a hilly BMX course, he was fearless, his father said.
	   ``The higher he jumped, the better,'' Flavio said, adding that
his son had an excellent shot at advancing to an international race
in Canada.
	   Colombian BMX racers have been targeted by criminals before.
	   In 1996, 13-year-old junior national champion Andres Varela was
seized from his school bus in Medellin by kidnappers, then later
freed by police unharmed.
	   The previous year, a 9-year-old BMX champion, Augusto Castro,
was kidnapped in Medellin. He was later released.
</TEXT>
