<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France strike enters sixth day; pilots ready to talk again 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: AMs. Ledes with pilots ready to talk again
AP Photos Planned
By DEBORAH SEWARD
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Saturday
the government was prepared to intervene in the Air France strike,
which is now in its sixth day and could tarnish the World Cup.
	   Air France President Jean-Cyril Spinetta said talks that lasted
all night without reaching agreement had been ``suspended.''
	   The pilots appeared divided, with the head of the main pilots'
union indicating new talks could take place Monday and a spokesman
saying they could go back to the table over the weekend.
	   The strike has embarrassed France ahead of the World Cup, which
opens Wednesday.
	   ``It's not the World Cup that concerns me, it's the recovery
underway of the company and its future,'' Jospin told reporters
before a meeting of the national council of the Socialist Party.
	   Air France is currently restructuring and needs to make pay cuts
to free up capital to modernize the company and its fleet of
planes.
	   The World Cup will take place ``normally,'' Jospin said.
``French people don't need to take a plane to attend the World Cup.
Nor do Europeans, and we are going to find a lot of airline
companies to transport the rest at the expense of Air France.''
	   Air France is the official World Cup carrier and is committed to
transporting the teams from one venue to another.
	   Jospin said the French government was ready to intervene to help
end the the strike and would play a role ``in the hours to come.''
	   There have been suggestions the government may name a mediator,
but by early evening no proposals were forthcoming.
	   Talks between Air France management and the the striking pilots
broke off Saturday about 8 a.m. (0600 GMT) after all night
negotiations.
	   The stumbling blocks remained planned salary cuts and an Air
France proposal to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay
reductions, as well as a two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots
earn less.
	   Spinetta, the Air France president, said there had been ``very
positive advances'' in the talks.
	   The pilots appeared more pessimistic.
	   ``It's so serious I prefer not to talk to you about it,'' said
Christian Paris, the spokesman for the SNPL, the main pilots'
union.
	   However, SNPL President Jean-Charles Corbet indicated new talks
could eventually take place Monday. However, another SNPL official,
Christian Roger, said talks could be resumed over the weekend.
	   Etienne Lichtenberger, president of the SPAC, one of the smaller
unions, said Air France's proposals were ``insufficient'' and that
it was ``out of the question'' to sign an agreement this weekend.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Saturday. Meanwhile, a train strike disrupted provincial
service.
	   (dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
