r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil     06-06 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil,0615 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Teammates vie for Romario's spot on Brazilian team 
</HEADLINE>
By PETER MUELLO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   OZOIR LA FERRIERE, France (AP) _ Romario is gone, and the battle
is on for his place in Brazil's starting lineup.
	   For now, Bebeto is the No. 2 striker, alongside Ronaldo. But
Edmundo openly says he deserves the job, and Denilson could upstage
them both once the Cup starts next Wednesday.
	   The rivalry has created a problem for coach Mario Zagallo. While
he encourages healthy competition among his players, the dispute
has created rifts that veterans say could weaken the group.
	   The disharmony was Edmundo's doing. In an interview Friday with
a Rio de Janeiro radio station, Edmundo said he deserved to start
because he was ``in better physical and technical shape, and
overall I'm better than Bebeto.''
	   The comment created turmoil at training camp and drew a sharp
reply from the high command. Team coordinator Zico said no one
would be allowed to disrupt the group, and Zagallo added that if
there were disciplinary problems among his 22 players, Brazil could
easily ``finish the Cup with 21.''
	   The problem is, Edmundo may be right.
	   At 27, Edmundo is at peak form. Last year he broke Brazil's
single-season scoring record with 29 goals and led Rio's Vasco da
Gama to the national championship, before jumping to Italy's
Fiorentina.
	   On the national team, he has nine goals in 34 games and was a
standout last year in the Tournoi de France and the America Cup,
which Brazil won for the first time away from home.
	   Edmundo's problem is his temper. Nicknamed ``Animal,'' he was
red-carded seven times last year and routinely fights with opposing
players, teammates and referees.
	   For now, the starter is Bebeto, Romario's co-star on Brazil's
1994 World Cup champions. Bebeto started in Brazil's 3-0 win over
Andorra this week, and Zagallo confirmed he would also start in the
Cup opener against Scotland.
	   The coach insisted his reasons for choosing Bebeto were purely
technical.
	   ``He can score, he moves well, he's more of an attacker than
Edmundo,'' Zagallo said. ``And he played in the (1996) Olympics
with Ronaldo, so they are better meshed.''
	   But Zagallo puts a high premium on experience. On his original
22-player roster, nine were World Cup veterans, although injuries
removed Romario and fullback Marcio Santos. Bebeto is playing in
his third World Cup _ Edmundo in his first.
	   Bebeto also was something of a surprise on the Cup roster. At
34, he has lost the mercurial quickness of four years ago. On his
Botafogo club, he has failed to produce the goals fans expected.
	   Neither Bebeto nor Edmundo can fill the role of Romario, who was
cut this week after reinjuring his calf. Brazil's offense pivoted
around Romario, the team's point of reference in the penalty area.
No one on the team now has his style or presence.
	   Many fans want to see 20-year-old sensation Denilson join
Ronaldo, 21, in what promises to be the Brazilian attack of the
future.
	   Denilson won a starting berth at the 1997 America Cup and held
it until last month, when Zagallo opted to start Rivaldo and
Giovanni, teammates on Spain's FC Barcelona.
	   But Zagallo is an unabashed admirer of Denilson, whose wizardly
ball-handling skills and brash, in-your-face dribbles have earned
him comparisons with the legendary Garrincha.
	   Zagallo guaranteed Denilson will see playing time in the Cup _
and possibly on the front line, his true position. If Bebeto and
Edmundo don't measure up, the anticipated Denilson-Ronaldo dynasty
could start now.
	   (pm-sl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil; CT:s; 
