<BODY>
<SLUG> BC- Jordan-Pipeline </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan has completed a feasibility study on
a 650-mile (1,000-kilometer) oil pipeline between the Iraqi and
Jordanian capitals.
	   Abdul-Wahab Zobbi, director general of the state Jordan
Petroleum Refinery, said Saturday the proposed pipeline would cost
about dlrs 250 million.
	   ``The study shows that the pipeline is feasible,'' he told The
Associated Press.
	   The study will be presented to the governments of Iraq and
Jordan for approval, he said. Both countries have long advocated
such a pipeline.
	   Jordan imports all of its daily consumption of 85,000 barrels of
oil from Iraq, under special dispensation from the U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
	   The fuel is carried by tanker trucks. But this form of transport
is costly and there have been several accidents, resulting in
fires, on the desert highway between the Jordanian capital, Amman,
and the Iraqi capital, Baghdad.
	   Zobbi declined to reveal a possible source of financing, but
officials say the kingdom is approaching France, Italy, Germany and
Japan for contributions.
	   Zobbi said the pipeline's capacity would be 100,000 barrels of
oil per day. It would run from Jordan's lone refinery in Zarqa, 17
miles (27 kilometers) southeast of Amman, to Haditha, a terminal on
the northwestern outskirts of Baghdad.
