<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pope names new envoy for Israel 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ Pope John Paul II on Saturday named an
Italian prelate to be his new envoy to Israel. The diplomatic
posting to Jerusalem comes as a possible papal visit there is
explored.
	   Monsignor Piero Sambi, 50, who has been serving in Indonesia,
will replace Monsignor Andrea Cordero di Montezemolo, who was named
in March to be the Vatican's envoy to Italy.
	   Sambi would likely be involved in any paving of the way for a
papal visit to Jerusalem.
	   John Paul has expressed a keen desire to journey there as part
of Holy Year and millennium celebrations in 2000. But the pope's
presence there would be sensitive because the Vatican state and
Israel differ over the future of the city, which is special to
Jews, Christians and Muslims.
	   Only last month, the pontiff said he hoped for international
guarantees for the ``unique'' and ``sacred'' nature of Jerusalem.
But Israel considers the entire city its eternal capital.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
