<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs, 2nd Ld,0502 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
power stations; South African striker Augustine; corrects lead sequence 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: includes items on Scotland ire over FIFA rule; Bangladesh
<TEXT>
	   AVIGNON, France (AP) _ Scotland, upset over a FIFA dicate which
prohibits treatment of players on the field, is threatening take
referees to court and sue them for negligence should the rule
result in players' injuries being aggravated.
	   ``You could have a case when a player with a severe head injury
could be carried off,'' manager Craig Brown said. ``We will take it
back to our medical men and we could see a circumstance where
litigation could be involved there.''
	   Brown is sensitive to the issue because he has two players,
Darren Jackson and Gordon Durie, who suffered head injuries earlier
this season. Jackson underwent brain surgery in August, while Durie
missed several weeks with a concussion.
	   Scotland's team doctor, Stewart Hillis, was once ordered off the
field when he attempted to treat Rob McKinnon during a Kirin Cup
match in Japan in 1995. Hillis said he will ignore the no-treatment
rule during the World Cup, if necessary.
	   ``Our priority is looking after the players,'' Hillis said. ``We
are not looking for confrontation.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Paramilitary forces will guard
Bangladeshi power stations during the World Cup to guard against
possible attacks by angry soccer fans in the event of power
outages, a senior official said Saturday.
	   Soldiers and police will take positions around all major power
stations 12 hours before the opening match June 10 in France,
Nuruddin Mohammad Kamal, chairman of the state-owned Power
Development Board, told reporters.
	   The nation's major cities, including Dhaka, Chittagong, Khulna
and Rajshahi, face regular power outages and citizens have often
staged violent demonstrations at power stations in response.
	   Bangladesh needs more than 2,100 megawatts of electricity each
year, but regularly generates only 1,700 megawatts.
	   Bangladesh did not qualify for the World Cup.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ A groin injury has South
African striker Brendan Augustine questionable for the team's World
Cup opener.
	   ``I'm getting worried,'' said coach Philippe Troussier, who told
the South African newspaper Saturday Star that Augustine hasn't
practiced in six days.
	   Troussier said a specialist would look at the injury when the
team arrives in France on Sunday from its training camp in
Germany's Black Forest. A final decision on Augustine's status will
be made Monday.
	   South Africa is already without midfielder John Moeti, who broke
his ankle in a league match before the team left South Africa in
May.
	   South Africa plays France on June 12 in the first-round World
Cup match in Marseilles. The team played Iceland in an exhibition
match Saturday in Obertal, Germany.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Just days, 1st graf
