<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-India-Yeltsin, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin urges India to sign non-proliferation pact remarks 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf to UPDATE with Gorbachev
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin spoke with India's
prime minister on Saturday and urged India to sign the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty, the Kremlin said.
	   In a telephone conversation with Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee, Yeltsin expressed concern over the recent spate of
nuclear testing by India and Pakistan, according to Yeltsin's
presidential press service.
	   ``It was stressed that the Indian-Pakistani nuclear competition
has spread far beyond the region. It undermines the nuclear
non-proliferation regime and sets a dangerous precedent of nuclear
weapons spread,'' the press service said.
	   The Kremlin also said Yeltsin and Vajpayee discussed how Russia
might play a role in encouraging a dialog between India and
Pakistan.
	   Also Saturday, a Russian newspaper published an article by
former Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in which he argued that the
five nuclear superpowers _ especially the United States and Russia
_ had inadvertently encouraged the Indian and Pakistani tests.
	   The superpowers have failed to take nuclear disarmament
seriously, Gorbachev argued in Nezavisimaya Gazeta. He said that
created the climate in which India and Pakistan felt justified in
carrying out the tests.
	   For the non-proliferation treaty to be successful, he said, the
superpowers need to take ``concrete steps toward nuclear
disarmament.'' Instead, he said, Moscow and Washington have ``been
making it increasingly clear that they link their defense
capability to nuclear weapons.''
	   India set off five underground nuclear tests last month,
prompting Pakistan to retaliate with a series of tests two weeks
later.
	   Under the 1970 Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, the five
members of the United Nations Security Council are the only nations
allowed to maintain nuclear arsenals. India and Pakistan have
refused to sign the treaty.
	   The Security Council has tentatively agreed on a resolution
urging India and Pakistan to stop their nuclear testing and denying
them status as nuclear states.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
