<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Tour of Italy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pantani wins time trial, virtually clinching Giro 
</HEADLINE>
EDs: UPDATES with more quotes, details; minor editing
<TEXT>
	   LUGANO, Switzerland (AP) _ Marco Pantani virtually clinched the
1998 Tour of Italy Saturday after surprising even his biggest
supporters by finishing ahead of Russian Pavel Tonkov in the
individual time trial.
	   Tonkov trailed Pantani by 1-minute, 28-seconds going into this
cycling classic's penultimate stage. But, Tonkov, a time trial
specialist, was expected to easily defeat Pantani and make up the
time.
	   In last week's time trial Tonkov beat Pantani by more than
2-minutes.
	   Instead, charged up by the prospect of winning his first Giro,
Pantani burst out of the start and rode powerfully throughout the
34-kilometer (21-mile) race, gaining another 5-seconds on Tonkov.
The Italian now holds a 1-minute, 33-second advantage.
	   ``Incredible,'' said an exuberant Pantani. ``I really think the
fear of losing this (leader's pink) jersey gave me a surge of extra
energy.''
	   It is virtually impossible for Tonkov, the 1996 Giro winner, to
catch Pantani in Sunday's final stage, a mostly flat 173-kilometer
(107-mile) ride from Lugano, Switzerland to Milan, Italy.
	   ``I was extremely concentrated from the start,'' said Pantani.
``I warmed up well -- better than in other occasions -- and then I
gave everything I had.''
	   Pantani, 28, has had a series of accidents, and was sidelined
for the entire 1996 season with a broken leg.
	   A climbing specialist, Pantani took over the leader's pink
jersey for the first time in his career five days ago during a
roller coaster ride through the Italian Alps.
	   Switzerland's Alex Zuelle, who was considered the race favorite
after dominating the initial stages, lost more than 30 minutes
during the Tour's toughest stage Thursday -- 239 kilometers (148
miles) up steep mountain roads in scorching heat.
	   When riders cross the finishline Sunday they will have covered a
total of 3,868 kilometers (2,398 miles).
	   Victory in Saturday's time trial went to Serguei Gontchar of the
Ukraine. He finished in 39-minutes, 54-seconds, posting an average
speed of over 50 kph (30 mph).
	   Pantani finished third, 30.60 seconds behind.
	   ``I knew that if i had lost time on Tonkov today, all the hard
work I have put in the past 21 days would have disappeared,''
Pantani said.
	   Italians Nicola Miceli, who was in fifth overall going into
Saturday's stage, and Riccardo Forconi were disqualified after
failing routine blood tests administered before the start of the
time trial.
	   (vg)
</TEXT>
