<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Eritrea-Ethiopia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. envoy steps up diplomacy, African ministers urge truce 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ U.S. Assistant Secretary of
State Susan Rice stepped up a campaign of shuttle diplomacy
Saturday in an effort to broker dialogue between Ethiopia and
Eritrea.
	   Rice left the West African capital of Ouagadougou for Ethiopia
and Eritrea where she hopes to meet with government
representatives.
	   Her latest peace efforts came on the same Ethiopian warplanes
bombed targets in Eritrea in another escalation of fighting over
their contested border.
	   Among the world's poorest countries, Eritrea and Ethiopia
contest ownership of six areas along their common frontier.
	   Before leaving, Rice met with foreign ministers from members
states of the Organization of African Unity. The ministers are
gathered in Burkina Faso for preliminary talks before a heads of
state summit next week.
	   Rice is promoting a peace plan for the two feuding Horn of
Africa countries. The plan was drafted by the United States and
Rwanda.
	   ``The peace recommendations by the United States and Rwanda
constitute a reasonable basis for a peaceful resolution for the
conflict,'' Rice told journalists in Ouagadougou.
	   She urged both sides to accept the peace plan before fresh
rounds of fighting blow up into full scale war.
	   The plan calls for the withdrawal of troops, the deployment of
observers in the disputed border regions, the return of civilian
administrations to the region and an inquiry into the cause of the
dispute.
	   ``We are very concerned about the escalation and fighting
between Ethiopia and Eritrea and we request both sides to respect
an immediate cease-fire,'' she said.
	   The African foreign ministers issued an urgent appeal Saturday
for Ethiopia and Eritrea to adopt the U.S.-Rwandan peace plan and
curb their mounting use of violence.
	   ``The Council of Ministers appeals to the two parties to put an
end to all hostilities,'' a joint statement said.
	   The growing conflict will likely dominate talks between OAU
heads of state who begin meetings Monday.
