<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More shelling, more dead in Kosovo in attack with military planes, Albanian sources issuing list of Decani missing; Ischinger and Rugova quotes, central European and Balkan countries condemning Kosovo violence at meeting in Brioni, Croatia; trims 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: AMs. UPDATES with three more ethnic Albanians reported wounded
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Dozens of houses were aflame and
Serb gunners kept shelling villages in Kosovo, where another four
people were killed in fighting, ethnic Albanian and Serb sources
said Saturday.
	   The Kosovo Information Center close to the Albanian leadership
said fighting continued Saturday in the Decani area, some 70
kilometers (45 miles) west of provincial capital Pristina. The
villages of Shaptej, Gramocel and Babaloc were targeted by the
Serbs' heavy artillery.
	   One three-year old child, identified as Leutrim Aga, was killed
sleeping in his bed in Gramocel and three more ethnic Albanians
were wounded in that village. Another ethnic Albanian was found
dead in nearby Babaloc.
	   The Center later claimed three more were wounded in another
Decani village, Prilep, in a Serb attack involving military planes.
None of the reports could be independently confirmed.
	   The Center also issued a list of 202 names of people missing
after the latest clashes in the Decani region.
	   It said Serbian forces were shelling a border strip west of
Djakovica, 75 kilometers (47 miles) southwest of Pristina.
	   Serbian sources said two men were killed in a border clash
between Serb-led Yugoslav army troops and an armed group attempting
to illegally enter the province from Macedonia Saturday. They were
the first dead at the Macedonian border.
	   A Serb policemen was also reported to have died in the Belgrade
military hospital of injuries sustained in previous fighting in
Kosovo.
	   Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people
and demand independence from Serbia, the larger of two republics
remaining in Yugoslavia.
	   A group of 16 central European and Balkan countries meeting
Saturday on Brioni island, Croatia, condemned violence and all
forms of terrorism in embattled Kosovo.
	   Speaking to reporters on Brioni, Ilir Meta, Albania's state
secretary for European integration, repeated his government's calls
for outside assistance to cope with the continuing influx of Kosovo
refugees.
	   Meanwhile, German foreign ministry official Wolfgang Ischinger,
touring the Balkans, met with ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova
in the provincial capital Pristina.
	   Ischinger told reporters his visit was part of an international
effort to help ``de-escalate the present crisis, to end military
action... and help refugees return.''
	   He spoke of ``ethnic cleansing'' _ the policy of forcefully
driving out ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, saying that was ``a
complete disaster, totally unacceptable.''
	   Ischinger was later scheduled to travel to Belgrade for meetings
with top government officials.
	   Rugova pleaded for ``urgent international intervention to stop
the Serb forces' aggression,'' insisting peaceful means were ``the
best way for achieving Kosovo's independence.''
	   However, Serbia is totally opposed to Kosovo's independence and
so are foreign powers, while the Kosovo Liberation Army rejects a
peaceful solution and is fighting toward secession from Serbia.
	   On Friday, the United Nations, in an unusually strong statement,
accused Serbian forces of atrocities in Kosovo where more than 250
people have died since March 1, in escalating clashes between
government forces and the KLA, the armed wing of the Albanian
independence movement.
	   In the Decani offensive this week, ethnic Albanian sources
earlier reported 50 dead, 200 missing and several villages
destroyed. There were also unconfirmed reports of a mass grave
containing 300 bodies.
	   Most of western Kosovo remained sealed-off Saturday, and it was
impossible to verify the conflicting reports.
	   More than 10,000 Kosovo Albanian refugees fled to northern
Albania this week.
	   (ih/str/kk/rp)
</TEXT>
