<HEADER>
w2551 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-TrainDerails 6thLd-Writethru   06-06 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
As search for bodies ends, train crash rescuers face the tragedy inspections on all ICE trains of the type that crashed; Trims HBG108,105,107 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: AMs; UPDATES with federal rail authority ordering new
AP Photos ESC101-102,107,111, TLK108,109, MUN101, FRA108,
By TONY CZUCZKA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ESCHEDE, Germany (AP) _ Federal rail officials on Saturday
ordered a second round of inspections of Germany's original fleet
of high-speed trains, showing their strengthening belief that a
wheel problem caused the nation's deadliest postwar train crash.
	   The death toll rose to 102 Saturday after rescuers digging by
hand through a sandbank found four more victims. Five of the
victims died in hospitals after Wednesday's crash in the town of
Eschede, 50 kilometers (30 miles) north of Hanover.
	   Investigators said a broken wheel on the first passenger car
appears to have caused InterCity Express 884 to derail and slam
into a motorway bridge.
	   Inspectors will check the wheels with ultrasound equipment,
searching for defects, and measure the thickness of the outer steel
rim _ the part that broke off the wheel of the crashed train. The
first inspections were done by eye, looking for visible defects.
	   ``Safety is always more important than cost effectiveness,''
Transport Minister Matthias Wissmann said in Eschede.
	   Officials estimate it will take two weeks to inspect all of the
59 trains that launched Germany's premier high-speed rail system,
inaugurated in 1991. A second generation of trains, introduced
since 1996, has a different wheel system.
	   Rail officials had already started general inspections of the
early InterCity Express trains. The new order means that a dozen
trains already checked will undergo a more thorough look.
	   Trains that pass inspection will be allowed to resume the normal
maximum speed _ 280 kilometers (175 miles) an hour. Top speed on
the trains was reduced to 160 kilometers (100 miles) an hour after
the accident.
	   Wissmann was quoted by the Neue Osnabruecke Zeitung as ruling
out a permanent speed reduction. However, he remained open to a
possible new safety system that would warn of wheel breaks and
derailments.
	   Meanwhile, a rescue effort that began with heavy cranes and
metal saws wound down Saturday with searchers sifting through sand
by hand to avoid any further damage to bodies mangled in the wreck.
	   The last bodies found were in a sandbank where the 200-ton
concrete bridge crumbled on the tracks after the train smashed into
its supports.
	   All recovered bodies were taken to a hospital morgue in Hanover,
where doctors catalog distinguishing features _ teeth, scars,
moles, facial hair, jewelry. Then they match their records with
information from relatives.
	   The process has been slow, with some bodies so mutilated that
dental records fail to help, and by Saturday only 29 victims had
been identified.
	   (cb-tsc) 	   
</TEXT>
