<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 8th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopian jets bomb airport, outskirts of Eritrean capital acknowledges that Eritrea downed one of its planes Saturday; Ethiopia to provide security ``window'' for evacuation flights; EDITS; no pickup 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: AMS. UPDATES with Ethiopia says it downed Eritrean jet Friday;
AP Photos planned
By JULIA STEWART
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea _ Ethiopian jet fighters bombed a combined
military-civilian airport in Eritrea for the second day Saturday as
hundreds of foreigners scrambled to leave the country.
	   There was no information available on casualties.
	   President Isaias Afwerki said he held out little hope for a
rapid solution to the worsening border conflict between the two
impoverished nations in the Horn of Africa.
	   Eritrea said it shot down one of the Ethiopian MiG 23
fighter-bombers Saturday and captured pilot Col. Bezabeh Petros.
	   Ethiopia denied it had lost any planes Friday during a raid on
Asmara airport.
	   A reliable source in the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry said
Ethiopia had shot down an Eritrean MiG over northeastern Ethiopia
Friday and captured the pilot.
	   ``At the moment, I'm not seeing any light at the end of the
tunnel,'' President Isaias Afwerki told reporters. ``But when I see
it, I want peace.''
	   A source familiar with the Eritrean Air Force, who asked not to
be further identified, said it was clear Ethiopia was trying to
wipe out Eritrea's small air force consisting of half a dozen aging
Soviet-era MiG fighter-bombers.
	   Isaias, however, said he didn't think the air raids represented
``a great escalation'' in hostilities because the Ethiopians ``have
already taken much more significant actions.''
	   He did not elaborate.
	   Ethiopia's army is about three times the size of Eritrea's
estimated 40,000-strong force.
	   Meanwhile in the Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa, diplomats from
Italy, Germany, Britain and the United States met Saturday with
Prime Minister Meles Zenawi, who told them Ethiopia would provide a
security ``window'' between 5 p.m. (1400gmt) Saturday and 6 a.m.
(0300gmt) Sunday to allow airplanes to land in Asmara to evacuate
their citizens, according to Italian Ambassador Marcello Ricoveri.
	   A U.S.-charter aircraft carrying 194 people, including 129
Americans, arrived in Frankfurt, Germany, early Saturday after
leaving Asmara Friday night.
	   Ethiopia said the Friday attack on the airport was in
retaliation an Eritrean attack on Mekele, 200 kilometers (125
miles) north of Addis. At least 44 Ethiopians civilians were killed
and 135 wounded in the Mekele attack, according to Radio Fana of
the Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front.
	   There was no explanation for Saturday's attack.
	   Eritrea and Ethiopia are at odds over at least six areas along
their common border which was traced by Italy after it conquered
Eritrea in 1885.
	   The Friday air strikes came a day after Meles agreed to a U.S.
and Rwandan proposal to end the border conflict peacefully.
	   But he warned that his country's patience was wearing thin
because of Eritrea's refusal to withdraw from territory Ethiopia
claims it occupied a month ago.
	   One of the recommendations of the proposal was that Eritrea
withdraw to positions held before May 6.
	   But Eritrea says it has not violated the international border
traced by Italian colonizers in 1885.
	   Across the continent in Ouagadougu, capital of Burkina Faso,
foreign ministers from the Organization of African Unity Saturday
urged Ethiopia and Eritrea to refrain from the use of violence.
	   ``The Council of Ministers appeals to the two parties to put an
end to all hostilities,'' their statement said.
	   The growing conflict will likely dominate talks between OAU
heads of state who begin meetings Monday.
	   Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. Eritrean
rebels were instrumental in helping the EPRDF overthrow a 17-year
military regime in July 1991.
	   (pvs/sl)	   
</TEXT>
