<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Rugby-Zimbabwe-Wales,0319 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Welsh rugby team defeats Zimbabwe, 49-11 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Wales fielded three international
debutants against Zimbabwe Saturday, with Richard Rees scoring two
tries to set up a victory in the last 15 minutes.
	   The Welsh scored eight tries, five of them in a final blitz that
confounded Zimbabwe.
	   The others came from Byron Haywood (3), Arwell Thomas (2) and
Wayne Proctor.
	   A penalty and three conversions by Thomas completed the scoring.
Thomas replaced Neil Jenkins as kicker, falling short of Jenkins'
usual performance record so that some points went begging.
	   In the early part of the match Zimbabwe kept the Welshmen on the
back foot for lengthy periods, scoring first with a penalty by
Kenny Tsimba from 35 meters (38 yards) out.
	   Rees opened his account five minutes later, bursting through the
Zimbabwe line and brushing aside home full-back Victor Olonga.
	   Zimbabwe regained the lead 6-5 with another penalty by Tsimba,
Wales being guilty of off-side.
	   An easy Thomas try right on half-time, which he converted, gave
Wales a lead of 12-6. Just before the break, Wales lost Mark Taylor
with a facial injury and David Wheatherley with an injured right
knee from a tackle.
	   Tries from Thomas and Haywood, who benefited from six swift
passes down the line, gave Wales the comfortable margin of 20-6.
	   First time front row forward Darren Morris performed well
against an unusually aggressive Zimbabwe pack.
	   At the 63rd minute Zimbabwe kept the possibility of an upset
alive with a try by scrum-half Ryan Bekker, who nipped through an
embarrassed Wales defense after a tap penalty. That brought the
score back to 20-11.
	   But then came the final five Welsh tries.
	   Zimbabwe rugby has been troubled lately by allegations of white
favoritism and the resignation of team manager Fred Jocks. But
morale was high throughout. 	   
</TEXT>
