u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Golf-EnglishOp     06-06 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-English Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Westwood takes lead; Australian Chalmers in second after 61 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   WARE, England (AP) _ Lee Westwood finished with three birdies on
the final four holes to take a one-stroke lead Saturday over
Australian Greg Chalmers after three rounds of the English Open.
	   A 24-year-old lefthander, Chalmers shot an 11-under,
course-record 61 and had a chance for a 59 _ which would have been
a record for the European Tour.
	   Billed as Europe's best young player, Westwood finished with a
5-under 67 as he attempts to win his second straight European Tour
event. He won last week's TPC of Europe championship in Hamburg,
Germany.
	   Westwood was in at 13-under 203 with Chalmers on 204 on the
par-72 Marriott Hanbury Manor course.
	   Colin Montgomerie fired a 69 to fall two shots off the pace
joined by Stephen Leaney of Australia (70) and Patrik Sjoland of
Sweden (70).
	   The 61 still found a place in the European Tour record books.
	   His 28 on the front nine was one short of tying the European
Tour record of 27 for nine holes, which is held by several players.
	   Chalmers' 61 was technically the third-best round ever shot on
the the European Tour. There have been eight rounds of 60, but only
two of them _ by Jamie Spence in Switzerland in 1992 and Bernhard
Langer in Germany last year _ were on par-72 courses.
	   ``I thought about a 59 from the moment I chipped in for eagle on
the ninth,'' said Chalmers, had had four birdies and two eagles on
the front nine.
	   ``But I'll take 61. It's fantastic.''
	   ``It felt like I could do nothing wrong. It's frightening in a
way, but great as well. Things just happen, and it's weird because
you feel totally relaxed, yet your heart is racing. It doesn't
happen often enough.''
	   Chalmers, after making the turn in 28, birdied the 10th, 12th
and 14th and needed two more birdies on the final four holes to
reach 59.
	   He had pars on 15 and 16. On the par-5 17th, he hit missed a
four-foot birdie putt. On the 18th his only hope of 59 was dropping
a 100-yard wedge shot for eagle. The shot was well wide and he
settled for par.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
