</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
King Hussein says Arab divisions are blocking proposed summit 
</HEADLINE>
By JAMAL HALABY
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Divisions stemming from the 1990-91 Gulf
Crisis are blocking a bid to hold an Arab summit, Jordan's King
Hussein said Saturday.
	   Arab governments have been unable to agree on a date, an agenda,
and the participants for a summit on the stalled Middle East peace
process, the king told some 150 journalists in his hilltop palace
in Amman.
	   ``The summit is hampered by some obstacles related to the period
of 1990-91, which must be vanquished,'' Hussein said, referring
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, which divided Arabs into a pro-Iraqi
camp and an anti-Iraqi one.
	   Arab diplomats say several Gulf Arab states are opposed to
inviting Iraq to the summit. At the same time, Syria is opposed to
the presence of Jordan and the Palestinians as it condemns their
separate peace treaties with Israel.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has called for the summit to
rally support for his position in the peace process, which has
foundered on Israel's rejection of a U.S. proposal for an Israeli
troop withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
	   The Palestinians accept the proposal, but Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has offered no more than a 9 percent pull back.
	   The king said there were forces within Israeli society that were
pushing the country toward ``going back to the fortress and hiding
behind its walls, giving the impression that this will ensure their
safety and security.''
	   ``We have to resist this policy and this inclination,'' he said
in what was seen as an implicit criticism of Netanyahu.
	   He called on Netanyahu to implement the Israeli-Palestinian
accords, which call for a withdrawal from the West Bank, ``to the
spirit and the letter.''
	   Failure to do so ``will have negative results,'' he warned.
	   Hussein repeatedly pledged his support to Arafat and his
administration in what appeared to be a reply to suggestions that
the king favors the radical Palestinian movement Hamas.
	   ``Our support to the Palestinian Authority is a sacred duty,''
said Hussein. The authority ``is the only side responsible for the
Palestinian people and we do not advocate any alternatives and will
not allow that.''
	   Turning to Jordanian affairs, Hussein defended a controversial
press bill, saying it would increase press freedom and was not a
step back from the liberalization process introduced in 1989.
	   The draft law, which parliament is expected to debate soon,
increases 30 fold the amount a journalist can be fined for
infringing a vague definition of state security. It also obliges
reporters to divulge their sources in court.
 &UR; jjh-jbm
</TEXT>
