w2589 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd-Writethru   06-06 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0709 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More shelling, more dead in Kosovo reported wounded in attack involving military planes, Albanian sources issuing list of Decani missing; Ischinger and Rugova quotes, central European and Balkan countries condemning Kosovo violence at meeting in Brioni, Croatia; trims 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with three more ethnic Albanians
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Dozens of houses were aflame and
Serb gunners kept shelling villages in Kosovo, where another four
people were killed in fighting, ethnic Albanian and Serb sources
said Saturday.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, which is close to the ethnic
Albanian leadership in the Serbian province, said fighting
continued Saturday in the Decani area, about 70 kilometers (45
miles) west of the provincial capital, Pristina. The villages of
Shaptej, Gramocel and Babaloc were targeted by the Serbs' heavy
artillery, it said.
	   Meanwhile, German foreign ministry official Wolfgang Ischinger,
touring the Balkans, met with ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova
in Pristina.
	   Ischinger said his visit was part of an international effort to
help ``de-escalate the present crisis, to end military action ...
and help refugees return.''
	   He spoke of ``ethnic cleansing'' _ the policy of forcefully
driving out ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, saying it was ``a
complete disaster, totally unacceptable.''
	   Ischinger was scheduled to travel on to Belgrade for meetings
with top government officials.
	   Rugova pleaded for ``urgent international intervention to stop
the Serb forces' aggression,'' insisting that peaceful means were
``the best way for achieving Kosovo's independence.''
	   Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people
and demand independence from Serbia, the larger of two republics
remaining in Yugoslavia. Serbia is totally opposed to Kosovo's
independence and so are foreign powers, while the Kosovo Liberation
Army rejects a peaceful solution and is fighting for secession.
	   More than 250 people have died since March 1 in escalating
clashes between government forces and the KLA, the armed wing of
the Albanian independence movement. More than 10,000 Kosovo
Albanian refugees fled to northern Albania this week.
	   The United Nations, in an unusually strong statement Friday,
accused Serbian forces of atrocities in Kosovo
	   Most of western Kosovo remained sealed off Saturday, and it was
impossible to verify conflicting casualty reports.
	   A 3-year-old child, identified as Leutrim Aga, was killed as he
slept in his bed in Gramocel and three more ethnic Albanians were
wounded in that village. Another ethnic Albanian was found dead in
nearby Babaloc, the Kosovo Information Center said.
	   The Center also said that three more people were wounded in
another Decani village, Prilep, in a Serb attack involving military
planes. None of the reports could be independently confirmed.
	   The Center also issued a list of 202 names of people missing
after the latest clashes in the Decani region.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources earlier reported 50 dead, 200 missing
and several villages destroyed in the Decani region. There were
also unconfirmed reports of a mass grave containing 300 bodies.
	   The Center said Serbian forces were shelling a border strip west
of Djakovica, 75 kilometers (47 miles) southwest of Pristina.
	   Serbian sources said two men were killed in a border clash
between Serb-led Yugoslav army troops and an armed group attempting
to illegally enter the province from Macedonia on Saturday. They
were the first dead at the Macedonian border.
	   A Serb policemen was also reported to have died in the Belgrade
military hospital of injuries sustained in earlier fighting in
Kosovo.
	   A group of 16 central European and Balkan countries meeting
Saturday in Brioni, Croatia, condemned the violence and all forms
of terrorism in Kosovo.
	   Speaking to reporters in Brioni, Ilir Meta, Albania's state
secretary for European integration, repeated his government's call
for outside assistance to cope with the continuing influx of Kosovo
refugees.
</TEXT>
