w2597 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-AirlineStrike     06-06 0187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Airline Strike,0190 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Striking Aeromexico flight attendants reach accord 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Striking flight attendants for Mexico's
largest airline have reached an accord with the company, the
union's secretary-general said Saturday.
	   The Aeromexico flight attendants called a meeting Saturday to
vote on the accord, Secretary-General Alejandra Barrales told The
Associated Press. She expected approval of the accord.
	   The 1,033 unionized flight attendants went on strike a week ago
over salaries, work hours, benefits and the size of flight crews,
but since the government took over right away they never actually
walked off the job.
	   Mexico's constitution gives the government the right to
temporarily seize companies vital to the nation's economy or
security.
	   Barrales said the airline agreed to all their main concerns _ an
18.3 percent raise, one additional flight attendant on each flight,
extra pay for night work and the beginnings of a retirement plan.
	   If the flight attendants declare an end to their strike, the
government will hand operations back over to Aeromexico.
</TEXT>
