<SLUG> BC-Spain-Cruise Ship </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World's largest cruise ship ends maiden voyage 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo BAR101
By RICHARD SCHWEID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BARCELONA, Spain (AP) _ It might seem like a 12-day
Mediterranean cruise on the inaugural voyage of the world's largest
cruise ship would be pretty relaxing, considering the ship has five
swimming pools, a spa, a miniature nine-hole golf course, tennis
courts, a casino, three grand dining salons, seven less informal
restaurants, a theater and 12 bars.
	   The Grand Princess, 15 floors high (201 feet or 61.26 meters)
and 951 feet (289.86 meters) wide, towered over the harbor as it
docked Saturday in this northern Spain port, the last call on its
maiden voyage. It is twice as big as the Titanic.
	   Passenger Steve Epstein of Philadelphia said the voyage wasn't
all lounge chair laziness.
	   ``You start the day at 6 a.m. when you want to tour a city like
we did in Venice,'' he said. ``There's something to keep you busy
from the minute you wake up to a delicious breakfast, right through
the evening with entertainment like Alan King and Red Buttons.
There's not much time for just relaxing.''
	   Not that passengers couldn't relax if they wanted to: after all,
each of the ship's 1,296 cabins has its own little balcony where
passengers can sit and watch the sea. And, with a crew of over a
thousand, the 2,600 passengers on this trip had plenty of people
eager to make their journey a pleasant one.
	   ``I've taken numerous cruises, and this is the best in terms of
service and attention from the crew,'' said Helene Goss, from
Aventura, FL. ``They did a tremendous job.''
	   Helene, and her husband, Morton Goss, each paid about dlrs 3,000
for the cruise, not including air fare. They considered it a fair
price when compared with other cruise lines.
	   The ship, which belongs to Princess Cruises, cost about dlrs 450
million to build. Most passengers seemed satisfied with its maiden
voyage, but there were some dissenters on arrival in Barcelona.
	   One man, who wouldn't give his name, said he paid for a suite,
but had to wait a day and a half for the butler that came with it.
He said he wasn't happy with the food or the service, but expected
other passengers wouldn't complain because they were happy to be
part of a prestigious maiden voyage.
	   And most of the passengers, leaving the ship to board tour buses
that would take them around the city, expressed satisfaction with
the voyage that began on May 26 in Istanbul with stops in Athens
and Venice.
	   ``It has been an excellent voyage,'' said Linda Senado, from
Mexico City. ``My cabin was a little small, but overall I would
give it high ratings. The ship is almost too big, though. It's so
big, I didn't even discover the nine-hole miniature golf course
until yesterday.''
	   (rw/krt)
</TEXT>
