<HEADLINE>
Cuba's cigar chief says quality is not dropping 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Responding to criticism that the quality of
Cuban cigars is dropping as production booms, the head of Cuba's
government cigar producers says the stogies are as good as ever.
	   In an article by the government news agency Prensa Latina,
monitored in Mexico City, the head of Cuba's Union of Tabacco
Companies said Cuban cigars are works of art and that there are
enough quality checks to ensure their flavor.
	   Production grew 40 percent last year, and is expected to grow
another 60 percent this year, Francisco Linares Calvo said Friday.
	   That means the industry will make 160 million cigars for export,
which will net the companies dlrs 280 million _ a profit of dlrs
180 million, Prensa Latina said.
	   The world market for Cuban cigars has been growing strongly over
the past few years. Some aficionados have complained that quality
has been dropping as production increases.
</TEXT>
