<SLUG> BC-Cuba-US Migration,0238 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cuba says no special system for U.S. visa lottery applications 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Cuba said Saturday that it won't set up any
special mechanisms to help its citizens apply for a new U.S. visa
lottery, in which hundreds of thousands of Cubans are expected to
participate.
	   In a statement reported by the government's Prensa Latina news
agency and monitored in Mexico City, Cuba's post office said it
would not set up a special system.
	   It reminded Cubans that no post offices send mail directly to
diplomatic offices of the United States, but said people can send
applications through the normal mail.
	   The lottery, the third of its kind, was announced Friday in
Washington. It opens June 15, and winners are granted an interview
by U.S. consular officers.
	   Applicants must answer questions about their education, work
experience and relatives in the United States.
	   In the last lottery, in 1996, more than 436,000 applications
were received. In the first, in 1994, 190,000 people applied.
	   The visa lotteries were set up to end the ``boat people''
crisis, in which hundreds of thousands of Cubans set off for the
United States on often dangerous rafts.
	   The United States agreed to give out at least 20,000 visas a
year and to return any Cubans intercepted on the high seas. The
boat exodus diminished significantly after the decision.
</TEXT>
