<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Mountain of Death,0797 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One village mourns 1,200 people dead in earthquake 
</HEADLINE>
By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   DASHTAK, Afghanistan (AP) _ Standing in a line at the edge of
the sheared-off mountainside, a mullah and his congregation intoned
a final prayer for the more than 1,200 people of Dashtak who
perished in last week's devastating earthquake.
	   Many of the dead, including 140 children who were attending
school, were swept to their death in a powerful landslide that
poured down the mountain.
	   ''If you want to go into this place and get your wood, do it
now,'' the mullah said. ''After this, people cannot walk in this
area. It is a big cemetery now.''
	   The mountain village of Dashtak was the hardest hit by the May
29 quake. More than one-fifth of its people were killed and 600 of
its houses destroyed when the side of the mountain fell away.
	   Now it is a sea of gray rock and dust that cakes the skin.
	   The scale of the disaster at Dashtak, so remote that
international aid workers did not find it for days after it was
leveled by nature's wrath, gives credence to estimates that as many
as 5,000 people died in the catastrophe.
	   An Associated Press reporter accompanied the first aid flight
into Dashtak and spent two days on the mountain with the
traumatized villagers before trekking back down and hitching a ride
to Rostaq, the nearest town, 20 kilometers (12 miles) away.
	   Struggling to alleviate a vast human disaster spread over 100
villages in 700 square miles (1,815 square kilometers), the United
Nations and a half-dozen other charity agencies have just three
tiny helicopters to deliver supplies and evacuate the seriously
wounded.
	   In Dashtak, the schoolhouse, its pupils and six teachers are the
symbol of a community's suffering, compounded by the survivors'
inability to give their dead a proper burial.
	   Beside their memories of the fateful morning, villagers are
haunted by the stomach-churning aftershocks that shake the mountain
daily and deepen the cracks in the earth.
	   They beg for the most rudimentary things to survive: food, tents
and water. The quake struck the remote region in the morning, when
many men were working the fields.
	   ''I saw the earth boiling and then it was like a big explosion.
All the dust came up from the village, I thought everything had
been swallowed by the earth,'' said Abdul Mahmood, who watched from
a distance. By the time he reached his home, nothing was left. His
wife and five children were buried under the rubble.
	   In the neighboring village of Bekha, Saeed Omar was plowing a
hillside with his two cows when the tremor hit, throwing him and
the animals into the air and depositing them hundreds of meters
(yards) away.
	   ''All the area was covered with dust. I left my animals, rushed
toward the village, and dug out two people,'' Omar said.
	   Not a single family in Dashtak escaped the disaster. Villagers
pointed in every direction and recited their grim lists: 40 dead
here, 15 there, young shepherds and their flocks buried on the
slope across the way.
	   Sarwar, 33, who like many Afghans uses just one name, said he
lost his whole family.
	   ''They are all here, '' he said pointing over the side of the
mountain. ''My mother, my father, my children, my wife. All of them
are here under deep rubble. I have three children. I am working to
try to find them, but there is no way.''
	   People came from neighboring villages to try to dig out the
dead, especially the school children. They used shovels, bare
hands, anything they could, usually without result.
	   People have a few potatoes and some bread to eat, but most of
their animals have died and they have nothing other than
international aid to fortify them.
	   Their water supply from three rivers has been contaminated by
the landslides and survivors are succumbing to disease. Ruhullah,
an Afghan doctor working for a Swedish charity, said he was seeing
pneumonia, skin diseases, tuberculosis, malnutrition and malaria
among survivors.
	   Even the youngest have no faith that the future won't bring more
death, more destruction, more misery.
	   ''I lost my whole family. I am now wondering about my future,''
said 10-year-old Zibi Sah, hunched over with grief after the quake
carried away her father and three little brothers.
	   Many said they didn't want to stay in Dashtak any longer and
were waiting for the authorities to help them move.
	   Saif-ur Rehman, 55, said he was worried about his wife and
children since all the family's arable land had been washed away in
the landslide.
	   ''The earth is very hard and the sky is too far. We cannot go
anywhere.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Afghanistan-Mountain of Death; CT:i; 
