<HEADLINE>
   APTV 1800 OUTLOOK SATURDAY JUNE 6, 1998    For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the next 12 hours. All times are GMT.  ---- EXPECTED: ---- UN: NUCLEAR  - APTV covers the expected vote by the UN Security Council condemning India and Pakistan over their recent rounds of nuclear tests.  (First run expected North America 1830) ---- US: HOLOCAUST - Survivors of the Nazi Holocaust who were saved as children under a programme called 'Kindertransport' which ferried them out of Germany gather in Washington.  APTV has a feature on the survivors and their amazing stories.  (First Run expected North America Late 1930) ---- US: SKOREA - APTV covers the arrival of South Korean President Kim Dae-jung in New York for his nine-day visit to the U-S.  (F-L-A-S-H tba) ---- DENMARK: WEDDING - Denmark's Princess Alexandra of Berleburg, Queen Margrethe's niece, exchanges vows with German count, Jefferson Friederich von Pfeil und Klein-Ellgut.  A-P-T-V has the royal wedding ceremony.  (First Run expected North America 1830)  (No Access Denmark/Europe 2230G) ---- RUSSIA: MIR - APTV will have coverage of the daily news conference aboard the Russian space station Mir, with elements from mission control on the ground. (First Run expected North America 1830) ---- MEXICO: CATHEDRAL -  Mexico City's cathedral, the largest church in the Americas, is finally being set straight after years of sinking into moist clay.  Officials say they have saved the imposing church from collapse.  APTV looks at Mexico's own version of the Leaning Tower of Pisa. (First Run expected Latin America 1900) ---- BOLIVIA: JAIL - Television cameras have been granted a rare glimpse behind the bars of Bolivia's highest security prison, Chonchocoro. The prison - home to fallen politicians and leading drug lords - lies 35 kilometers outside the capital La Paz.  APTV takes an inside look at the prison home to some of Bolivia's most feared criminals. (First Run expected Latin America 1900) ---- PERU: MINISTER - APTV covers the swearing-in ceremony of Peru's new economic minister, Dr. Jorge Baca Campodonico.  (First Run expected Latin America 1900) ---- PERU: ENVIRONMENT - Hundreds of young school children demonstrated outside Lima to mark World Environment Day on Friday.  They gathered outside an endangered bird sanctuary in the area.  (First Run expected Latin America 1900) ---- RUNNING:  ---- ALBANIA: REFUGEES - APTV has pictures of the stream of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo fleeing over the hills to the safety of nearby Albania. (First Run F-L-A-S-H 1640) ---- LEBANON: ELECTIONS - Lebanon is set to hold the third round of its local elections on Sunday - the first municipal poll there in 35 years.   Local elections scheduled for 1969 were never held because of political tensions that eventually erupted in 1975 into the Lebanese civil war, which raged for 15 years.  Features scenes of preparations being made for the vote. (First Run Europe Late 1500) ---- SWEDEN: KING - Sweden's King Carl XVI Gustaf has celebrated the 25th anniversary of his ascension to the throne a bit early.  The ceremony at the royal palace in Stockholm was held earlier than the September 15 date to avoid stealing the show from the country's fall elections. (First Run Europe Late 1500) ---- ERITREA: WRAP - Celebrations are held in the capital of Asmara after an Ethiopian jet, which had been bombing the city, was shot down. Wraps with earlier elements of foreign nationals arriving in Frankfurt on a chartered flight evacuating them from the turmoil in the region.  (First Run Europe Update 1130/wrap Europe Late 1500) ---- FRANCE: WORLD CUP 2 - Previous scene-setting World Cup package from Paris and Marseille updated with fresh pictures from Lyon featuring preparations underway for the world's biggest sporting event. Despite the excitement, Lyon, the geographical hub of the largest-ever World Cup, appears untroubled at the prospect of the imminent football fever. (First Run Europe Update 1130) ---- IRAN: MAYOR - On Sunday, Tehran's mayor Gholamhossein Karabaschi goes on trial on charged of corruption.  In hardline Iran, Karabaschi gained huge popularity with his moderate views and ideas. APTV previews his trial, which is being seen as the latest round in the power struggle between Islamic hardliners and the moderate supporters of President Khatami.  (First Run APTV Eurovision Window 1440) ---- TURKEY: CRASH LANDING - 163 passengers and crew of a French airliner had a lucky escape after their plane's landing gear failed soon after it took off for Paris from Turkey.  The A-O-M jet skidded down the runway at Antalya airport in a shower of sparks.  (First Run Europe Update 1130) ---- KOSOVO: SCHUESSEL - Wolfgang Schuessel, Austria's Foreign Minister, arrived in Pristina to try to bring Serbs and ethnic Albanians in the troubled province to the negotiating table.  He came after a week that saw increased tensions and a flood of refugees fleeing to nearby Albania. (First Run Europe Update 1130) ---- CAMBODIA: KHMER - Over one-thousand Khmer Rouge fighters have switched sides, trading in their guerrilla gear for official Cambodian army uniforms.  It was a scene long thought unimaginable at Anlong Veng, the rebels' stronghold until its recent capture by the army with the help of Khmer Rouge defectors.  (First Run Americas 0900) ---- THAILAND: DOG - With the help of an American high school student, a stray dog, crippled by a speeding taxi, will soon get medical treatment in the United States. APTV has the story. (First Run Americas 0900) ---- ---- Editor of the Day: 44 171 427 4163 Master Control Room - 44 171 427 4131 ---- APTV 
