<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Italy,0565 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Baggio is a happy man, likely to start against Chile 
</HEADLINE>
By PIERO VALSECCHI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Roberto Baggio is a happy man these days.
	   Richer with a newly signed prestigious contract with Inter
Milan, the imaginative Italian soccer veteran is expected to start
in Italy's World Cup opener against Chile.
	   ``Life can begin anew at 31 of age. I'm happy to be here and
ready to help the team to go as far as possible in the
tournament,'' Baggio said.
	   ``I'm ready to play. It's up to coach (Cesare) Maldini to take
decisions,'' he added.
	   Baggio, who earned a last-minute berth on Italy's World Cup team
thanks to the 22 goals scored with low-ranked Bologna, is likely to
be in the starting 11 at Bordeaux next Thursday as a substitute of
Alessandro Del Piero.
	   Baggio is starting in his third World Cup. In the two previous
editions he helped Italy to earn a third place in 1990 and a second
spot in 1994.
	   Del Piero, the young star-forward who replaced Baggio at
Juventus and on the national team, is recovering from a right this.
	   Baggio, who signed a two-year contract with Inter before flying
to France Friday, said he was looking forward to playing with
Brazilian star Ronaldo next season.
	   ``We look like a dangerous, powerful duo,'' Baggio said. ``But
it will be tough, because everybody will be expecting great things
from us. For the time being we must think of the World Cup, on
rival sides,'' Baggio said.
	   Baggio, who will get about dlrs 2.5 million a year from Inter,
said he considered Brazil the best World Cup team and the favorite
to win the title.
	   From the Brazilian training center Ronaldo made it known that he
considered Baggio's transfer to Inter a boost to the Milan club and
chances of winning the league title and the Champions Cup next
season.
	   On different teams, Ronaldo and Baggio combined for 47 goals in
the just concluded Italian Serie A.
	   Coach Maldini said the Italian team was not yet at 100 percent
but added it was improving day after day.
	   ``We are getting quicker and have great motivations for the
match with Chile. The first match is crucial for qualification to
the next round,'' the Italian coach said.
	   He disclosed that he planned to have Fabio Cannavaro and
Alessandro Nesta marking closely Chile's strikers Marcelo Salas and
Ivan Zamorano.
	   The defensive duo will be tested in Sunday's friendly against a
French regional selection along with Inter's offensive midfielder
Francesco Moriero.
	   Baggio will team in front with Christian Vieri, the Italian
striker of Atletico Madrid who has recovered from stomach problems.
	   The regional selection was picked by Italian officials to
replace the original opponent, the local amateur team.
	   (pv-sl)
</TEXT>
