<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Military Service </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudanese students enrol for controversial military service 
</HEADLINE>
By MOHAMED OSMAN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ With their mothers wailing, hundreds of
Sudanese students climbed into trucks in Khartoum's main square
Saturday to start their military service.
	   In what is the first intake of 1998, some 90,000 high school
students are expected to report for training in the next few days.
	   Their enlistment comes days after President Omar el-Bashir
ordered a general mobilization following a rebel victory in
southeast Sudan.
	   The Sudan Peoples' Liberation Army announced Tuesday that it had
taken the garrison town of Ulu, 455 kilometers (280 miles)
southeast of Khartoum.
	   On Saturday, the head of Sudan's only legal political party,
Mutasim Abdul-Rahim, issued a statement urging ``all those who are
able to carry a gun to join the (military training) camps and move
to the operational zones to defend the gains of the homeland.''
	   ``Jihad (holy war) has now become an obligation that comes
before any other duty,'' Abdul-Rahim said.
	   The training program, which can include deploying the students
in the war zones of southern and eastern Sudan, has been highly
controversial.
	   In April, 52 conscripts drowned in the Blue Nile when their boat
capsized as they fled a camp southeast of Khartoum. Opposition
groups said the death toll was was much higher _ at least 129 _ and
the incident generated widespread criticism of the conscription of
students.
	   But the government has decreed that students have to fufill
their national service in order to obtain the certificates required
for entrance to university.
	   In April, el-Bashir said his government plans to recruit 655,000
students over three years for the war against rebels.
	   The SPLA is fighting for more autonomy for the predominantly
Christian and animist southerners from the Islamic north. More than
1.3 million people have died in the war and consequent famines.
 &UR; mo-bm-jbm
</TEXT>
