<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Croatia-Australia,0366 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Croatia 7, Australia 0 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Davor Suker scored three goals Saturday
as Croatia trounced Australia 7-0 in its last warmup match before
the World Cup.
	   The victory prompted outbursts of delight throughout the capital
of Zagreb as people sounded horns and screamed joyfully.
	   Although Australia did not qualify for the World Cup, the result
_ the best in Croatia's eight-year history _ certainly boosts its
confidence. Its previous biggest margin of victory came in a 7-1
rout of Estonia.
	   The first goal came already in the 14th minute, when Suker hit a
penalty kick after Australia's goalkeeper Zeljko Kalac earned a
yellow card for a foul on Mario Stanic.
	   Suker scored again in the 37th minute, and only three minutes
later, Robert Prosinecki made it 3-0. Team captain Zvonimir Boban
netted in the 47th minute.
	   In the 63rd, Suker scored his third goal of the match and then
left the game. His substitute, Ardian Kozniku, wasted no time in
scoring goal No. 6 in the 72nd minute. Boban finished the rout with
his second goal in the closing minutes.
	   The victory gives Croatia some momentum after a 2-1 loss to
Slovakia last week.
	   The team is also playing without Alen Boksic, one of its top
strikers, who has been ruled out of the World Cup with a knee
injury. Another striker, Igor Cvitanovic, was sent home by the
coach Miroslav Ciro Blazevic for refusing to run laps in practice.
	   Blazevic subsequently listed only four strikers on his final
roster, putting his highest hopes in Suker.
	   The team departs for France on Monday.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Lineups:
	   Croatia_Drazen Ladic (Marijan Mrmic, 46th), Davor Suker (Ardian
Kozniku, 64th), Zoran Mamic, Aljosa Asanovic (Krunoslav Jurcic
46th), Zvonimir Soldo (Goran Juric, 4th), Zvonimir Boban, Mario
Stanic (Silvio Maric, 46th), Robert Prosinecki, Igor Stimac, Dario
Simic.
	   Australia_Zeljko Kalac, Marc Viduka, Alex Tobin, Craig Foster,
Ned Zelic, Brett Emerton, Tony Popovic, Mark Babic, John Aloisi
(Nick Rizzo 74th), Josip Skoko (Ross Aloisi, 79th), Fausto De
Amicis.
	   (sv/jw) 	   
