u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-Eritrea-Ethiopi     06-06 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Eritrea-Ethiopia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian president appeals for halt; negotiation offer 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia
By FRANCES D'EMILIO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italy's president on Saturday, appealing for an
immediate halt to what he called the ``absurd'' conflict between
Eritrea and Ethiopia, offered to help mediate the dispute.
	   The African nations, which were one until Eritrea gained
independence in 1993, are at odds over at least six areas along
their border which was traced by Italy after it conquered Eritrea
in 1895.
	   President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro added that Rome had furnished
maps and documents describing the border.
	   In a message to the presidents of both African countries,
Italy's head of state noted that during his visit to the Ethiopian
and Eritrean capitals last fall, both sides seemed to be
cooperating for progress.
	   ``It's thus with surprise and dismay that we are witnessing
today border battles, air strikes that hit innocent civilians
victims, the language of war and retaliation,'' Scalfaro wrote.
	   ``The indications of both sides are that the border is commonly
recognized and that there are no claims to change it,'' Scalfaro
said, adding ``all that is happening is thus absurd under every
aspect.''
	   Saying continued conflict risks ``compromising for decades to
come'' the prospects for development in the countries, among the
world's poorest, Scalfaro called for immediate halt to the
hostilities.
	   An Italian envoy, headed for Monday's meeting of the
Organization of African Unity in Burkina Faso, was willing to help
start talks, Scalfaro added.
	   ``Italy is ready to help you ... so that you can start
negotiations on all aspects upon which you must resume the path of
understanding and collaboration,'' Scalfaro said.
	   Italy has strong ties with its former colony. Many Italians run
businesses there and scores of Italian priests and nuns are
missionaries there.
	   Earlier, the Italian foreign ministry indicated two Italian
military C-130s would start flying out some 150 Italians late
Saturday night from Asmara to Djibouti.
	   The evacuation was arranged after Italian and other Western
diplomats arranged for an 13-hour safety ``window'' for Asmara
airport, with Ethiopian guaranteeing it would not target the
aircraft.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Italy-Eritrea-Ethiopia; CT:i; 
