<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Chile,0371 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Salas and Zamorano ready to face Italy 
</HEADLINE>
By SERGIO CARRASCO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MARIGNAC, France (AP) - The 23 goals that Marcelo Salas and Ivan
Zamorano scored in qualifying games are ancient history. ``What
counts now it the ones we will score in the World Cup,'' beginning
with Italy, Salas declared.
	   Salas, bought recently by Italy's Lazio for dlrs 20 million,
scored 11 goals and Zamorano, from Internazionale of Milan, added
12. Together, they scored as many goals as Argentina, the winner of
the South American qualifying tournament.
	   ``We both have the goal in our blood,'' Zamorano said.
	   Both strikers spoke in the first press conference offered by the
Chilean team since its arrival in Bordeaux.
	   ``It's good for Chile that we can play together,'' Salas said.
	   Chilean coach Nelson Acosta knows those two players are crucial
to his team's success.
	   ``We have a balanced team. If one player gets injured, we have
another. But I would worry a lot if something happened to Zamorano
or Salas,'' Acosta stated.
	   When reminded of the shower of goals scored in the qualifying
round, Salas said that ``they don't count now. What counts is the
goals that we will score against Italy, Austria and Cameroon,''
Chile's opponents in the first round.
	   ``We want to reach the second round, that is our aim. Whatever
comes after that, it will be a windfall,'' Salas said.
	   Teammate Fabian Estay said that Chile ``wants to make history in
this World Cup, after an absence of 16 years.''
	   Estay seems to have assumed the key position of playmaker,
relegating Jose Luis Sierra to the bench.
	   ``Zamorano and I know each other by heart. And with Salas is
very easy to play. To be honest, it's a real luxury to count with
such good strikers. It makes my job as playmaker much easier,''
Estay said.
	   Zamorano, who is 31, said that although he hopes ``to be in
another World Cup, I will play this one as if it were the last
one.''
	   Salas future is more open. He is only 23 and will join Lazio
once the World Cup is over, after becoming an international star
with Argentina's River Plate.
</TEXT>
