<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Banker,0356 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican banker returned from Spain arrested, freed 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A flashy banker recently extradited to Mexico
for allegedly swindling banks out of millions of dollars was
arrested for eight hours, then freed.
	   Angel Rodriguez Saez _ known as ``El Divino,'' or ``The Divine
One'' _ is charged with fiscal fraud and violating banking laws for
allegedly swindling banks out of an amount that reports put
anywhere from dlrs 4 million to dlrs 400 million.
	   He fled to Spain in 1994 after banking scandals rocked Mexico.
Spanish police arrested him in July 1996 after he dove off his
yacht into the Mediterranean trying to elude them. He was
extradited to Mexico on June 1 and was due in court again Monday.
No trial date has been set
	   His lawyers obtained court papers preventing him from being
arrested, but authorities detained him Friday after he appeared at
a hearing.
	   They held him for eight hours, saying he had failed to appear
before a judge on Tuesday, as he is required to do every week,
local news media reported.
	   Finally, a judge ruled that the attorney general's office had
misinterpreted the ruling and Rodriguez Saez had not been required
to check in Tuesday.
	   He was freed later Friday, saying he had been mistreated during
his detention, suffering injuries to his knee and testicles.
	   Rodriguez Saez built a financial empire during Mexico's banking
privatization in the early 1990s. Shortly after he left Mexico,
regulatory authorities seized his bank, Banpais, after discovering
capital shortfalls and bookkeeping irregularities.
	   Spanish authorities agreed to his extradition in February and
Rodriguez Saez dropped his objections two months later.
	   Rodriguez Saez was the first major player in Mexico's 1994
banking and political scandals to be returned home.
	   Mexican officials have failed to win extradition of former
Assistant Attorney General Mario Ruiz Massieu from the United
States, while financier Carlos Cabal Peniche _ the most important
figure in the 1994 banking scandals _ is still at large.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Banker; CT:i; 
