<SLUG> BC-Panama-Polls,0141 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Panama throws out law regulating opinion polls 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) _ Panama's Election Tribunal has thrown
out a new law regulating opinion polls that news media called a
violation of freedom of the press, a newspaper reported Saturday.
	   The law, which took effect May 20, forced news media to register
any opinion polls with the Election Tribunal, and banned them from
publishing them unless the tribunal gave them authorization,
according to El Panama America.
	   El Panama America filed a complaint before the Supreme Court on
May 28 calling the law unconstitutional. The Interamerican Press
Society sent a letter to the tribunal calling the law restrictive.
	   The tribunal said news media still have to file their polls with
the tribunal within three days of their publication.
</TEXT>
