<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Monument </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Monument unveiled for victims of helicopter crash 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   PROKOSKO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ International officials
unveiled a monument on Saturday at the site of a helicopter crash
that killed twelve of their colleagues traveling in a peace mission
last September.
	   Senior German diplomat Gerd Wagner, a deputy to top peace
mediator Carlos Westendorp of Spain, was killed in the crash. Also
killed were five Americans, four Germans, a Briton and a Pole.
	   Wagner's successor, Hanns Schumacher, unveiled the stone pyramid
along with the head of the United Nations mission to Bosnia,
Elisabeth Rehn. The ceremony was attended by the victims' families.
	   The names of all twelve victims were carved in the stone of the
monument near this picturesque village in central Bosnia.
	   The Ukrainian four-member crew survived but all passengers were
killed in the accident on Sept. 17, 1997.
	   The delegation led by Wagner was en route to Muslim-controlled
Bugojno, about 90 kilometers (55 miles) northwest of Sarajevo, to
encourage the continued return of ethnic Croat refugees.
	   The helicopter ran into thick fog about 20 minutes after takeoff
and smashed into a mountainside. The crew managed to escape through
the shattered glass nose of the craft but was hindered from helping
passengers because of fire and thick smoke.
	   Westendorp's other deputy, U.S. Ambassador Jacques Klein, said
in a speech on Saturday the death of his colleagues was an
obligation to ``finish the work they began.
	   ``They have given their lives for the noblest of causes _ for
peace,'' he added.
	   (ab/ac/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
