<HEADLINE>
Arantxa's dog is a Roland Garros regular 
</HEADLINE>
By STEPHANIE VAN DEN BERG
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ After her win over Monica Seles in the women's
final Saturday, Sanchez Vicario climbed up to the players' box to
hug her family, her coaches and her Yorkshire terrier.
	   The dog, named Roland, after Roland Garros, has his own stadium
pass and goes to all of his owner's matches, accompanied by
Arantxa's mother.
	   By now, he's a veteran of the French Open. He's been here 10
years. That's 70 in dog years.
	   ``He knows all the spots, he knows all the places. He's friendly
with all the people,'' said Sanchez Vicario. ``I mean, obviously he
enjoys it here a lot too.''
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   NAMES TO NOTE:
	   Remember these names: Juan Carlos Ferrero and Fernado Gonzalez.
The Spaniard and the Chilean are playing the boy's singles final at
the French Open on Sunday.
	   It's always a good idea to keep track of the junior winners,
because they often come back with a vengeance in the men's
tournament.
	   This year, 1995 junior French Open champion Mariano Zabaleta of
Argentina caused a stir when he beat No. 2 seed Petr Korda in the
first round.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   SOCCER FAN: Brazilian soccer star Ronaldo has turned a few heads
at the French Open. Teen star Anna Kournikova went out to the
stands to meet him at a fourth-round match between Cedric Pioline
and Marat Safin.
