<HEADLINE>
editing. Teammates vie for Romario's spot on Brazilian team 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with four grafs on team meeting with Edmundo; minor
By PETER MUELLO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   OZOIR LA FERRIERE, France (AP) _ Romario is gone, and the battle
is on for his place in Brazil's starting lineup.
	   For now, Bebeto is the No. 2 striker, alongside Ronaldo. But
Edmundo openly says he deserves the job, and Denilson could upstage
them both once the Cup starts next Wednesday.
	   The rivalry is a problem for coach Mario Zagallo. While he
encourages healthy competition among his players, the dispute has
created rifts that veterans say could weaken the group.
	   The disharmony was Edmundo's doing. In an interview Friday with
a Rio de Janeiro radio station, Edmundo said he deserved to start
because he was ``in better physical and technical shape, and
overall I'm better than Bebeto.''
	   The comment created turmoil at training camp and drew a sharp
reply from the high command. Team coordinator Zico said no one
would be allowed to disrupt the group, and Zagallo added that if
there were disciplinary problems among his 22 players, Brazil could
easily ``finish the Cup with 21.''
	   Defender Roberto Carlos said on Saturday that the players had
rebuked Edmundo for the interview.
	   ``We made it clear to him that nobody has the right to make
trouble for the team,'' Roberto Carlos said. The proper channel for
complaints is to air them personally with Zagallo, he said.
	   Edmundo excused himself before the group. ``He told us he meant
to say he was ready to play,'' Roberto Carlos said.
	   The problem is, Edmundo may be entirely right.
