<HEADLINE>
Two men sentenced in 1994 slaying of Guatemalan court president 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) _ Two men were sentenced to 25 years in
prison each for the 1994 assassination of the president of
Guatemala's highest constitutional court, the judge announced
Saturday.
	   Marlon Oliver Salazar Lopez and Roberto Antonio Trabanino Vargas
were sentenced in 1996 to 12 years each, but an appeals court
overturned the sentence and ordered a new trial.
	   Judge Ruben Anibal Delgado Paz didn't say when he issued the new
sentences.
	   Epaminondas Gonzalez Dubon was killed in a drive-by shooting on
April 1, 1994, blocks from his home in Guatemala City as he
returned with his wife, Wendy.
	   The previous year, he had condemned the May 1993 attempt by
then-president Jorge Serrano Elias to suspend the constitution.
