w2681 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Albania-GunsandPoliti     06-06 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Guns and Politics,0541 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Once disgraced leader finds opportunity in Kosovo crisis 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo
AP Photo BHA101
By BRIAN MURPHY
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ A flurry of arms looting last year began
former Albanian President Sali Berisha's tumble from power. The
weapons _ and the fighting in Kosovo, where many of them are being
used _ could now figure in his strategy for a political comeback.
	   Berisha's power base in northern Albania is the conduit for
automatic rifles, mortars and other guerrilla-type weapons reaching
ethnic Albanian separatists in the neighboring Serbian province of
Kosovo. The arms are lugged across the rugged border by hand and by
mule.
	   Some diplomats are drawing a clearer link between the convoys
and Berisha's own battles against Prime Minister Fatos Nano, though
they have yet to accuse Berisha of orchestrating the illicit arms
trade.
	   The arms traffic puts needed money in the pockets of Berisha's
hard-core political backers while making Nano's government appear
unable to control the northeastern frontier, diplomats said. At the
same time, Berisha can portray himself as a champion of Albanian
nationalism and the outgunned Kosovo Liberation Army, militants
seeking independence for the province.
	   Internal unrest in Albania, touched off by the fighting in
Kosovo, could offer Berisha and his allies an opening to climb back
into power, diplomats speculated. This is an alarming prospect for
many European leaders, who have repeatedly urged Berisha to end
anti-government ``agitation'' since his election defeat in June
1997.
	   At a meeting of opposition parties on Friday, Berisha called
Nano's government an ``enemy of the Albanian nation,'' referring to
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and elsewhere in the Balkans. He called
the Serb forces _ against whom Albanian separatists are waging war
in Kosovo _ ``barbarians'' and the rebels ``blessed.''
	   Such rhetoric further alienates Berisha from the West, where
political and military leaders have expressed resolve not to allow
the Kosovo conflict to escalate. About 10,000 refugees have fled to
Albania to escape the latest Serb offensive, which began last week.
	   Fighting in Kosovo since March has claimed at least 250 lives.
But refugees have given unconfirmed reports of a mass grave with
300 bodies, according to the Belgrade-based Beta news agency.
	   A Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
there are indications the arms trafficking is becoming more
consolidated and is moving away from a ``bazaar of freelancers.''
Also, the amount of weapons crossing the border appears to have
increased significantly as support for the rebels has grown, he
said.
	   Some Kosovo separatist bands are now outfitted with looted
Albanian army uniforms, giving at least the appearance of greater
unity among the ragtag units.
	   Hundreds of thousands of guns and other military equipment were
taken in the anarchy in early 1997 following the collapse of shady
investment schemes that cost many Albanians their entire savings.
Berisha's government was widely blamed for permitting the financial
meltdown.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Albania-Guns and Politics; CT:i; 
