<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours, 1st LD Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW and Mercedes out of Le Mans race within five hours 
</HEADLINE>
By ANDREAS EVAGORA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LE MANS, France (AP) - BMW and Mercedes, two of the top
challengers at the Le Mans 24 Hours race, each lost both of their
cars early in the endurance race Saturday afternoon.
	   After five hours, the Toyota GT One driven by Belgian Thierry
Boutsen, German Ralf Kelleners and Geoff Lees of Britain was in the
lead with 76 laps of the 13.6-kilometer (8.5-mile) circuit.
	   The Mercedes of German Bernd Schneider, which was fastest in
practice, fell out of the race with motor failure after just 90
minutes.
	   Though it started in pole position, Mercedes had cautioned
against over optimism before the race because the CLK-LM, related
to the successful CLK-GTR, is making it Le Mans debut.
	   Mercedes only began 24-hour tests of the car at a track in
Homestead, Florida three weeks ago.
	   In sweltering conditions, two Porsche GT1s were in second and
third close behind the leading Toyota.
	   In second place was the car driven by Jorg Muller and in third
the vehicle driven by Alan McNish of Britain.
	   Nissan R390 GT1s were in fourth and fifth.
	   But the early hours of the race were dominated by problems at
Mercedes and BMW.
	   After four hours, the other Mercedes, driven by Jean Marc
Gounon, suffered another engine failure.
	   Both BMW V12s were put out of the race in the fourth hour
because of vibrations to the front and back of the car.
	   The cars' lead drivers were Tom Kristensen and Pierluigi
Martini.
	   The early leader, the Toyota GT One headed by Martin Brundle,
lost 15 minutes in the fourth hour after it span out of control
with brake problems when driven by Eric Helary.
	   ''Eric had a spin that was brake-problem enduced. The car was
running easily so it was a surprise, but it is always a suprise
when a car brakes down,'' said a disappointed Brundle.
	   After five hours the car was back in 24th place, eight laps
behind the leader.
	   ``It doesn't look like we can win it now as we are so many laps
behind. It's out of our hands. But we can learn for next year.''
	   The leading prototype was the Porsche LMP198 in sixth place.
	   (ae-sz)
</TEXT>
