<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Refs,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Referees hope they won't be the stars of the World Cup AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
By ROBERT MILLWARD
<TEXT>
	   GRESSY, France (AP) _ Now they know the first round games they
are handling, the 34 World Cup referees fear they may become the
biggest stars.
	   ``I hope not. I hope that the World Cup will be remembered for
the football and the goals scored, rather than for the red cards
and for the actions of referees against the players,'' said
England's Paul Durkin.
	   ``The World Cup should be remembered for the skill factor not
the ill-discipline of players.''
	   FIFA's decision to punish foul tackles from behind with a red
card has put the officials in the spotlight because this is the
first competition the mandate applies to.
	   Referees have always had the power to expel a player for a
tackle from behind if they believe it could have led to serious
injury. For the sake of consistency and to protect the most
skillful players from dangerous tackling, soccer's International
Board, meeting three months ago, made it mandatory.
	   ``The new decision that referees have been given is to stop
forwards and particularly skillful players getting seriously
hurt,'' said Durkin, who takes charge of Italy vs. Austria at
Saint-Denis June 23.
	   ``If referees are consistent in their approach and support the
law then the standard of the game will be better.''
	   Durkin and the other 33 referees have been housed at a plush
hotel secluded in a small town 30 kilometers (20 miles) outside of
Paris. The media news were allowed their only access to the
officials on Saturday and most of the questions were about the
tackle from behind mandate.
	   ``Since the International Board announced it was demanding red
cards for such tackles, I have noted several which would apply,''
Durkin said. ``Watching the Premier League games I have often
thought `that's a red card in the World Cup.'
	   ``People have got to realize it's not just for the World Cup,''
the English official said. ``The ruling also applies in leagues
across the world from next season so that a lot of players, coaches
will be watching what happens here.''
	   (rjm-dm)
</TEXT>
