<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Heat Wave </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy sizzles in early heat wave 
</HEADLINE>
With AP Photo
<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italians and tourists sought cool relief splashing
in the sea and in city fountains Saturday as the country sizzled
through a late-spring heat wave with temperatures as high as 37
degrees (99 F).
	   Among those suffering from the heat was anti-corruption hero
Antonio Di Pietro. The former Milan prosecutor-turned-politician
was recovering in a hospital in the southern city of Matera after
fainting during a rally a day earlier for political reform.
	   Other Italians suffering from the heat included some of the
hundreds left homeless by earthquakes last fall in central,
Apennine hilltowns. Many of the homeless are living in cramped,
flat-roofed trailers provided by the government.
	   The highest temperatures were recorded near Foggia, a city in
Puglia, the region on the Adriatic forming the ``heel'' of the
Italian peninsula.
	   Hot blasts of air, known as the scirocco wind, from northern
Africa, added to the misery.
	   Weather forecasters said the heat wave, which built up over
several days, would start fading Sunday. But while temperatures
were predicted to fall, stifling humidity was expected to increase.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
