<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Somalia-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least 88 dead in week-long fighting over Baidoa 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOGADISHU, Somalia (AP) _ At least 25 people were killed
Saturday in factional fighting for control of the strategic
northwestern town of Baidoa, residents and faction spokesmen said
Saturday.
	   Control of the town 150 kilometers (93 miles) northwest of
Mogadishu changed hands several times during the day, residents
contacted by high frequency radio said.
	   At least 88 people have been killed since fighting between
forces loyal to faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid, who retained
control of Baidoa, and the Rahanwein Resistance Army broke out at
the beginning of the week.
	   Residents said fighting raged for several hours in Baidoa, and
bodies of the dead lay in the streets.
	   Baidoa is one of a few Somali towns with a functioning airport
and economy.
	   Earlier Saturday, Baidoa residents and a spokesman for the
Rahanwein Resistance Army in Mogadishu said the RRA had captured
control of the town from Aidid's forces, who were then trapped at
the airport.
	   Following the report, Aidid travelled from Mogadishu to Baidoa
in a convoy of 200 heavily armed men and 15 trucks armed with heavy
machine guns.
	   Sources close to Aidid, who controls southern Mogadishu, said
his forces overwhelmed the RRA forces south of the town and later
took back control.
	   Last December, Aidid and 23 faction leaders agreed to hold a
national reconciliation conference in Baidoa. The RRA and others
said they would not attend unless Aidid withdrew his militia, which
he has not done.
	   The conference, first scheduled for Feb. 15, has been postponed
three times, the last time indefinitely.
	   Somalia has had no central government since clan-based faction
leaders combined to oust dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in January
1991, then turned on each other as the country disintegrated into
fiefdoms protected by private militias.
	   (AAN/dmc)	   
</TEXT>
