<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-American Survivor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American student cope with trauma of survival 
</HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   CELLE, Germany (AP) _ After nearly two months of riding the
rails through Africa, Greece and Switzerland, Jaime Hawk had one
more stop: She wanted to see Hamburg, Germany before she headed
home to find a summer job.
	   What started out as the last hurrah of her junior-year abroad
ended in tragedy.
	   ``It was supposed to be the last punch on her Eurail pass,''
Hawk's cousin, U.S. Army Maj. Rob Strope, 38, said Saturday.
	   The high-speed train she boarded early Wednesday derailed and
smashed into the side of a bridge near the town of Celle, 140
kilometers (85 miles) south of Hamburg. The impact hurled Hawk
through a window.
	   By Saturday, the crash's death toll had reached 102. Rescuers
continued the search for bodies by hand, while a team of experts
investigated what might have caused a broken wheel on the first
passenger car to break, causing the train to derail.
	   Hawk, a 20-year-old native of Boise, Idaho, suffered injuries to
her neck, but doctors at Celle General Hospital expected her to
fully recover.
	   She had been staying with her cousins in Wurzburg since mid-May,
after finishing her studies in Florence, Italy. On Wednesday
morning, Strope dropped her off at the station to catch the 8:30
a.m. train.
	   On the way home that afternoon, the major heard a radio report
of a high-speed train crash but didn't say which train. He drove
straight to the radio station where his fears were confirmed.
Jaime's train had crashed.
	   Strope said Hawk remembers little of the accident. Just reading
a book when the accident happened, and then flying out of her seat.
``Then she remembers being in the hospital,'' he said.
	   When they arrived _ first, before her mother could make it from
Idaho _ Hawk was disoriented. She asked them if they were OK. And
she didn't seem to grasp how badly she was hurt.
	   ``One of the things she said is that she was going to miss her
flight, and by the time she got home all the good summer jobs would
be gone,'' Strope said.
	   Doctors said it would be several weeks before she can leave the
hospital. And it's not clear when she'll be able to resume her
studies at Gonzaga University in Spokane, Washington.
	   ``She's doing super. But she's a little frustrated she can't
move,'' said Strope. ``She fells very lucky. We're trying to keep
her mind off the crash.''
	   (tc-me-cb-aet) 	   
</TEXT>
