<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Argentina-Doping Rumors,0383 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Passarella angrily denies doping rumors 
</HEADLINE>
By VICENTE LEONARDO PANETTA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   L'ETRAT, France (AP) _ The Argentinian World Cup delegation
Saturday angrily denied rumors that internal doping tests had
proved positive for one of its players.
	   ``I'm tired of denying rumors. Lets talk about soccer, please. I
don't know where this silly story comes from,'' the team's coach,
Daniel Passarella, said at a news conference.
	   The rumor was spread by a radio station in Argentina. It
suggested that the player involved was Juan Veron, from Italy's
Sampdoria.
	   Veron said he felt ``mad and sad, as I have a family behind me.
They (the radio station reporters) even made up comments attributed
to me. I never said anything. This is the first time I speak'' on
this issue,'' he told reporters.
	   In spite of the denials, rumors persisted that the controls
showed the presence of some kind of dubious substance.
	   ``It's possible that some substance might have showed up, but it
is well known that most players had the flu,'' the team's
physician, Luis Seveso, said at the same news conference.
	   ``People are talking a lot of nonsense,'' Seveso said, though he
added fuel to the controveray by saying he would make some
inquiries. ``Tonight I will visit each room and tell the players
not to take any medicine without my consent,'' he said.
	   Argentina's Soccer Association president Julio Grondona had said
early today that he knew nothing about the alleged doping. ``In any
case, that's what the controls are for. We don't want a repeat of
what happened in 1994.''
	   He referred to a positive test by Diego Maradona after the
second game of the 1994 World Cup in the United States. Argentina
dropped Maradona from the rest of the tournament and he was latter
banned by FIFA for 15 months for his second positive test.
	   After that World Cup, in which Argentina was eliminated in the
second round, coach Alfio Basile was replaced by Passarella, who
took over with the mission of imposing a strict discipline in the
team and preventing new episodes of this kind.
	   One of the first measures he took was ordering regular doping
tests.
	   (vlp-rjm)	   
</TEXT>
