<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Helms-China,0554 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. senator suspects quid pro quo in Clinton-China technology dealings 
</HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The chairman of the U.S. Senate Foreign
Relations Committee said Saturday he suspects a link between
political contributions to Democrats and decisions by President
Bill Clinton's administration on missile technology exports to
China.
	   ``Don't know whether it's my head or my heart talking, but I
think we're going to find something,'' Republican Sen. Jesse Helms
said on CNN's ``Evans and Novak.''
	   Helms' committee is among several in the Senate looking into
allegations of favor-trading in the administration's treatment of a
major Democratic Party donor with satellite dealings in China. A
frequent Clinton critic, Helms said his committee will hold five or
six hearings on the matter.
	   Congress and the Justice Department are asking whether Clinton
waived restrictions on a satellite export to China in February as a
favor to major Democratic donor Bernard L. Schwartz, chief
executive officer of Loral Space and Communications Co. The White
House and Schwartz deny any such motivation.
	   As part of the investigation, the senators have asked for
documents relating to the president's decision to let Loral launch
a satellite atop a Chinese missile after an earlier one exploded.
	   The dispute centers on what happened after the explosion two
years earlier, in February 1996. Loral headed a defense industry
team that examined what went wrong and shared the information with
the Chinese.
	   Critics contend the report may have helped China improve its
long-range ballistic missiles, but Loral executives say they turned
over no sensitive material.
	   Top intelligence and security officials are divided over whether
Loral and another firm, Hughes Electronics, illegally gave
technology to China, The New York Times reported Saturday.
	   A classified CIA report concluded the companies revealed no
sensitive information, the newspaper reported. But, citing
government and congressional sources it did not identify, the Times
said the intelligence arm of the State Department found just the
opposite.
	   Republican Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott met with Helms and
other committee chairmen this week in what he said was the first of
weekly sessions on the China matter.
	   Afterward, Lott said the controversy could make it harder for
the administration to win most-favored-nation trading status for
China this year.
	   But in the CNN interview, Helms expressed resignation that
Clinton will win the trade designation despite the satellite debate
and criticism of the president's visit this month to Beijing.
Tiananmen Square in Beijing was the center of student protests nine
years ago in which scores were killed in an Army crackdown.
	   The designation merely confers normal trade status on China.
Clinton announced his decision to grant MFN to China on Wednesday,
30 days before last year's designation expires, and Congress has 60
days after the expiration to vote it down.
	   Helms has long opposed MFN for China. He calls the trade status
a sellout of human rights.
	   ``I hope it won't (go through), but I suspect it will,'' Helms
said. ``They've got the votes for it in the Senate, I think, the
way I count.''
</TEXT>
