<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Eritrea, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Plane to pick up Britons in Eritrea Tightens With Eritrea-Ethiopia 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Updates with British plane to pick up Britons from Eritrea.
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A British air force plane flew to Eritrea on
Saturday to pick up the estimated 60 Britons still in the East
African nation where fighting with Ethiopia has escalated over
their disputed border.
	   Both sides in the conflict arranged safe passage for the plane,
which set from Britain in the morning and landed in Crete en route
to the Horn of Africa.
	   The Foreign Office said the Royal Air Force plane could
accommodate all the British people who wish to leave. The flight is
expected to take them to Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, where the British
consul was arranging accommodation.
	   The Foreign Office on Friday advised about 120 British citizens
in Eritrea to leave as soon as possible because of the worsening
conflict.
	   Forty-eight Britons left Eritrea that night on a U.S. aircraft
which landed in Frankfurt early Saturday. The Foreign Office said
the Britons, mainly working for the non-governmental organization
Voluntary Service Overseas, then flew to London.
	   Ethiopian warplanes bombed airports outside the Eritrean capital
on Saturday . The civilian airport was struck by several bombs,
setting off bursts of fire as foreigners were trying to leave the
country. The military airport was also bombed.
	   ``We had seen tanks driving through the streets and we saw the
MiGs bombing the airport which was frightening,'' said Jenny
Tinker, 26, from Reading, England, who has been teaching in Eritrea
for two years and was among the 48 Britons who returned to London
on Saturday.
	   ``The Eritreans are used to it,'' said Debbie McGrath, who also
worked in the education field in Eritrea. ``They have had 30 years
of fighting. People stood out and watched for the MiGs as they went
over and clapped when one was shot down.''
	   Britain is supporting U.S. and Rwandan efforts to broker a peace
deal between the warring countries, Foreign Office minister Tony
Lloyd told BBC radio on Saturday.
	   ``If we can get a cease-fire, then of course it is possible to
begin the process of negotiation and arbitration to resolve the
issue. We have pushed for both sides to recognize there cannot be a
military solution to this problem. We will support the Americans
and Rwanda to broker a regional solution to this problem,'' he
said.
	   Eritrea, which gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993, has
always claimed it remains inside its own territory as determined by
Italian colonial boundaries.
	   (acw-eml)
</TEXT>
