<HEADER>
w2759 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-Clashes     06-06 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Clashes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Further clashes in south Yemen: four more killed, 14 wounded 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Four people were killed and 14 wounded as
riots continued in southern Yemen for a second day Saturday, a
security official said.
	   The casualties brought the toll for the two days to eight dead
and 18 wounded in the villages around Ad-Dali, a town 250
kilometers (156 miles) southeast of the capital, San`a, the
official added.
	   The clashes began Friday after soldiers at a checkpoint near
Ad-Dali opened fire on a car, killing one person and wounding
another. In a statement Saturday, Yemeni security officials said
the car's driver refused to stop at the checkpoint.
	   Armed civilians opened fire on the checkpoint later Friday, the
officials said. Weapons are not difficult to buy in Yemen, owing to
the recent war and the government's weak authority.
	   For a second day Saturday, the government deployed tanks and
armored personnel carriers to try to restore order in the villages.
	   Civilians were leaving the area, officials said.
	   The political bureau of the Socialist Party, which ruled south
Yemen when it was an independent state, called Saturday for an end
to the military presence in the area, compensation for the families
of the victims and the release of all detainees.
	   The party said the clashes were caused by popular indignation
against widespread corruption and ``arbitrary practices'' against
civilians.
	   Ad-Dali lies in Lahij province, south Yemen, which was a
separate country until it united with north Yemen in 1990. The
south tried to secede in 1994, provoking a brief civil war. The
northern-based armed forces then took control of the south, but
continue to be widely resented.
