<SLUG> BC-Guyana-Presidency,0277 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guyana president asks for direct talks with rival 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ With an election recount completed,
Guyana President Janet Jagan has called on her chief rival to sit
down for one-on-one talks.
	   Jagan and the president of the opposition People's National
Congress, Desmond Hoyte, have not met in person since the December
election in which Jagan defeated Hoyte.
	   In the aftermath of the vote, Hoyte's party claimed fraud and
demonstrations turned violent. On Tuesday, an international panel
announced that its recount of the votes found no serious
irregularities.
	   ``I think it would be very good if the leaders of the two major
parties of Guyana have a frank and honest discussion,'' Jagan said
Saturday in her regular television and radio program, ``This Week
with the President.''
	   Hoyte has not said if he will meet with Jagan, but has indicated
that he would agree only if a specific agenda is set. Jagan, the
U.S.-born widow of popular former president Cheddi Jagan, said she
would agree to Hoyte's request.
	   Race is at the root of most conflicts in Guyana, a former
British colony. Jagan's party is backed by the majority population
of East Indian descent, while Hoyte's draws support from the 40
percent of people of African descent.
	   In her address, Jagan indirectly criticized those in Hoyte's
party who want to boycott the sessions of Parliament. Jagan said
the minority politicians have an obligation to take their seats in
Parliament and represent their constituents.
	   ``Otherwise, what was the point of the people voting for them?''
she asked. 	   
</TEXT>
