<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Switzerland-Yugoslavia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia held to 1-1 draw by Swiss substitute's first goal 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Substitute Patrick Mueller's first
goal for Switzerland earned his side a 1-1 draw Saturday against a
Yugoslavia team playing its last warm-up match before the World Cup
finals.
	   Mueller's spectacular 83rd minute strike, five minutes after he
came on, canceled out an early goal by Yugoslav midfielder Branko
Brnovic.
	   Yugoslavia had sat back on its lead after going ahead in the
sixth minute and was given a further scare in the 88th minute when
a Patrick Haas free kick was tipped over the bar by keeper Ivica
Kralj at full stretch.
	   Yugoslav coach Slobodan Santrac said his team was tired after
its World Cup preparations.
	   ``It was difficult to get so many players from so many European
leagues playing together,'' he added. ``The Swiss succeeded in
stopping us from playing our own game.''
	   The Yugoslavs open their World Cup campaign next Sunday, when
the team takes on Iran in Saint-Etienne.
	   It is one of the favorites to qualify from first-round Group F,
which also includes the United States and three-times champion
Germany.
	   On Wednesday Yugoslavia beat fellow qualifier Japan 1-0 courtesy
of a goal by defender Sinisa Mihajlovic.
	   A cautious Yugoslavia side was given an energetic workout by the
depleted Swiss, who missed out on a place in France after a
disastrous qualifying campaign.
	   After starting brightly, Switzerland was caught by surprise as
Savo Milosevic's cross from the right was met by Espanyol player
Brnovic, who steered a powerful shot past advancing Swiss keeper
Pascal Zuberbuehler.
	   Yugoslavia was content to break out from defense after that,
with no serious chances of taking a two-goal lead until a
Mihajlovic corner rattled the Swiss in the 34th minute.
	   A spell of Swiss pressure, in which the team won six corners,
ended with a 44th minute goal by Alexandre Comisetti being
disallowed for handball.
	   Milosevic was involved in most of Yugoslavia's most promising
moves until he was replaced in the second half. Star striker
Predrag Mijatovic was substituted at half time and Mihajlovic,
known for his powerful long-range free kicks, had only limited
chances.
	   The Swiss pressure mounted in the second half, but when the
equalizer came it was from an unexpected source.
	   Mueller, of Geneva club Servette and playing in only his second
match for the national team, curled a right-footed shot into the
top right corner of the goal.
	   Lineups:
	   Switzerland _ Pascal Zuberbuehler, Murat Yakin, Stephane
Henchoz, Marco Zwyssig, Johann Vogel, David Sesa (Fabio Celestini
87th minute), Johann Lonfat (Bernt Haas 46th), Sebastien Fournier,
Frederic Chassot (Patrick de Napoli 61st), Stephane Chapuisat,
Alexandre Comisetti (Patrick Mueller 78th).
	   Yugoslavia _ Ivica Kralj, Zoran Mirkovic, Miroslav Djukic
(Slobodan Komljenovic 46th), Sinisa Mihajlovic, Goran Djorovic,
Dragan Stojkovic (Dejan Govedarica 46th) , Slavisa Jokanovic,
Branko Brnovic (Zeljko Petrovic 46th), Vladimir Jugovic, Predrag
Mijatovic (Darko Kovacevic 46th), Savo Milosevic (Dejan Stankovic
78th).
	   Referee: Juan Manuel Brito Arceo. Attendance: 24,000.
 &UR; (gm)
