<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Cardoso Woes,0484 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President Cardoso losing support among poor 
</HEADLINE>
By JACK EPSTEIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ For the first time since he became
president, Fernando Henrique Cardoso is losing support among the
nation's poor majority, a pollster said Saturday.
	   As a result, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, a perennial socialist
candidate for president, appears to be gaining on Cardoso, who
assumed power on New Year's Day in 1995 and is running for
re-election in October.
	   ``The poor population is pushing Fernando Henrique down,'' Helio
Gastalde, director for the IBOPE polling firm, told reporters. ``We
can easily infer that there is great dissatisfaction with the
economic situation, with the fear of unemployment.''
	   Three separate polls released Saturday show da Silva as having
gained support over the past month _ with the poor as his biggest
booster. In the past, low income voters had been ardent Cardoso
supporters since his anti-inflationary economic program had allowed
them to spend more income on consumer items.
	   At campaign stops, da Silva has hammered home the theme that
Cardoso has ignored the needy in his efforts to curb inflation and
stabilize the economy and has failed to initiate sweeping social
programs that the poor so badly need.
	   Da Silva, who lost a close race in 1989 to Fernando Collor de
Mello and was easily beaten by Cardoso in 1994, is also changing
his radical image. He no longer criticizes the stabilization
program, which brought inflation from 50 percent a month to 5
percent annually.
	   Instead, he has focused on such social issues as rising
unemployment _ officially 8 percent but critics say its twice that
_ and lack of political will to significantly change the nation's
skewed distribution of wealth, one of the world's worst.
	   Cardoso hasn't helped his own cause.
	   Last month, he offended many here by calling anyone who retires
at 50 a ``bum.'' Cardoso, who has been campaigning to reform
Brazil's social security system, surprised many by the sharp
attack.
	   Moreover, previous polls have described him as out of touch with
Brazilian reality, preferring to travel abroad than to his own
nation's hinterlands.
	   Last month, Cardoso led a 35-member business delegation to
Spain. On Saturday, he flew to the United States to attend the
signing of an education agreement between Brazil and the World
Bank, speak at the U.N and visit with President Bill Clinton at
Camp David.
	   ``With all these trips, the voters see him as more worried about
his and the country's image than internal problems,'' said
Gastalde.
	   Most political analysts agree that there will likely be no clear
winner in the first round of elections in October, causing a runoff
election a month later, an unlikely political scenario just several
months ago.
</TEXT>
