<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Airline Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,0228 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aeromexico flight attendants end strike end strike. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with flight attendants voting to
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Flight attendants for Mexico's largest
airline ended a strike Saturday after six days. They had never
stopped working, however, because the government took over the
airline's operations when the strike began.
	   Union negotiators reached an accord with Aeromexico on Friday,
and put the proposed settlement to their members Saturday
afternoon.
	   About 300 union members present voted unanimously to approve the
accord, according to the union's secretary-general, Alejandra
Barrales.
	   The 1,033 unionized flight attendants went on strike a week ago
over salaries, work hours, benefits and the size of flight crews.
	   But they continued to work after the government took over
operations of Aeromexico. Mexico's constitution gives the
government the right to temporarily seize companies vital to the
nation's economy or security.
	   Barrales said the airline agreed to all the union's main
concerns _ an 18.3 percent raise, one additional flight attendant
on each flight, extra pay for night work and the beginnings of a
retirement plan.
	   The government has said it would hand operations back over to
Aeromexico when the strike ended.
</TEXT>
