<SLUG> BC-UN-Annan-Nuclear,0279 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Annan repeats offer to help India and Pakistan resume dialogue With UN-India-Pakistan 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ After the Security Council condemned South
Asian nuclear tests, Secretary-General Kofi Annan renewed his offer
Saturday to help India and Pakistan resume a high-level dialogue to
resolve longstanding differences.
	   Annan attended Saturday's session in which the 15 council
members voted unanimously on a resolution to demand that India and
Pakistan refrain from further nuclear tests, halt weapons programs
and sign nuclear control agreements unconditionally.
	   The resolution also urges the two South Asian rivals to resume
negotiations on issues, including Kashmir, the Himalayan area over
which they have fought two wars since gaining independence from
Britain in 1947.
	   ``I would like in particular to welcome the call to India and
Pakistan to resume their bilateral talks on the issues that have
sadly divided them,'' Annan told the council. ``I will continue my
own efforts to encourage this dialogue in the hope that it will
reduce tensions and the danger of an escalation in the nuclear arms
race.''
	   The dialogue broke down last year because of differences over
Kashmir.
	   During his remarks, Annan said last month's nuclear tests on the
subcontinent ``are unquestionably disturbing developments with
far-reaching consequences for the region and for the international
community.''
	   Echoing remarks of council members, Annan said the tests also
``seriously impact on the ongoing process of nuclear
nonproliferation and nuclear disarmament and its future and our
common security.''
</TEXT>
