<SLUG> BC-Britain-Diana's Mother, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Princess' mother vows to carry out Diana's wishes in will reply on plot allegations 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: Updates at end with report Al Fayed will ask government to
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Princess Diana's mother, responding obliquely to
Mohamed Al Fayed's criticism of her relationship with her daughter,
vowed Saturday to carry out Diana's wish that she help with the
uprbringing of Prince William and Prince Harry.
	   Al Fayed, whose son Dodi died in the car crash that killed Diana
nine months ago, said Friday that Frances Shand Kydd was a bad
mother, accused her of snobbery and said Diana ``did not give a
damn about her.''
	   Most of Saturday's newspapers attacked Al Fayed for the remarks
he made after a Paris meeting of witnesses and the judge handling
the French investigation of the Aug. 31 crash.
	   Al Fayed has angered Diana's family with his allegations that
she intended to marry his son and that the two were victims of a
murder plot. He made clear Friday that Mrs. Shand Kydd had not
spoken to him at all during the day-long meeting.
	   In a statement issued to the national news agency Press
Association on Saturday, Mrs. Shand Kydd said, ``I have nothing to
say about yesterday in Paris, except many thanks to many people who
were kind and helpful to me.
	   ``Diana's will, which has been made public, stated her wishes to
me.
	   ``I shall try my utmost, all my days, to carry out her wishes
and what she asked of me.''
	   Diana's will, which was made public in March, requested that her
mother be consulted over the ``upbringing, education and welfare''
of Princes William and Harry.
	   Al Fayed was quoted as telling the Sunday Mirror newspaper, `` I
do not regret anything that I said. I do not feel I have anything
to apologize for.''
	   He also reportedly told the tabloid that he will try to find a
member of Parliament to force the government to give an assurance
in the House of Commons that the intelligence agencies had nothing
to do with the two deaths.
	   He said he wanted to challenge the government to deny a cover-up
of the circumstances surrounding the crash and that he was writing
to more than 200 legislators, the tabloid said.
	   (acw) 	   
