<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours, 2nd-Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Porsches storm to leadership; spectators injured after crash 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: Race update at 9 hours, next update at 12 hours.
By ANDREAS EVAGORA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LE MANS, France (AP) - Two Porsches grabbed the lead in the
ninth hour of the Le Mans 24 Hour race Saturday, after a Toyota was
unable to maintain its early lead in the endurance race.
	   At the same time a prototype, the Courage C51, was challenging
GT cars for the first time by moving into fourth place.
	   Nine hours after the start of the race, the lead was held by the
Porsche GT1 driven by Jorg Muller and Uwe Alzen of Germany and
France's Bob Wolleck.
	   The car had completed 137 laps.
	   Also on 137 laps, and in second place, was another Porsche GT1,
driven by Alan McNish of Britain and France's Laurent Aiello and
Stephane Ortelli.
	   The Toyota GT One driven by Thierry Boutsen lost a lead it had
held for more than four hours, when it went into the pits for a
scheduled pit stop.
	   After the scheduled pit stop, the Toyota One lost further ground
at when it was in the pits for 15 minutes with gearbox problems.
	   As nightfall descended, the two Porsches took full advantage to
move into the lead.
	   The Toyota continued to slip down the field and was in seventh
place after nine hours.
	   In the race between prototypes, the Courage C51 driven by Didier
Cottaz, Marc Goosens and Jean Philippe had improved to fourth
place.
	   Porsche's leading prototype, the LMP1, was in fifth but was
losing ground on the Courage C51 with lighting problems.
	   Some drivers of cars that were already out of the race said that
they have nevertheless learned valuable experience.
	   ``We are really disappointed as the car was going faster than
expected,'' said Steve Soper, driver of one of BMW's V12, which
pulled out after four hours.
	   ``Suddenly we had a wheel-bearing problem and the race was
finished. But we only started developing the car last October with
serious driving in April, and there is nothing like Le Mans for
testing a car.''
	   ``In 25 years of driving I have never been able to overtake so
easily on the straight, so I'm already looking forward to next
year,'' Soper said.
	   Race organizers said that several spectators were slightly
injured by flying gravel and pieces of spoiler from a Porsche 911
GT2 that rolled out of control.
	   The car was driven by Briton Nick Ham, who was also lightly
injured in the accident, which took place when the car rolled off
the track at Mulsanne Corner.
	   (ae-sz) 	   
</TEXT>
