<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-Rhein Fire-Galaxy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Galaxy reach World Bowl on Kleinmann's overtime FG 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) _ Ralf Kleinmann hit a 46-yard field
goal with 41 seconds left in overtime Saturday to carry the
Frankfurt Galaxy into the NFL Europe's World Bowl.
	   Behind the German national's kick, the Galaxy edged the
Duesseldorf Rhein Fire 20-17 in front of a record football crowd at
Rhein Stadium of 41,212.
	   Kleinmann also sent the game into overtime, tying the game at
17-17 by connecting for a 36-yarder with 46 seconds to play.
	   Rhein Fire (7-3) had already clinched a berth in the World Bowl
to be held June 14 in Frankfurt, Germany, but the Galaxy (7-3)
needed to win to hold off the Amsterdam Admirals.
	   Chris Dittoe rallied the Galaxy in the second half, hitting
receiver Mario Bailey for 5 yards with 2:32 to play that cut the
Rhein Fire lead to 17-14.
	   Dittoe, who replaced the injured Damon Huard to start the second
half, also dived over from the 1-yard line for the team's first
score.
	   The Rhein Fire dominated until the third quarter with Mike
Quinn, playing for the Pittsburgh Steelers next season, throwing
two touchdown passes.
	   Quinn, the league's leading passer, hit Kevin Lee for 29 yards
with 7:44 remaining in the half. His 9-yard toss to Dialleo Burks
early in the third quarter put Rhein Fire ahead 14-0.
	   But the game turned when Quinn's handoff on the Rhein Fire
1-yard line was fumbled and Dittoe carried it in on the next play.
	   The Amsterdam Admirals could also finish 7-3 by winning Sunday,
but have the worst record when the three teams have faced each
other head-to-head.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
