<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Women's World Championships,0500 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US beats Brazil, Russia shocks Australia 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Lisa Leslie and Natalie Williams combined for 32
points and 27 rebounds as the U.S. National Team defeated Brazil
93-79 on Saturday, advancing to the Women's World Championship
game.
	   There the Americans will meet Russia, which shocked previously
unbeaten Australia 82-76. The U.S. team defeated Russia 96-60 in
group play earlier in the week.
	   Ruthie Bolton added 16 points for the Americans, 13 of them in
the second half when the United States took control of the game.
	   The win avenged a bitter 110-107 defeat in the semifinals of the
1994 World Championships, a game in which the U.S. was also
favored. Brazil went on to win the world title, and Bolton, who
played in the '94 game, was determined not to let it happen again.
	   ``It brought back some bad feelings,'' Bolton said of the
matchup. ``I did not want to go through those feelings again.''
	   Brazil seemed poised early on to upset the Americans. Paula da
Silva controlled much of the first half, scoring 16 of her
game-high 25 points to help Brazil build a 10-point lead, 47-37,
with 4:43 left.
	   But the Americans crawled slowly back into the game, helped by
the Brazilians' inability to take full advantage of their free
throws. Brazil was making 71 percent of free throws coming into the
game but made just nine of 16 in the first half.
	   The U.S. had cut the margin to 45-44 at the break, and the
American team's depth began to take its toll five minutes into the
second half.
	   ``The Americans have 12 players they can use,'' said Brazilian
coach Antonio Carlos Barbosa. By contrast, all but seven of
Brazil's points came from just four players.
	   Leslie and Williams scored 16 points each, and Leslie led the
Americans with 14 rebounds.
	   In the day's other game, heavily favored Australia struggled
offensively as the Russians blocked nine shots and took away the
inside game of Carla Porter and Jenny Whittle. Power forward
Michelle Griffiths led the Australians in scoring with 17 points,
but she was just six of 17 from the field.
	   The Australians trailed for most of the game. They last led with
4:21 left in the first half, and Russia steadily pulled away after
that.
	   Mounting a ferocious press, Australia cut Russia's 75-62 lead
with 3:02 left to just 76-74 with 1:41 remaining. But Irina
Routkovskaya, who was making just 56 percent of her free throws
coming into the game, hit four pressure free throws in the last 53
seconds to seal the win.
	   Elena Baranova was the Russians' real hero, finishing with 25
points, 14 rebounds, four assists and three blocked shots.
Baranova, who plays for the Utah Starzz, dominated the boards in
the last two and a half minutes, when the Australians made three
straight steals in the backcourt.
	   Elena Pshikova added 22 points and made five of seven
three-pointers, while Elena Khudacova had 16 points and 14
rebounds.
</TEXT>
