<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Briefs,0447 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs CUBA: Cubans on their own in applying for U.S. visas 
</HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Cuba said Saturday that it won't set up any
special mechanisms to help its citizens apply for a new U.S. visa
lottery, in which hundreds of thousands of Cubans are expected to
participate.
	   In a statement reported by the government's Prensa Latina news
agency and monitored in Mexico City, Cuba's post office said it
would not set up a special system.
	   The lottery, the third of its kind, was announced Friday in
Washington. It opens June 15, and winners are granted an interview
by U.S. consular officers.
	   In the last lottery, in 1996, more than 436,000 applications
were received. In the first, in 1994, 190,000 people applied.
 &UR; GUYANA: President asks for talks with chief rival
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ With an election recount completed,
Guyana President Janet Jagan has called on her chief rival to sit
down for one-on-one talks.
	   Jagan and the president of the opposition People's National
Congress, Desmond Hoyte, have not met in person since the December
election in which Jagan defeated Hoyte.
	   In the aftermath of the vote, Hoyte's party claimed fraud and
demonstrations turned violent. On Tuesday, an international panel
announced that its recount of the votes found no serious
irregularities.
	   Hoyte has not said if he will meet with Jagan, but has indicated
that he would agree only if a specific agenda is set. Jagan, the
U.S.-born widow of popular former president Cheddi Jagan, said she
would agree to Hoyte's request.
 &UR; CUBA: Cigar chief says quality is not declining
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Responding to criticism that the quality of
Cuban cigars is dropping as production booms, the head of Cuba's
government cigar producers says the stogies are as good as ever.
	   In an article by the government news agency Prensa Latina,
monitored in Mexico City, the head of Cuba's Union of Tabacco
Companies said Cuban cigars are works of art and that there are
enough quality checks to ensure their flavor.
	   Production grew 40 percent last year, and is expected to grow
another 60 percent this year, Francisco Linares Calvo said Friday.
	   That means the industry will make 160 million cigars for export,
which will net the companies dlrs 280 million _ a profit of dlrs
180 million, Prensa Latina said.
	   The world market for Cuban cigars has been growing strongly over
the past few years. Some aficionados have complained that quality
has been dropping as production increases.
</TEXT>
