<SLUG> BC-UN-Korea,0193 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean president meets U.N. chief 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
visited Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Saturday before attending a
reception in conjunction with a Korean exhibit at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art.
	   The United Nations released no statement after the half-hour
meeting between Annan and Kim at U.N. headquarters.
	   The South Korean president, who was elected last December, is to
meet with Korean-Americans on Sunday, then receive an award from
the International League for Human Rights for his contribution to
civil liberties.
	   Before winning the presidency, Kim spent 40 years as an
opposition politician, including 7 1/2 years in prison or house
arrest and four years in exile under a succession of military
dictators.
	   He has been abducted by government agents, sentenced to death
and, by his account, targeted for assassination four times by those
who saw him as a threat to ruling regimes.
	   On Monday, he will address the Council on Foreign Relations
before traveling to Washington for an address to Congress and a
meeting with President Bill Clinton.
</TEXT>
