w2872 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-RugbyU-Austral     06-06 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Australia-England-O'Neill </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australians feel vindicated by test thrashing 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Australian rugby bosses John O'Neill
and Dick McGruther said their attacks on England's touring rugby
team were vindicated by Saturday's record 76-0 Wallaby win.
	   The pair were strongly critical of the English Rugby Union for
allowing an under strength team Down Under and were proved right in
an 11-try romp which was England's worst defeat.
	   ``What can you do, pretend it didn't happen?'' ARU chief
executive O'Neill said.
	   ``They sent a squad out here with 20 uncapped players and
they've turned out a test team tonight and been beaten 76-0.''
	   He described the feeling as ``sweet and sour.''
	   ``You win a Test match 76-0 against England and you don't
celebrate,'' O'Neill said. ``For a country that has figured in the
top four in the world to be beaten 76-0 by Australia is a crying
shame. If ever there was a message to the English RFU this is the
message. This is not what international rugby is about, it's not a
contest.''
	   O'Neill said he felt sorry for the English players who were sent
out for the slaughter.
	   ``The (English) have painted us as some sort of madmen from the
southern hemisphere telling them how to run their business,''
O'Neill said. ``How would you feel if you were an English player
walking off the paddock tonight? And now they've got five games in
New Zealand which are horrific.
	   ``Those poor players, as determined and proud as they are, are
not test players.''
	   O'Neill and McGruther were lampooned in Britain for their
comments when England's touring party was announced.
	   McGruther had described the squad as the worst prepared English
to visit Australia since the First Fleet, and said the RFU was
responsible for the biggest sell out since Gallipoli.
	   ``I would just hope the England officials now realize that if
you want primacy in Test rugby you've got to be proactive and do
something positive about it,'' McGruther said Saturday.
	   England coach Clive Woodward believed the loss was a ``freak
result.''
	   ``It wasn't a a case of an embarrassment or humiliation. We just
had a bit of a bad day,'' said Woodward. ``The scoreline was a
freak result. The game got away from us and it turned into a bit of
an exhibition which was disappointing.''
	   Tony Diprose, who captained England for the first time, said his
side could not believe the result.
	   ``Everyone is a little bit shell-shocked,'' Diprose said. ``But
we think we can lift ourselves up and play well through to the end
of the tour.''
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
