	   WORLD AT 0000 GMT:
	   NEW:
	   _YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO. More shelling, more dead in Kosovo.
	   _UN-KOREA. Kim Dae-jung briefs U.N. officials in first visit to
U.S. as president.
	   _US-SHUTTLE-MIR. Cosmonauts fail to locate leaks.
	   _LEBANON-ELECTIONS. Fear of upsetting sectarian balance hangs
over elections.
	   _BOSNIA-FAIRY TALE. Tale of grateful goldfish turns true for
Bosnian family.
 &UR; MAIN SPOT NEWS:
	   ASMARA, Eritrea _ With a border dispute escalating into bombing
raids, hundreds of foreigners scramble out of Eritrea, fearing it
will be engulfed in war with Ethiopia. ERITREA-ETHIOPIA. Recap
expected by 0200 GMT. By Julia Stewart. AP Photo ASM101.
	   UNITED NATIONS _ The 15 members of the Security Council have
demanded in a unanimous vote that India and Pakistan refrain from
further nuclear tests, halt weapons programs and sign nuclear
control agreements unconditionally. UN-INDIA-PAKISTAN. Recap
expected by 0200 GMT. By Robert H. Reid. AP Photos NYR104-105.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _UN-ANNAN-NUCLEAR _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan repeats his
offer to help India and Pakistan resume dialogue. AP Photo NYR105.
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Serb gunners shell villages in Kosovo
with heavy artillery on and fighting flares along the province's
southern border with Macedonia. Four people died in the clashes,
ethnic Albanian and Serb sources say. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO. Has moved.
By Ismet Hajdari. AP Photos BAJ101-104.
	   PARIS _ Both sides on Sunday show a willingness to begin new
talks aimed at ending a strike by Air France pilots that has
threatened to tarnish the World Cup. AIR FRANCE-STRIKE. Recap
expected by 0200 GMT. By Deborah Seward. AP Photos PAR107-109.
	   UNITED NATIONS _ On his first trip to the United States since
assuming office, South Korea's President Kim Dae-jung briefs U.N.
officials on measures to improve the atmosphere with the Communist
North. UN-KOREA. Recap expected by 0200 GMT. By Robert H. Reid.
	   SPACE CENTER, Houston _ Mir's cosmonauts pump a green,
fluorescent gas into their damaged laboratory module Saturday in an
unsuccessful effort to locate leaks caused by last year's
near-catastrophic collision. US-SHUTTLE-MIR. Has moved. By Marcia
Dunn. AP Photos XHTN101-103.
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Authorities trying to maintain Beirut's
sectarian balance urge voters to avoid partisanship in Sunday's
municipal elections. LEBANON-ELECTIONS. Expected by 0200 GMT. By
Hussein Dakroub. AP Photo BEI101.
	   ESCHEDE, Germany _ Federal rail authorities order a second round
of inspections of Germany's original fleet of high-speed trains to
concentrate on the wheels, believed to have caused the nation's
deadliest postwar train crash. GERMANY-TRAIN DERAILS. Has moved. By
Tony Czuczka. AP Photo ESC101.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _GERMANY-BACK ON TRACK _ German passengers unfazed by high-speed
crash. AP Photo NY192.
	   DASHTAK, Afghanistan _ A mullah and his congregation pray for
the more than 1,200 people of their Afghan village who perished in
last weekend's devastating earthquake that set off a landslide that
tore down a mountain. AFGHANISTAN-MOUNTAIN OF DEATH. Has moved. By
Zaheeruddin Abdullah. AP Photos FTBD110-116.
	   JEZERO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Every Bosnian child knows the story
of a poor woman who caught a golden fish, released it and in return
gained wealth and happiness. It's a Balkan fairy tale _ but it
turned into reality for one poor family. BOSNIA-FAIRY TALE.
Expected by 0200 GMT. By Alexandar S. Dragicevic. AP Photo SAR101.
	   LOOKING AHEAD: On Monday, a memorial service is held for Linda
McCartney in London. Foreign Ministers of nine Balkan countries
meet in Istanbul on Monday to increase cooperation in the turbulent
region.
 &UR; FEATURES: Arts and Entertainment
	   BEIJING _ Like any metropolis, Beijing gives its citizens plenty
to fret about. Job security and the city's historic elegance are
vanishing, while traffic and pollution intensify. Husband-and-wife
artists Liu Qinghe and Chen Shuxia are taking a fresh look at
chaotic urban life in China. ARTS-CHINA-PAINTING DUO. To move as
wire time permits. By Renee Schoof. AP Photos NY450-1
	   NEW DELHI, India _ At 82, M.F. Husain is India's best-known
contemporary artist. But he and other Indian artists are only now
attracting wider attention abroad, slowly reshaping the attitude
that Indian art begins and ends with ancient temple sculpture.
ARTS-INDIA-HUSAIN. To move as wire time permits. By Donna Bryson.
AP Photo NY455
	   LOS ANGELES _ Movie soundtracks have always been popular, but
they are getting even more so. The ``Titanic'' album was a huge
success with 25 million discs sold worldwide. ``We are in the
longest continuous cycle of successful soundtrack releases,'' one
industry source says. ARTS-US-SOUNDTRACKS. To move as wire time
permits. By Michael Fleeman. AP Photo NY456
	   Also Moving:
	   ARTS-US-Olivia Newton-John AP Photo NY452
