<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Today In History,0598 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saturday, June 13 
</HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
	   Today is Saturday, June 13, the 164th day of 1998. There are 201
days left in the year.
	   Highlights in history on this date:
	   1546 - Protestant princes of Germany denounce Council of Trent.
	   1547 - Hungary and Turkey sign five-year truce.
	   1653 - British fleet defeats Dutch off North Foreland.
	   1721 - England joins Treaty of Madrid with Spain and France.
	   1839 - Milosh, King of Serbia, abdicates, and is succeeded by
his son Milan.
	   1886 - Mysterious death by drowning of Bavaria's ``Mad'' King
Ludwig.
	   1900 - Boxer Uprising against Europeans in China begins.
	   1916 - Jan Christian Smuts captures Wilkelsthal City in German
East Africa.
	   1953 - A military coup led by Gen. Gustavo Rojas Pinilla
overthrows unpopular government of President Laureano Gomez. Rojas
Pinilla voluntarily steps down in 1957 as Colombia returned to
democratic rule.
	   1940 - Paris is declared an open city in World War II.
	   1956 - Last British troops leave Suez Canal base, turn waterway
over to Egypt after operating it for 74 years.
	   1969 - Withdrawal of U.S. combat troops from South Vietnam
begins with pullout of unit fighting in Mekong Delta.
	   1971 - New York Times begins publishing the Pentagon Papers.
	   1973 - United States, North Vietnam, South Vietnam and Viet Cong
sign new pact in Paris designed to reinforce Vietnam cease-fire.
	   1974 - Army in Republic of Yemen seizes power in bloodless coup.
	   1982 - Saudi Arabia's King Khaled dies and Crown Prince Fahd
assumes the throne.
	   1984 - Nicaragua says its troops forced group of U.S.-backed
rebels to flee across border into Costa Rica after four days of
heavy fighting.
	   1987 - Panamanians stage peaceful protests to demonstrate their
displeasure with nation's military leadership.
	   1988 - Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman says policeman is
killed during ethnic protest in Azerbaijani capital of Baku.
	   1988 - Turkish Premier Turgut Ozal visits Athens in an historic
bid to improve ties between Greece and Turkey.
	   1989 - Syrian and Christian gunners fight five-hour shelling
duel around Beirut.
	   1990 - Romanian riot police attack a tent city set up by student
protesters in downtown Bucharest, touching off riots that leave
four people dead and 200 injured.
	   1991 - 26-year-old Lebanese woman is sentenced to death by
Kuwait's martial law court for turning in her Kuwaiti husband to
the Iraqi military.
	   1992 - The U.N. begins to demobilize most armies of the four
Cambodian factions, but the Khmer Rouge refuses to comply.
	   1993 - Kim Campbell becomes Canada's first woman prime minister.
	   1994 - Colombia, Mexico and Venezuela sign a free trade pact.
	   1995 - Bosnian Serbs release nearly all U.N. hostages and
promise to free the final 15 captives by week's end.
	   1996 - An Garuda Indonesian Airways DC-10 jet skids off a runway
in southern Japan on takeoff and bursts into flames, killing three
people and injuring 108.
	   1997 - Timothy J. McVeigh, a 29-year-old army veteran, is
sentenced to death for bombing a government building in Oklahoma
City in 1995, killing 168 people.
	   Today's Birthdays:
	   Richard Barnfield, English poet (1574-1627); Thomas Arnold,
English educator-historian (1795-1842); William B. Yeats, Irish
poet (1865-1939); Malcolm McDowell, English actor (1943--); Stellan
Skarsgard, Swedish actor (1951--).
	   Thought For Today:
	   One is easily fooled by that which one loves _ Moliere, French
actor-playwright (1622-1673).
</TEXT>
