<HEADER>
w2884 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APNewsSummary     06-06 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0683 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ With a border dispute escalating into
bombing raids, hundreds of foreigners scrambled out of Eritrea on
Saturday, fearing it will be engulfed in war with Ethiopia. One of
their main escape routes came under attack for a second straight
day. Ethiopian jets again bombed a military-civilian airport not
far from Asmara, forcing embassies to step up their exit plans.
Late Saturday, foreign diplomats met with Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi in Addis Ababa and received a pledge that Ethiopian
warplanes would suspend their bombing of the airport from Saturday
evening until Sunday morning so evacuations could take place,
Italian Ambassador Marcello Ricoveri said. (ERITREA-ETHIOPIA)
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The 15 members of the Security Council
have demanded in a unanimous vote that India and Pakistan refrain
from further nuclear tests, halt weapons programs and sign nuclear
control agreements unconditionally. After Saturday's vote,
non-nuclear states, including New Zealand and Canada, also sent a
strong message to the United States and the other four nuclear
powers, telling them to fulfill commitments to reduce their own
nuclear arsenals. Islamic countries also complained the council has
ignored Israel's refusal to sign arms control treaties or accept
international controls on its nuclear program. Israel has never
acknowledged having nuclear weapons but is believed to have the
technology to build them. (UN-INDIA-PAKISTAN)
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Saturday
the government was prepared to intervene in the weeklong Air France
strike which has embarrassed the country ahead of the World Cup,
which opens Wednesday. Air France President Jean-Cyril Spinetta
said talks that lasted all night without reaching agreement had
been ``suspended.'' The pilots appeared divided, with the head of
the main pilots' union indicating new talks could take place Monday
and a spokesman saying they could go back to the table over the
weekend. Air France is the official World Cup carrier and is
committed to transporting the teams from one venue to another.
Jospin said the French government was ready to intervene to help
end the the strike and would play a role ``in the hours to come.''
(AIR FRANCE-STRIKE)
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb gunners shelled villages in
Kosovo with heavy artillery on Saturday and fighting flared along
the province's southern border with Macedonia. Four people were
killed in the clashes, ethnic Albanian and Serb sources said. The
artillery attack targeted three villages in the Decani area, 45
miles (70 kilometers) west of Pristina, said the Kosovo Information
Center, which is close to Albanian leaders in the province. Serb
police and army forces have recently stepped up their campaign to
crush the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of the Albanian
independence movement. The militants have been gaining in
popularity and numbers after years of heavy-handed rule by Serbian
authorities in Kosovo, the secessionist southern province where
ethnic Albanians represent 90 percent of the population of 2.2
million. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ The danger of losing this capital city's
sectarian balance was at stake in Sunday's municipal elections.
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri has appealed to voters not to ignore
candidates from the Christian minority when they elect a new city
council for this city of Sunni Muslim majority. ``Let's maintain
the national balance and give mutual coexistence top consideration
when voting,'' said Hariri, a Sunni Muslim who has endorsed a slate
of candidates that includes Christians, Sunnis and Shiite Muslims.
Beirut, the city where the civil war of 1975-90 began, elected a
half-Muslim, half-Christian council in its last local elections 35
years ago. But the demography has since changed in favor of the
Muslims. (LEBANON-ELECTIONS)
</TEXT>
