<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Nationwide Senior PGA,0533 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Morgan in familiar spot, leading on the Senior PGA Tour AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
With AP Photos XAX102-104
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
	   ALPAHRETTA, Georgia (AP) _ Gil Morgan, locked in a seasonlong
battle with Hale Irwin for dominance of the Senior PGA Tour, shot a
3-under-par 69 to share the lead with Bob Eastwood after the second
round of the Nationwide Championship.
	   Morgan, who has three victories, three other Top 10 finishes and
dlrs 853,818 in earnings this year, moved to the top of the
leaderboard by blasting out of a sand trap at No. 18 within two
feet (less than a meter) of the hole. He tapped in for a birdie
that left him with an 8-under 136 after two rounds.
	   ``I was very fortunate to finish like I did,'' Morgan said.
	   Eastwood breezed through the first 13 holes on a cloudy, breezy
day at five under before hitting a shot into Lake Windward at No.
14, resulting in a double-bogey. He bounced back to birdie the
final hole, finishing with a 4-under 68 for the round and tied with
Morgan.
	   Sixty-two-year-old Gary Player, seeking to become the
second-oldest player to win on the seniors tour, struggled with his
putter but was still in contention at 139, three shots off the
pace.
	   Player began the day tied with Morgan for the lead at five under
but settled for a second-round 72 after missing four birdie putts
inside of 10 feet (3 meters) on the back nine.
	   ``I played so well,'' Player said. ``I guess that's what makes
golf such a fascinating, humbling game.''
	   Jose Maria Canizares was alone in third with a 7-under 137,
while Player was one of four players at five under.
	   Heading into the final round, Morgan clearly had his eyes on
Irwin, who also has three victories this year (despite playing only
eight senior tournaments) and leads the money list with dlrs
1,051,850.
	   Irwin shot his second straight 70 and was just four shots off
the lead, part of a group at four-under.
	   ``He's still out there,'' Morgan said. ``He can catch up pretty
quick because he's such a good player. When I was standing there at
18, I looked at the scoreboard and wondered where Hale was.''
	   Player had three birdies on the front nine and stretched his
streak of bogey-free holes to 26 before running into trouble after
the turn. He had bogeys at 10 and 11 and scrambled for pars on the
next two holes, including a testy 4-footer (one-meter) at the par-3
13th after his tee shot barely cleared the water in front of the
green.
	   ``Wait till you get to 63 and see how tough it is,'' Player
quipped to the large gallery that followed him around the Golf Club
of Georgia.
	   Player, who actually turns 63 on Nov. 1, pulled his game
together and gave himself one birdie chance after another all the
way to the clubhouse.
	   But he couldn't convert any of them, missing from 5 feet (1.5
meters) at 14, 9 feet (3 meters) at 15, 5 feet (1.5 meters) at 17
and 8 feet (2.5 meters) on the final hole. The last two putts
lipped out of the hole.
	   ``Those putts were right in the hole and they came out,'' Player
moaned, shrugging his shoulders. ``What can you do?''
</TEXT>
