<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0690 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
training session; Alessandro Del Piero; Roberto Baggio 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Includes items on Turks and Caicos; ticket swindles; French
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Turks and Caicos, the island nation in the
Caribbean, will likely become the 200th member of FIFA,
international soccer's governing body.
	   The organization currently lists 197 member associations, and
the Palestinians _ who have provisional status _ are almost certain
to gain full membership at a FIFA congress on Monday. The official
agenda then calls for votes on Eritrea and, finally, Turks and
Caicos.
	   The archipelago, with a population of only 15,000 people, ``has
a sports infrastructure which leaves a great deal to be desired,''
said a FIFA statement. ``The association, however, is keen to
benefit from the islanders' enthusiasm for football, and promote
official structures.''
	   ____ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ Legal action may be taken against travel agents
selling non-existent game tickets, the World Cup organizing
committee warned.
	   ``Certain unscrupulous agents have undertaken to sell tickets
for World Cup matches, in sometimes unbelievable quantities, which
they are now unable to hand over to their buyers,'' the French
Organizing Committee (CFO) said Saturday.
	   The CFO singled out Great Portland Entertainments of England,
which reportedly sold 2.4 million pounds (dlrs 3.9 million) worth
of 40,000 tickets it could not supply.
	   In another case, a travel agent claimed to have purchased from
the Cameroon Federation tickets representing 15 percent of the
capacity of a stadium _ for a game in which Cameroon wasn't even
playing.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ David Trezeguet, the 20-year Monaco
striker, laid his claim for a starting place in France's World Cup
team scoring twice Saturday in a 3-1 win against Finnish champion
club HJK Helsinki.
	   Trezeguet scored the only goal Friday as France's probable team
for the World Cup game against South Africa next Wednesday downed
Finland 1-0.
	   France took on HJK on a sunny day in Kauniainen, outside
Helsinki in a training session consisting of three 30-minute
periods, refereed by France head coach Aime Jacquet. France fielded
a team of substitutes and non-playing reserves from Friday's match
against Finland.
	   ____ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Italy's World Cup star Alessandro Del
Piero said Tuesday he felt healed from a right thigh strain and
increasingly confident to regain his place on the team.
	   ``I believe it still can be Del Piero's World Cup,'' said the
young striker of Juventus of Turin, whose presence at France '98
had been put at risk by the injury suffered during the Champions
Cup final against Real Madrid last month.
	   However Del Piero looked tense and cautious as he kicked the
ball and joggled by his own during Italy's first training in
France, at the sports center of Senlis.
	   Team doctor Andrea Ferretti and coach Cesare Maldini both
confirmed that Del Piero's thigh lesion had disappeared.
	   ``He will begin tougher exercises with the teammates by Monday
to test his complete recovery under stress,'' said Maldini.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Fans were kept away, and parking of cars
was forbidden close to the walls of the sport center of Senlis
where Italy's World Cup team is preparing for the upcoming matches.
	   Tight security was common at all places hosting World Cup teams.
	   Policemen with dogs patrolled the center and put to flight two
intruders trying to reach Italy's training field through one of two
cemeteries adjacent to the sports center.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Italian veteran soccer star Roberto Baggio
was full of praise for cyclist Marco Pantani, who virtually
clinched the Tour of Italy on Saturday.
	   ``We both experienced a lot of sufferings and unexpected
comebacks. We proved you must never give up,'' said Baggio, who is
starting in his third World Cup after overcoming a streak of
injuries and controversy.
	   Pantani's career was nearly ended by two bad spills and a broken
leg in 1995.
</TEXT>
