<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-India-Pakistan,0733 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council urges India, Pakistan to halt nuclear tests 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECAPS previous
AP Photos NYR104-105
By ROBERT H. REID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The 15 members of the Security Council
have demanded in a unanimous vote that India and Pakistan refrain
from further nuclear tests, halt weapons programs and sign nuclear
control agreements unconditionally.
	   After Saturday's vote, non-nuclear states also sent a strong
message to the five major nuclear powers _ the United States,
Russia, China, France and Britain _ telling them to fulfill
commitments to reduce their own arsenals.
	   Islamic countries complained the council has ignored Israel's
refusal to sign arms control treaties or accept international
controls on its nuclear program. Israel has never acknowledged
having nuclear weapons but is believed to have the technology to
build them.
	   The Indian Foreign Ministry denounced the U.N. resolution as
``coercive and unhelpful'' and said ``we find it grotesque that an
organ of the United Nations should seek to address India in this
manner.''
	   Pakistan's ambassador, Ahmad Kamal, also spoke out against the
resolution.
	   ``Nonproliferation is no longer an issue in South Asia,'' he
said after the vote. ``There is a real danger of nuclear conflict''
and ``no amount of sermonizing and lamentations can rectify or
reverse this unfortunate development.''
	   He said Pakistan ``reserves the right... to deter aggression by
conventional weapons or non-conventional means.''
	   The resolution, co-sponsored by Japan, Slovenia, Sweden and
Costa Rica, denied India and Pakistan legal status as ``nuclear
powers.'' Formal status would enable them to keep their nuclear
arms under the 1970 Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
	   The resolution condemned the South Asian tests and urged India
and Pakistan to halt deployment of missiles capable of carrying
nuclear warheads and to sign nuclear arms control treaties.
	   It also called on India and Pakistan to exercise restraint and
find ``mutually acceptable solutions'' to the ``root causes of
those tensions, including Kashmir,'' the Himalayan territory
disputed by them.
	   Japanese Ambassador Hishashi Owada said the Indian and Pakistani
tests last month could plunge the international community ``into an
uncontrollable world of nuclear proliferation.''
	   U.S. Ambassador Bill Richardson echoed that remark, saying the
tests ``represent a profound blow'' to efforts to control nuclear
weapons.
	   South Korean Ambassador Lee See-Young said the council must act
decisively to avoid sending ``wrong messages to other parts of the
world,'' presumably North Korea.
	   But it was clear from the debate that while many nations oppose
the tests by India and Pakistan, they object to the way the
Security Council handled the issue.
	   Iran, Egypt, the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain accused it of
following a double-standard by ignoring Israel's suspected nuclear
weapons program.
	   ``We expect the Security Council to ... single out Israel to
adhere to this treaty,'' Egyptian Ambassador Nabil Elaraby said.
	   New Zealand's U.N. ambassador, Michael Powles, said nuclear arms
have ``no legitimate place in the world'' and that all states are
obliged to eliminate them. Australian envoy Penelope Anne Wensley
also encouraged nuclear states to do their part to promote
disarmanent.
	   The message underscored the challenge facing the major nuclear
powers in marshaling international pressure to curb the nuclear
arms race in South Asia.
	   Nuclear states agreed to take steps to reduce their arsenals as
part of a compromise to convince other nations to accept an
indefinite extension of the nonproliferation treaty three years
ago.
	   Also Saturday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan renewed his
offer to encourage India and Pakistan to resume a high-level
dialogue that broke down last year because of differences over
Kashmir.
	   ``I will continue my own efforts to encourage this dialogue in
the hope that it will reduce tensions and the danger of an
escalation in the nuclear arms race,'' Annan told the conference.
His offer was welcomed in the resolution.
	   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since they gained
independence from Britain in 1947 _ two of them over Kashmir, which
is physically divided between the two countries.
</TEXT>
