<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Korea,0485 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean president meets U,N. chief RECAPS previous for some points to UPDATE with more details. 
</HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Arriving on his first trip to the United
States since taking office, South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
briefed U.N. officials Saturday on plans for improving links to
communist North Korea.
	   The two countries have remained technically at war for a half
century.
	   Following a 45-minute meeting with Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and other U.N. officials, a U.N. statement said Kim ``focused on
relations between the two Koreas and on the new policy (of South
Korea) aimed at the development of peaceful relations between the
two states.''
	   The statement said Kim ``explained at length the steps being
taken with that objective in mind and the plans which he has for
facilitating this process.''
	   U.N. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Kim and
Annan also reviewed the situation in South Asia in the wake of last
month's nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
	   Before Kim arrived, the Security Council condemned the tests and
called on both countries to cease further testing and weapons
development. U.N. officials also have expressed concern that South
Asian testing might encourage North Korea to roll back on pledges
not to develop nuclear weapons.
	   The U.N. statement gave no details about Kim's plans for
improving ties with the North. A state of war remains in effect
since a 1953 armistice ended fighting in the Korean War.
	   Before leaving Seoul, however, Kim said South Korea would
support any moves by the United States to promote political and
economic detente with North Korea.
	   ``As was shown in the former Soviet Union and Eastern Europe,
the engagement policy of the United States and the sunshine policy
of the new South Korean government will be more effective for North
Korea,'' he said Friday.
	   He was expected to elaborate on that theme in Washington next
week when he meets with President Bill Clinton and addresses a
joint session of Congress. Under the Trading With the Enemy Act,
U.S. companies are prohibited from doing business with North Korea.
	   Kim, who took office last February, was a longtime opposition
figure who spent 7 1/2 years in prison or house arrest and four
years in exile under a succession of military dictators.
	   Those credentials could help encourage a reduction in mutual
hostility between the rival states.
	   After meeting with Annan, Kim attended a reception at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, which opens an exhibition of Korean art
next week.
	   He was to meet Sunday with Korean-Americans and receive an award
from the International League for Human Rights for his contribution
to civil liberties.
	   On Monday, he will address the Council on Foreign Relations
before traveling to Washington.
</TEXT>
