<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Porsches in control at halfway stage of Le Mans race 
</HEADLINE>
By ANDREAS EVAGORA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LE MANS, France (AP) - Porsche was closing in on its third
consecutive Le Mans triumph at the halfway point of the famed
endurance race Sunday morning, with two of its factory models well
ahead of the field.
	   After 12 hours of the race, a Porsche GT1 driven by Alan McNish
of Britain and France's Laurent Aiello and Stephane Ortelli was in
the lead, with 181 laps.
	   The car was less than one lap ahead of another Porsche, driven
by Jorg Muller and Uwe Alzen of Germany and France's Bob Wolleck.
	   In third place, on 178 laps, was the Nissan R390 driven by John
Nielsen, Franck Lagorce and Michael Krumm.
	   Less than a lap behind, in fourth, was the first prototype, the
Courage C51 driven by Didier Cottaz, Marc Goosens and Jean Philippe
Belloc.
	   But at the halfway stage it was Porsche, which dominated Le Mans
in the 1980s with seven straight wins, that seemed set for its 16th
overall race win and third victory in succession.
	   During the day, the race was contested in hot, dry conditions.
	   But thirty minutes before the halfway stage, rain started to
pour over the Le Mans course.
	   With the race being contested in darkness, teams were forced to
make a tough decision between using full wet or intermediate tires.
	   As the rains came, McNish completed a lap on slick tires before
the car changed to full wet tires and colleague Aiello took over.
	   ``It was a difficult decision to make between the two types of
tire,'' McNish said as he left his car. ``Whatever we do is a risk
because we can't see the clouds and so can't predict how long this
rain will last.''
	   A Toyota GT1 driven by Martin Brundle posted the fastest lap at
the halfway point.
	   Brundle's time of 3:41.809 in lap three was the fastest since
the course was slightly redesigned before last year's race.
	   But it was a Nissan R390 GT1 that was the closest challenger to
Porsche.
	   Nissan's good run included a triple stint from Franck Lagorce
through the late afternoon during which he completed 38 laps.
	   ``I was only scheduled to drive for two stints but I was
enjoying myself so much that I didn't want to get out of the car,''
Lagorce said. ``The car was exactly as we wanted.''
	   By midrace Sunday morning, 11 of the 47 starters had pulled out
of the race, including two cars each fielded by Mercedes and BMW.
	   After a good start, Mercedes driver Bernd Schneider, the fastest
driver in practice, was forced to withdraw within an hour, after a
steering pump led to an engine failure.
	   ``I thought we had a good chance to finish after all our good
testing results, where we didn't have any problems,'' Schneider
said. ``To retire after one hour is really disappointing.''
	   Mercedes was shaken by a second withdrawal when Jean Marc Gounon
had to pull out of the race with steering problems.
	   BMW also leaves this year's Le Mans disappointed.
	   Both its cars were pulled out within four hours because of a
loss of grease on wheelbearings.
	   ``This loss of lubrication would have eventually led to a wheel
bearing seizing up and this was too high a risk to take,'' said
Gabriele Rafanelli, BMW's race director.
	   (ae-sz)
</TEXT>
