<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA-Michelob Light,0534 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Andrews take second-round lead 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ST. LOUIS (AP) _ Donna Andrews is threatening to rain on Annika
Sorenstam's parade.
	   Andrews, who began the day at even par, shot a 6-under-par 66
Saturday to take a two-stroke lead over Sorenstam, the first-round
leader and defending champion in the rain-shortened LPGA Michelob
Light Classic.
	   After an opening 67, Sorenstam said the 6,337-yard (5,792-meter)
Forest Hills Country Club is like her home course. She is looking
to win the event for the third time in four years and she entered
the second round with a one-shot lead, but finished with a 73.
	   Andrews took advantage by making birdies from No. 11 through 14,
then making a 6-foot putt for birdie on No. 18 for a back nine of
31.
	   ``I really didn't hit the ball that great,'' Andrews said. ``I
mean, I hit 17 greens, so when I missed a shot, I still kept it on
the green. But I just got hot with my putter on the back side. I
was hitting my putts really solid and hitting them right where I
wanted to. As long as I had the speed right, they seemed to be
going in.''
	   Caroline McMillan and Cindy Figg-Currier were tied for third at
3-under 141. Amateur Marisa Baena, Sara Hallock and Lori West were
four strokes back.
	   Despite finishing over par on Saturday, Sorenstam feels she is
still playing well enough to win for the first time this year.
	   ``Yesterday was probably the best I've played in a long time,''
she said. ``Today, I was really happy with the way I was striking
the ball. I had one bad swing on No. 1, but other than that, I was
putting for par on every single hole.''
	   Andrews, a six-time winner, won the Longs Drugs Challenge in
April. She was not thinking about winning this event until she hit
the back nine Saturday.
	   ``I didn't really look at the leaderboard until I made the turn.
I made the turn at one under and was actually surprised to see that
one under was on the leaderboard,'' she said. ``I thought, `If I
could go out and shoot a couple under on the back side, I'd be
right in this thing.'''
	   But Sorenstam will not be easy to beat.
	   ``I know I can do it on this course. I've done it before,'' she
said. ``Today could have been a good round if I would have made
some putts. Hopefully, tomorrow I'll hit the ball the same and I
will make the putts. I think that will be difference.''
	   The 21-year-old Baena, who just finished her junior year at
Arizona, is attempting to become the first amateur to win an LPGA
tour event since JoAnne Carner won the Burdines Invitational in
1969.
	   ``Tomorrow is going to be really interesting because today, I
putted so good, and yesterday, I didn't,'' said Baena, who followed
Friday's round of 69 with a 73. ``I'm kind of excited to see (what
happens) tomorrow. My putting is so much better and I think that
gives you confidence.''
	   Sorenstam said that the fact that Baena is an amateur is
irrelevant.
	   ``Obviously, she's playing well and that's what I look at. I
want to beat the players that are playing the best this particular
week. Whether she's an amateur or not doesn't mean anything.''
</TEXT>
