<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike,0470 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Both sides in Air France strike show willingness to begin new talks 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECAPS previous
AP Photos PAR107-109
By DEBORAH SEWARD
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Both sides in a strike by Air France pilots on
Sunday showed a willingness to begin new talks aimed at ending the
walkout ahead of the World Cup.
	   Airline officials said Saturday evening that they were in
contact with the pilots about resuming negotiations but that no new
talks had yet been set. Prime Minister Lionel Jospin also said
Saturday the government was prepared to intervene but no concrete
proposals have yet emerged.
	   Talks between Air France and the pilots were suspended Saturday
after the pilots walked out of negotiations.
	   The pilots appeared divided about new talks, with the head of
the main pilots' union indicating a new round could take place
Monday and a spokesman saying they could resume over the weekend.
	   Both sides were under pressure to end the strike from the
government, worried about France's image and embarrassed by the
strike, which has threatened to tarnish the world soccer
championship that opens Wednesday.
	   Air France is the official World Cup carrier and is committed to
transporting the teams from one venue to another.
	   The pilots were protesting pay cuts planned by Air France, which
is currently restructuring and needs to free up capital to
modernize the company and its planes.
	   Talks between Air France management and the striking pilots
broke off Saturday after all night negotiations.
	   The stumbling blocks remained planned salary cuts and an Air
France proposal to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay
reductions, as well as a two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots
earn less.
	   During the day, Jospin met with the head of Air France, as well
as his finance and transport ministers. He said the French
government was ready to help end the strike, and there have been
suggestions the government may name a mediator.
	   The World Cup will take place ``normally,'' Jospin said.
``French people don't need to take a plane to attend the World Cup.
Nor do Europeans, and we are going to find a lot of airline
companies to transport the rest at the expense of Air France.''
	   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, the Air France president, said there had
been ``very positive advances'' in the talks.
	   The pilots appeared more pessimistic, with a leader of one of
the smaller unions saying Air France's proposals were unacceptable.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Sunday. Meanwhile, a train strike disrupted provincial
service and service was expected Sunday in some areas.
	   Once the air strike ends, Air France says it will take three
days for service to be restored fully to normal. 	   
</TEXT>
