<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections,0379 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beirut fears losing its sectarian balance in municipal polls 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Polls open at 0400 GMT
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ The danger of losing this capital city's
sectarian balance was at stake in Sunday's municipal elections.
	   Prime Minister Rafik Hariri has appealed to voters not to ignore
candidates from the Christian minority when they elect a new city
council for this city of Sunni Muslim majority.
	   ``Let's maintain the national balance and give mutual
coexistence top consideration when voting,'' said Hariri, a Sunni
Muslim who has endorsed a slate of candidates that includes
Christians, Sunnis and Shiite Muslims.
	   Beirut, the city where the civil war of 1975-90 began, elected a
half-Muslim, half-Christian council in its last local elections 35
years ago. But the city's demography has since changed in favor of
the Muslims.
	   A similar shift has occurred in the northern city of Tripoli,
which on May 31, in the second stage of the four-stage polls,
reduced its Christian minority to a mere one member on its council.
	   Christian politicians have voiced fears that their sect will
similarly become marginalized in Beirut's elections.
	   With the memories of the civil war in mind, Muslim clerics
joined Hariri in urging their followers not to be too partisan in
their voting in Beirut.
	   In the other part of the country voting on Sunday, the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah and the pro-Syrian Amal parties are vying
for the votes of southern Lebanon.
	   All attempts to get the two Shiite groups to agree on a joint
ticket failed.
	   Hezbollah, whose guerrillas are the most active opponents of the
Israeli occupation of part of southern Lebanon, hopes the polls
will consolidate its claim to lead the 1.2 million Shiites, the
country's largest single sect.
	   No elections will be held in the zone which Israeli troops and
their Lebanese militia allies have controlled since 1985 to try to
prevent guerrilla attacks on northern Israel.
	   The municipal polls, widely seen as extending democracy after
the civil war, began in Mount Lebanon province on May 24. They are
scheduled to end in the eastern Bekaa Valley on June 14.
</TEXT>
