<SLUG> BC-Mexico-US,0230 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican senators threaten to call off meeting with U.S. counterparts 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexican senators are threatening to cancel a
meeting with their U.S. counterparts this month unless the U.S.
Senate majority leader apologizes for criticizing Mexico's
president.
	   The conflict is over a U.S. money-laundering sting dubbed
``Operation Casablanca'' in which U.S. agents made dozens of
arrests and seized millions of dollars in drug profits.
	   After first praising the operation, Mexican officials _
including President Ernesto Zedillo _ have condemned it, saying
U.S. undercover agents appear to have operated in Mexico without
the government's knowledge. Sting operations are illegal in Mexico.
	   Mexico has lodged a formal protest with the United States.
	   In a letter made public Friday, American Sen. Trent Lott told
Zedillo the criticism contrasted with the pledges the president had
made about how he intended to crack down on drug kingpins.
	   ``It should be welcomed by all governments interested in
combating those who profit from trafficking in illegal narcotics,''
Lott wrote.
	   Mexican senators from all three major parties condemned the
letter as insulting, Mexican news media reported.
	   Mexican senators will vote Tuesday on whether to cancel the
Interparliamentary Meeting with U.S. lawmakers.
</TEXT>
