<HEADLINE>
Japan seen extending new aid loan to Malaysia: report 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan will likely agree to a request from Malaysia
to resume economic assistance, four years after the Southeast Asian
nation accepted what was to be its last Japanese aid loan package,
a local newspaper said Sunday.
	   Malaysia has requested the aid, which is expected to total
several billion yen (dlrs several tens of million) in loans,
because his country has been hit hard by a region-wide economic
crisis, the Yomiuri newspaper reported, citing unnamed government
sources.
	   On Friday, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who
visited Tokyo earlier in the week, said he expected to get dlrs 1-2
billion worth of loans in Japanese yen.
	   During his stay in Japan, Mahathir criticized Western-based
financial aid institutions such as the International Monetary Fund
for being insensitive to Asian people.
	   Japan has long been an important donor to Malaysia, but in 1994
the Malaysian government indicated it would no longer require
Japanese aid loans, citing difficulties in repaying borrowed yen
due to the rapid appreciation of Japan's currency.
	   In recent months the yen has weakened dramatically, falling to
six-year lows against the U.S. dollar.
