<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Soundtracks,1027 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No longer in background, movie music now big business AP Entertainment Writer 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo NY456
By MICHAEL FLEEMAN
<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ The alternative rock group Filter grinds out
a gritty version of Three Dog Night's ``One'' on ``The X-Files''
movie soundtrack. But for this sci-fi hit, the magic number is
really four.
	   That's how many albums have been produced by the film and TV
versions of ``The X-Files,'' including two movie soundtracks
released last week _ one with songs, the other with Mark Snow's
creepy score, fleshed out for the movie with an 85-piece orchestra.
	   It's testimony not only to the success of ``The X-Files,'' which
hits theaters June 19, but to the explosive popularity of movie
music, led in recent times by the ``Titanic'' album, a huge success
with 25 million discs sold worldwide.
	   ``We are in the longest continuous cycle of successful
soundtrack releases we've ever had since the modern era dawned with
'Saturday Night Fever' (in 1977),'' said Glen Brunman, who heads
the industry leader, Sony Music Soundtrax. It has the soundtracks
for the summer event movies: ``Godzilla'' and ``Armageddon.''
	   Movie soundtracks have always been popular, especially musicals
like ``The Sound of Music'' and ``South Pacific,'' and many have
produced hit singles: ``Moon River,'' ``Theme From a Summer
Place,'' ``All the Way,'' among them. Some of the biggest selling
soundtrack albums have included ``Purple Rain,'' ``The Lion King,''
``The Bodyguard'' and ``Saturday Night Fever.''
	   Theories abound as to why soundtracks are selling so well today,
be it better music, bigger movies or just momentum. Even more
puzzling is the reason behind the popularity of orchestral scores.
	   Composer agent Richard Kraft suggested that audiences are
cooling to the cynicism and grunge of pop and are looking for an
old-fashioned emotional rush.
	   ``I think people are increasingly becoming tired of (musicians)
who are too cool for the room,'' said Kraft. ``'Titanic' really
tapped into people's desire for emotional connection. People are
craving emotional, instrumental music.''
	   The question is when will it all cool down. For the moment,
nobody seems to know; they're too busy selling records.
	   The ``Titanic'' album followed the 20 million-selling ``The
Bodyguard'' soundtrack. Other recent multimillion sellers include
the soundtracks for ``City of Angels,'' ``Forrest Gump,'' ``Men in
Black'' and ``Sleepless in Seattle.'' And television has cashed in
on the wave; the ``Ally McBeal'' album debuted at No. 7 on the
charts.
	   ``The X-Files'' isn't the only movie with multiple soundtracks.
DreamWorks' Christmas release, the animated feature ``Prince of
Egypt,'' will have three soundtracks, including the traditional
disc with music from the movie and two soundtracks ``inspired by''
the film _ one with country music, the other rhythm and blues.
	   The huge sales have both padded the wallets of already
successful recording artists who contribute songs, and sent the
salaries of movie score composers soaring. The best can now command
dlrs 1 million per film or more.
	   James Horner, who did the ``Titanic'' score, could make as much
as dlrs 30 million, industry sources estimated, with additional
money rolling in from his movie score albums for ``Deep Impact''
and the upcoming ``The Mask of Zorro.''
	   Indeed, the fact that movie composers can even get their own
albums, as opposed to a couple of throwaway tracks on a songs disc,
speaks to the public's appetite for film music, observers say.
	   ``Film composers who sort of toiled in the background in their
dark little rooms have gotten the recognition they are due,'' said
Kraft, whose Kraft-Benjamin Agency clients include Danny Elfman
(``Batman,'' ``Men in Black'') and Elmer Bernstein (``The Ten
Commandments,'' ``Devil in a Blue Dress'').
	   But the success has brought complaints, particularly from some
studio executives in this semi-cost-conscious era in Hollywood,
whose worries about dlrs 10 million to dlrs 20 million actors are
suddenly compounded by dlrs 1 million composers. Record companies,
too, are facing increased costs for production, rights and
promotion.
	   But all this, explained Sony's Brunman, is just basic economics.
	   ``There is no doubt in the world of soundtracks, like all other
worlds, the law of supply and demand rules,'' he said. ``There is a
tremendous demand now for soundtracks, a tremendous demand for
artists to do those soundtracks and tremendous demand for great
composers with great scores. So the prices go up.''
	   Another problem is that the increasingly expensive soundtracks
can be riskier than regular recordings since they're often one-shot
deals instead of record franchises by artists with fan bases.
	   And as the number of soundtracks increases _ 36 expected this
summer _ the talent supply is running thin, said David Was, who
shares executive producer credits on the ``X-Files'' albums with
the show's creator, Chris Carter.
	   Was can rattle off stories of big-name groups trying to unload
B-side material onto movie soundtracks, and laments it's getting
increasingly harder to find new artists or established groups that
haven't already committed to other soundtracks.
	   ``There's no fresh kill around to put in your knapsack,'' he
said.
	   Not that this problem has slowed things down _ yet.
	   ``The record companies are in a fever now with soundtracks,''
said Was, ``and they'll continue to be until the one hit doesn't
pay for the eight misses. And maybe that may never happen. It'll
(continue) until you somehow run out of bands to put on these
things.''
	   For composers like Snow, the 51-year-old veteran of the TV music
trade with credits that include ``Hart to Hart'' and ``Crazy Like a
Fox,'' the current climate couldn't be better, for he knows there's
no formula and the success may not last.
	   ``The first thing you have to think about is the movie, and how
it works,'' he said. ``You have to serve the movie first, and if
you're lucky enough _ and it's really luck when the thing takes off
as a record _ it's beautiful.''
</TEXT>
