<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Badi Assad,0834 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guitar virtuoso Badi Assad finds freedom in a new, universal sound AP National Writer 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo NY310
By TODD LEWAN
<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ This music takes you places ...
	   To a corner of the rain forest, where a hummingbird hovers
beside a droplet-laden petal. To an immense sea, where rhythm is
measured by the lapping of waves on blushing sand. To a lofty
mountain, where a whispering wind wakes the pines.
	   A force in the guitar world at 30, Assad (pronounced Ah-SAHj)
has won prizes and critical acclaim in Europe and the United States
for her impressive fingerstyle, snappy lines and harmonically and
texturally complex material.
	   Now, with the release of her fourth album, ``Chameleon,'' which
industry insiders are touting as one of the freshest musical
offerings in years, more than just guitar buffs are listening to
Assad's mood-compelling music.
	   ``As far as most of the world is concerned, Brazilian music got
stuck in the 1960s _ bossa nova, Gilberto Gil, Caetano Veloso,''
Assad says in her native language, Portuguese. ``Well, it didn't
get stuck. There's a whole new generation of Brazilian musicians
out there, and I'm part of it.''
	   The first Brazilian to record with a major American label _
Polygram _ since the end of the 1964-1985 military dictatorship,
Assad creates her revolutionary sound by cross-pollinating pop,
classical, jazz, flamenco, African and Brazilian styles.
	   On ``Chameleon,'' she adds an earthy texture by using gold and
wood flutes, the Australian didgeridoo, a string quartet, acoustic
bass and a battery of percussion devices, from Peruvian llama
hooves to deer-skinned ``Taos'' drums. What emerges is a style so
original that classifying it seems pointless _ though listeners
sometimes try.
	   ``I don't want to be confined to some marketing category like
world music, pop, jazz, or whatever,'' Assad says in a speaking
voice much like her clear and honeyed singing voice. ``My music
tries to break down walls between man, music, nature and
spirituality. It doesn't fit inside any one box. It fits into many
boxes.''
	   The root of Assad's music is a classical fingerstyle, a
technique so mastered that, even during her most intense
crescendos, her fingers seem to flutter over the nylon strings like
butterflies.
	   She may, at any time, turn the guitar into a percussion
ensemble, tapping or knuckling the body with one hand while playing
a bass line with the other. She also generates rhythmic sounds by
slapping, whacking and striking her nose, throat and cheeks.
	   ``People say, 'Why is this woman beating her face?''' Assad
says. And then she giggles. ``But many people make sounds using
their faces. I've just put them together into music. The human
voice is the richest instrument. We haven't begun to explore all it
can do musically. I never feel ashamed when I'm exploring.''
	   The ``sonic journey,'' as she calls it, began for Maria Angela
Assad at age 13 in Rio de Janeiro. Her father, Jorge, a clock
repairman who made extra money playing ``bandolim'' _ a Brazilian
mandolin _ had enlisted Assad's older brothers, Sergio and Odair,
to accompany him on guitar at parties and restaurants.
	   ``'You can't do this, you're a girl,' my father told me,'' Assad
recalls. ``He was used to having the boys play with him. So I
taught myself the guitar, because I thought my brothers got his
attention because they played. I thought, this is how I will touch
my father.''
	   Her mother soon nicknamed the slight teen-ager with the full
mane of bouncy, black curls ``Badi'' (pronounced BAH-Jee) _ magical
lion. Says Assad: ``There's some of that in my personality _
fighting for the right to follow what's inside you, not being
afraid to show who you are.''
	   Months later, Assad moved with her parents to Sao Joao da Boa
Vista, an outback in the farming belt around Sao Paulo. Her
brothers stayed in Rio to study classical music _ they've become a
world-class concert duo _ so Assad took up the duty of playing
alongside her father.
	   The rugged country around Sao Joao da Boa Vista, with its
waterfalls, ravines and forest-draped hills, had an impact on the
slight, shy teen-ager. Today, she derives the energy to compose
from ``the soul of nature, be it the wings of a butterfly, the
surge of the tide, the force of the wind.''
	   Assad shuns electronic instruments in her recordings. ``The idea
is to make the connection that must exist between humans and Earth.
The acoustic instruments give you the vibration, the depth, the
soul of the Earth.''
	   At 17, Assad returned to Rio to study classical music. Soon she
was performing alongside Pat Metheny, Dori Caymmi, Hermeto and
Milton Nascimento and winning awards, including best Brazilian
guitar player at the International Villa-Lobos Festival. ``I wanted
to be like my brothers, so I spent 15 hours a day playing guitar.
But I studied the technical aspects of guitar too much. I lost the
heart of the instrument.''
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-Badi Assad; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
