<HEADER>
w2959 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-US-BadiAssad 1stAdd   06-06 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Badi Assad, 1st Add,0294 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK: the instrument.'' 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   That realization struck her during a bus ride to Chile, where
she was to represent Brazil in a competition. Actually, she did the
striking. ``I don't know why, but all of a sudden I just smashed my
hand, mechanically, against the side of the bus and it swelled up
into a knot. At that precise moment, I knew that I had been given a
warning from a greater force.''
	   She played at the contest, then dropped out of college, took
private acting and voice lessons and married a Sao Paulo
businessman who was almost 30 years her senior. In 1989, her
husband asked her to make a record so he could give copies to his
employees as Christmas gifts. From this sprang ``Danca dos Tons''
(``Dance of Sounds''), her first album.
	   Assad divorced several years later, but the records kept coming:
She released ``Solo'' in 1994, ``Rhythms'' in 1995, and ``Echoes of
Brazil'' in 1996. Along the way she developed mouth percussive
techniques and African ``polyrhythms.''
	   ``Somewhere inside of me I've got Africa,'' she says. ``The
songs, the rhythm, the smells, the soul. I listen to so much
African music _ Lokua Kanza from the Congo, for one _ that it has
to come out of me somehow.''
	   Sony liked the new sound and offered her a multimillion-dollar
contract _ with a catch: The company wanted to market her as a pop
singer. She refused. ``It was like asking me to sell my soul,'' she
says.
	   Assad says maintaining the integrity of her music is the goal,
not fame.
	   ``Artists are not here to get famous,'' she says. ``You are at
the service of something greater, a greater meaning. When you are
on stage you are a reflection of the light in the audience. You are
not THE light.''
</TEXT>
