<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Peter Weir,0825 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The who, what, when, Weir, and why of `The Truman Show' 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: 'The Truman Show' opened June 5.
AP Photo NY348
By DOUGLAS J. ROWE
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Peter Weir talked to his agent and anyone else
who would listen about coming up with a solid screenplay.
	   ``Let's look under the carpet, get people to open their bottom
drawers, send me things that are really in poor shape, rather than
something green-lit with an actor attached, because they're often
bland, because they've gone through all the processes,'' the
53-year-old Australian director told his agent.
	   ``I said `Tell the studios and producers that they don't need to
offer me something that's ready to go. I'm happy to look at things
that might need a year's work on them.' At least I might find
something interesting.''
	   One person who listened to Weir was Scott Rudin. The producer of
such films as ``In and Out,'' ``Ransom'' and ``The First Wives
Club'' sent him ``The Truman Show,'' written by Andrew Niccol
(``Gattaca''). Weir was impressed with the originality of the story
about a man whose entire life is telecast as a hugely popular
24-hour-a-day TV show _ unbeknownst to its 30-year-old star, Truman
Burbank.
	   Weir says the only way he could begin thinking about the movie
was to imagine ``Who could be Truman?''
	   ``You just can't even begin without having that face in your
mind,'' he said. ``And I thought it had to be a star, because that
was part of the logic why they watched the show all this time.''
	   Only three actors came to mind in 1995 when he first started
casting about: Tom Cruise, Tom Hanks and Brad Pitt. Then Rudin
suggested Jim Carrey, who rose to stardom with the ``Ace Ventura''
movies, ``The Mask'' and ``Dumb and Dumber'' but came a cropper in
``The Cable Guy.''
	   Weir was intrigued by the idea of the pet detective becoming the
True Man of his Kafkaesque concoction because he considers Carrey
``a brilliant comic, up there with Chaplin and Keaton.''
	   ``I always thought of him as a sort of silent star, because he
would have been a star in that era. It wasn't dependent on verbal
dexterity, dialogue.''
	   But Weir wondered what success had done to Carrey, whose films
have exceeded dlrs 1 billion at the box office worldwide.
	   ``Is he the same guy? I sensed this recklessness about his work.
Is that something that he just used to catapult him into the arena?
And now he's had success, he may be conservative in his approach.
And I needed someone who's absolutely fearless.''
	   Carrey allayed Weir's fears once they met.
	   And Weir says he never thought twice about how Carrey's track
record mainly consisted of comedy.
	   ``I know my film history,'' Weir says, noting that Charlie
Chaplin moved from being the Little Tramp into drama. ``Who would
ever have wished that he stayed in one-reel comedies?''
	   He came across a film titled ``Doing Time on Maple Drive,'' in
which he felt Carrey did a fine job in a serious role. And he says
he didn't fret about casting Carrey because it was not a
conventional film.
	   ``This man was meant to be unknowing,'' Weir said. ``He didn't
know he was being photographed, didn't know he was performing. So
there were no rules. We could just make the rules up. So any
limitation in his ability I could handle by doing it another way.''
	   If Weir succeeds, this would be the fourth time he has directed
a transformational role for an actor who previously was seen as
limited.
	   Mel Gibson became more than the road warrior Mad Max in the 1981
war movie ``Gallipoli''; Harrison Ford showed he could be more than
a ``Star Wars'' warrior in ``Witness,'' the 1985 cop thriller/love
story, and, as Weir himself notes, Robin Williams soared from his
stand-up persona as the teacher in 1989 in ``Dead Poets Society.''
	   ``They were looking for change,'' Weir says about all three
actors. ``It's quite exciting when someone's looking to break out
of their mold, their safe area. If they're willing to take a risk,
it's a form of energy really. To generalize, you can find that it's
like they're making their first movie. And I love that. I love that
feeling of double or nothing.''
	   Now Carrey is getting raves and magazine covers _ as if he now
has the heft of a Hanks.
	   Weir, whose two children are grown now and who still lives in
Sydney with his wife, realized the marketing department might have
a big job on their hands, selling an offbeat movie with Carrey, but
that was their job.
	   ``My job was to make a film that people want to see,'' he says.
``Then you think if it's a good movie, people will go. `If you
build it, they will come.'''
	   Still, Weir concedes that two factions have to be sold on this
movie: Carrey fans who might not want to see him in a dramatic role
and serious moviegoers who might not want to see Carrey, period.
	   ``I hope we haven't fallen between the bar stools.''
</TEXT>
