<SLUG> BC-ARTS-China-Painting Duo,0798 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Painters looking at Beijing's restless urbanites 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos NY450-1
By RENEE SCHOOF
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Like any gritty metropolis, Beijing gives its
citizens plenty to fret about. Job security, low rents and the
city's historic elegance are vanishing, while traffic, pollution
and consumerism intensify.
	   Liu Qinghe and Chen Shuxia, husband and wife, are painters in
their 30s who are taking a fresh look at chaotic urban life in
China.
	   Liu, one of the country's leading young artists, uses
traditional Chinese ink and wash _ the centuries-old medium in
scroll paintings of mountains and villages _ to paint pictures of
city people.
	   The original use of an old form makes Liu unusual among
contemporary Chinese painters.
	   Chinese artists today take for granted the freedom they have had
for more than a decade in choosing styles and subjects.
	   Until the late 1970s, socialist realism in support of the
government's political aims was the rule. Today, only pornography
and works that overtly call for the downfall of China's communist
leaders are off-limits.
	   Once Chinese painters got the freedom to experiment, many began
to imitate well-known modern Western painters.
	   Liu started out rejecting the Chinese painting he learned as a
child because its traditional subjects seemed irrelevant. He
studied Western oil painting in art school in the 1980s, but
decided he wasn't any good at it.
	   ``After I graduated, I realized that Chinese things suited me
better,'' he said in an interview in his office at the Central
Academy of Fine Arts, a room just big enough for a bed, books, a
desk and an easel.
	   Liu's style of painting modern urban themes in bold ink lines
and soft ink washes has proved a success. He spent a one-year
residency at the Royal Academy of Fine Art in Madrid in 1992. Since
then, his paintings have sold to collectors around the world.
	   In ``Evening Breeze,'' recently shown at the respected Red Gate
Gallery in Beijing, where Liu is represented, two young women _ one
in shorts and a tight knit top, the other in a chemise and floral
skirt _ sit on the thick cement posts of a chain barricade, staring
out to sea. Pale orange undertones tint the sky, the reflection of
the water, the stone slabs on the ground.
	   As in many of Liu's works, the poses and expressions suggest
unease. In the background, a man with wide, wild eyes stares away
from the women, toward the viewer.
	   One critic, Li Shaowen, described Liu's works as telling
``ordinary stories happening in the metropolitan city, in a tone as
calm as the writing of Chekhov, as if he is leading the viewers
away from the steamy downtown into a small area of shade...''
	   Liu said his work is intended to examine the struggles of urban
people.
	   ``They have a feeling of urgency pressing on them,'' he said.
``They're more educated and worldly than Chinese in the
countryside, but that doesn't make them more relaxed. It just
leaves them overworked and rundown.''
	   ``Hardly anyone in Beijing these days is at peace,'' adds Liu's
wife, Chen Shuxia, who is somewhat more serious and quiet than her
fast-talking, jovial husband.
	   In Chen's ``Bright Sunshine,'' a man and a woman sit at a small
outdoor cafe table under a white umbrella, each looking solemnly in
different directions, each _ much like Liu and Chen themselves _
wearing simple, modern clothes that would fit in anywhere.
	   Liu said he and his wife are careful to avoid critiquing each
other's paintings because as a couple they have so much emotional
influence over each other. They share many basic likes and dislikes
about painting, including a distaste for political art.
	   Liu says politically inclined art, even when it is meant to
tweak the government, still seems akin to the rigidly
propagandistic works of the ultra-leftist 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution.
	   ``I don't think there's any need to paint political works,'' Liu
said. ``I'm not interested in it. My paintings, and Chen Shuxia's
too, are peaceful.''
	   Both Liu and Chen lament Beijing's worsening air pollution and
the loss of its traditional architecture, which has been replaced
with a jumble of boxy high-rises.
	   They live with their 7-year-old daughter on the edge of the
city, still in the pollution and sprawl but far enough from the
center that, Liu says, ``you can hear the pigs snorting if the
night is quiet.''
	   ``We both like tranquility. We don't get involved in politics,
and we don't think about the business end of painting very much,''
Chen said.
	   ``We put a lot of energy into protecting a tranquil state of
mind. That way, when I'm finished with a painting, if I can't sell
it today, I'm still willing to paint tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-China-Painting Duo; CT:i; 
