</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-New Algonquin,0576 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Old Algonquin hotel is new again 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos Photos NY453-4
By BETH GARDINER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ ``Look at him, a rhinestone in the rough.''
	   Immortal words? Maybe. Cruel, certainly. And for those with a
literary bent, unmistakably from the golden age of the Algonquin
hotel, a time when the country's brightest literary lights gathered
for drinks and never-ending turns of phrase.
	   With a dlrs 5.5 million makeover, the new owners of the
venerable 96-year-old hotel hope to recapture the flavor of those
long hours spent at the famed Round Table and market them to
customers seeking a taste of times past.
	   ``Every successful hotel tries to find and identify a niche that
separates it from the competition,'' said Ian Lloyd-Jones, a Briton
and president of the Atlanta-based Camberly Hotel Company, which
bought the Algonquin last year.
	   ``Most hotels try to do it with the fine dining room or the
spa,'' he said. ``Here, the engine that drives the hotel is
intelligent entertainment.''
	   In its heyday in 1920s and '30s, Dorothy Parker, Robert
Benchley, James Thurber and their cleverer-than-thou crowd of
writers, artists and journalists spent lunches and evenings besting
one another's witticisms, nursing drinks and collecting anecdotes
that often ended up in print.
	   But those years were over before the end of World War II. With
several recent movies and books celebrating those days, the owners
sought to recapture a sense of the group's style.
	   The Round Table _ where Parker (responsible for the ``rhinestone
in the rough'' toss-off) and pals like Alexander Woollcott, George
S. Kaufman and Harold Ross gathered nightly to trade gibes and
jokes in the 1920s and '30s _ has become the centerpiece of the
dark and cozy lobby.
	   But like much in the hotel, the dark wooden table is a replica,
not the original.
	   ``We've tried to stay true to the traditions,'' Lloyd-Jones
said. ``This does look like it's back in the '30s. It doesn't look
like it was just renovated.''
	   Designers pored through turn-of-the-century photos of the hotel,
refurbished antique chairs and put together wallpaper patterned
with cartoons from The New Yorker magazine, several of them poking
fun at famous Algonquin characters.
	   While they saved a version of the Round Table, the new owners
eliminated the old Rose Room, the hotel restaurant where the
literary crowd ate, drank and talked.
	   Still, the hotel on West 44th Street, between Times Square and
Grand Central station, remains devoted to the written word and the
art of talking.
	   Once, when the hotel hired musicians to play a cocktail party, a
guest complained, Lloyd Jones recalled. When the music stopped, the
guest said, ```Listen. What do you hear?'
	   ``I said, `A lot of conversation.' He said, `That's the music of
the Algonquin.' And a light bulb went off.''
	   Camberly, which bought the Algonquin from the Aoki Corp., hopes
to capitalize on the hotel's history by inviting authors for public
readings and holding classical music performances.
	   Richard Hubert of Atlanta has been coming to the hotel with his
wife, Linda, since the 1960s precisely because it reminds him of an
era gone by.
	   ``Hotels are big commercial things these days, and they whisk
you in and out of the lobby,'' he said. ``You come in here and sit
down and have a drink, and they treat you in a civilized manner.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-New Algonquin; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
