<HEADLINE>
APTV 0100 GMT Outlook    APTV 0100 OUTLOOK SUNDAY JUNE 7 1998    For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the next 12 hours. All times are GMT.  ---- EXPECTED: ---- US: SOUTH KOREA - President Kim Dae-jung has arrived in the U-S for a nine-day trip to the United States, where he will seek more economic assistance and propose a new policy of engagement toward North Korea. APTV has coverage of his arrival in New York and his meeting with U-N Secretary-General Kofi Annan. We also expect coverage of Kim attending an award ceremony at the international league for human rights. ---- INDONESIA: HABIBIE TOWN - APTV has a feature from President Habibie's hometown - Pare-Pare on the island of Sulawesi. We speak to his childhood friends and see how the village is relishing its link with the country's new president. (ASIA PACIFIC LATE 0715) ---- INDONESIA: HABIBIE - APTV has highlights of President Habibie's first ever interview with the Indonesian media. In his answers, the president commented on political reforms, insisted on a lawful inquiry into corruption under his predecessor and gave his opinion on the IMF programme. (AFTER EUROPE EARLY 0300)  INDONESIA: TRIAL - Two policemen accused in the killing of four student protesters have been arraigned in a military court in what defence lawyers described as a hasty, misguided attempt to satisfy public demand for reform. APTV has coverage of the court proceedings and file of the shooting. (AFTER EUROPE EARLY 0300) ---- SOUTH AFRICA: RHINO DUNG - Not content with using ordinary paper, one artist in South Africa is going to the extraordinary length of having paper specially made from rhinoceros dung. APTV has the story of Deryck Healey and his ``recycled'' art. (EUROPE EARLY 0300) ---- WORLD CUP: ST DENIS - The Paris suburb of Saint Denis - where the 1998 World Cup final will be staged - has held a late-night ceremony to symbollically inaugurate the official celebrations. APTV has coverage. (EUROPE EARLY 0300) ---- RUNNING: ---- UN: NUCLEAR - The Security Council on Saturday demanded that India and Pakistan refrain from further nuclear tests, halt weapons programmes and sign nuclear control agreements unconditionally. APTV has coverage of the vote and comments from the U-N ambassadors from the U-S, Britain and Pakistan. (FIRST RUN LATIN AMERICA 1900) ---- RUSSIA: MIR - The last U-S astronaut on the Mir space station said joint crew training before blast-off will be crucial to the success of the new international space station Alpha. Andrew Thomas was speaking during a live link-up before flying back to Earth on the U-S space shuttle Discovery. (FIRST RUN NORTHAM UPDATE 1830) ---- US: HOLOCAUST - It's a Holocaust story that many of us have never heard. Between 1938 and 1940, Britain rescued some 10-thousand Jewish children from Europe, saving them from the Nazi concentration camps where their parents were sent. APTV talks to survivors of the so-called ``Kindertransport'' and has coverage of their annual reunion in Washington D-C. (FIRST RUN NORTHAM LATE 1930) ---- ALBANIA: REFUGEES - APTV has pictures of the stream of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo fleeing over the hills to the safety of nearby Albania. The packages also includes coverage of the humanitarian relief effort. (FIRST RUN 1640 F-L-A-S-H) ---- WORLD CUP: VERON - Argentinian football player Juan Veron and his coach Daniel Passarella on Saturday vehemently denied reports from a radio station in Argentina that Veron had failed an internal doping test. APTV footage of the Argentinian team in training and comments by both Veron and his coach. (FIRST RUN 2045 F-L-A-S-H) ---- DENMARK: WEDDING - Princess Alexandra of Berleburg, Queen Margrethe's niece, has exchanged vows with German count Jefferson Friederich von Pfeil und Klein-Ellgut. APTV has coverage of the royal wedding ceremony. (FIRST RUN NORTHAM UPDATE 1830)  ---- MEXICO: CATHEDRAL - Mexico City Metropolitan cathedral, the largest church in the Americas, is finally being set straight after years of sinking into moist clay. APTV's feature includes soundbites from the architect who heads the restoration team. (FIRST RUN LATIN AMERICA 1900) ---- BOLIVIA: JAIL - APTV has been granted a rare glimpse of life behind the bars of Bolivia's highest security prison, Chonchocoro, which is home to several key figures in Bolivia's recent troubled past. (FIRST RUN LATIN AMERICA 1900) ---- Editor of the Night: 44 171 427 4163 Master Control Room - 44 171 427 4131 ---- APTV 
</HEADLINE>
