<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Scott Bairstow,0651 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five questions with Scott Bairstow: a young hunk and old soul AP Television Writer 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo NY457
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ If Scott Bairstow, at 28, seems to have a
touch of the old soul about him, consider this: He's been a working
actor since childhood, has been married four years and has a young
son.
	   That knowing quality was most recently on display in
``Significant Others,'' the short-lived Fox series that apparently
went a little too heavy on youthful angst for TV viewers.
	   Bairstow, however, was appealing as ever. His talent and hunky
blond looks have won him roles in the films ``White Fang 2: Myth of
the White Wolf,'' ``The Postman'' and ``Wild America,'' and on
television in ``Lonesome Dove: The Series'' and the movie, ``Two
for Texas.''
	   He also had a memorable guest role on an early episode of ``The
X-Files'' as an ill-fated faith healer.
	   The Canadian native grew up on a farm _ ``more of a hobby farm,
a big garden,'' he says _ in Steinbach, Manitoba. There was a
family tradition of artistic creativity: father Doug is the
longtime principal oboist with the Winnipeg Symphony, and mother,
Diane, was a cellist until arthritis forced a career switch to
family counseling.
	   ``They really raised me to be a free spirit, which I think
facilitated my choices,'' said Bairstow. He started his career on
the Canadian children's show, ``Let's Go.'' He first gained notice
here in the 1993 TV movie, ``There Was a Little Boy.''
	   He and his wife, Marty, are raising 3-year-old Casey in suburban
Seattle, away from the smog and congestion of Los Angeles. And away
from the heart of the entertainment industry, a fact that doesn't
worry Bairstow.
	   ``I've been doing it (acting) since I was 10 and doing it
professionally in the States since I was about 20,'' said Bairstow.
The soft-spoken actor seems confident _ but not cocky _ that he can
keep his hand in.
	   1. On ``Significant Others'' you played Henry, a talented writer
who's made a living writing racy stories for the Internet. Are you
an online junkie?
	   Bairstow: I have a 3-year-old son who's smarter than me. I want
to wait until there's a little more control on the Internet or I
have a little more knowledge of how to control it so my son's not
open to seeing things I wouldn't want him to at this age.
	   2. The ``Significant Others'' character was unsettled and unsure
of what he wanted. Is it fair to say you're someone who isn't
reluctant to make decisions?
	   Bairstow: I haven't shied away from commitments. It's just sort
of life for me. I guess God puts things on your plate and you've
got to choose whether or not you're gonna eat them. I haven't spit
anything out yet.
	   3. Why did you decide so young to become an actor?
	   Bairstow: I can't even remember deciding. It's like it's always
what I've done, starting early, being in plays in grade four or
even before then. ... I think a true actor is just an actor. I
mean, I haven't gone to school for it, it's just inside of me, I
think. An undeniable thing. I just thank God I realized it at a
young age.
	   4. What's it like being a dad?
	   Bairstow: Awesome. People ask me, 'Did you ever think you were
going to be a dad?' And I'd say, 'Yeah, I did.' Because I see
myself as a parent. But I didn't know what I was talking about. I
really love it. It's like if you cut off your arm and had it walk
around; it's the same kind of thing.
	   5. Given your dedication to your family and career, it seems
that when people talk about Gen X, they're not talking about you.
	   Bairstow: Well, I'd like to think they are. I'd like to think
the face they painted on Gen X isn't as true as they like to think
it is. That's just a bunch of people in suits saying, 'Here's this
generation that doesn't care about anything and thinks society owes
them.' I just don't think that's correct.
</TEXT>
