<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Video Nation,0935 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
America: One big TV show, and all the extras you'll ever need 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ``When I look at the television, I want to see me starin' right
back at me.''
	   _Counting Crows
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; By TED ANTHONY &QC; 
 &UR; AP National Writer &QC; 
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Truman Burbank of ``The Truman Show'' might be
considered one lucky man. His ``life'' is unequivocal,
choreographed _ and utterly safe. Television birthed him, nurtured
him and watches over him. Television, quite literally, makes his
sun rise.
	   Now here's the rub: While Truman (Jim Carrey) strives to escape
TV-land and reach the real world outside, we in the ``real world''
are busy struggling to escape to television's fantasy world.
	   ``The Truman Show'' and real life, in diametrically opposite
ways, both demonstrate that the lines between television and
reality are blurring. Like the new Peter Weir movie, the whole
world's becoming a soundstage.
	   Everywhere in real life, there is a video camera. Not just the
security cameras trained perpetually on office elevators, automated
teller machines, the aisles of discount stores and elsewhere,
recording and preserving countless disposable moments. Not just
JenniCam, in which anyone wanting a voyeuristic glimpse into a
narcissistic twentysomething's boudoir simply needs to type in an
Internet address.
	   It goes far deeper. In the 1990s, neighbor films neighbor,
parent films child, child films pet, all for entertainment _ and
perhaps for that chance at the nationwide candid camera that Allen
Funt conceived and ``America's Funniest Home Videos'' anointed.
	   Live TV only augmented that. It showed Oswald taking Ruby's
bullet, Bobby Kennedy taking Sirhan Sirhan's bullet, demonstrators
being beaten by Chicago police and Neil Armstrong moonwalking. The
Challenger exploded in real time; O.J. led a slo-mo police chase
and the choppers filmed from above.
	   Camcorders hit the shelves and reality became king _ Rodney King
_ as would-be filmmakers caught everyday activities and horrors on
film. Now Dave Letterman's best comedy involves a camera and the
unexpected reactions of random people on the street. Fox serves up
``When Animals Attack,'' ``America's Deadliest Police Chases'' and,
yes, ``America's Deadliest Swarms.'' And of course we have Jerry
Springer _ faux verite, let's call it. All are symptoms of the same
syndrome: Americans want to be on television, and ``real''
Americans want to watch other ``real'' Americans on TV.
	   ``We've become bored with watching actors give us phony
emotions,'' says the megalomaniacal director Christof (Ed Harris)
in ``The Truman Show.'' And he's right on target. The addiction to
fiction has been replaced by a zeal for the real.
	   When Truman finally does communicate with Christof, he asks the
understandable question: ``Was nothing real?''
	   ``You were real,'' the director replies. ``That's what made you
so good to watch.''
	   Americans want not only to consume their narratives, but to
participate. So we blur. People tape their party, then have another
party to watch the video. Tourists roam Manhattan's streets with
camcorders, shooting moving pictures of motionless buildings.
Princess Diana, one of the nearest things the world has ever had to
a Truman, was, publicly, the star of a show _ her life. When she
died, Weir says, ``the show really was over.''
	   That's not all. MSNBC _ a legitimate news organization _ appears
as a fictional doppelganger of itself in the movie ``Deep Impact,''
dutifully chronicling Armageddon. Sundry senators guest-star on
``Murphy Brown.'' Geraldo mimics his own show on the ``Seinfeld''
finale. The real becomes the fictional. And the reverse. ``Gopher''
from ``Love Boat'' and ``Cooter'' from ``The Dukes of Hazzard''
emerge from show business to become congressmen. Ronald Reagan
serves two terms as president. ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' made as a
movie parody, leads to a Spinal Tap tour _ and more than one album.
The fictional becomes the real.
	   Dizzying.
	   In the end, Christof smites Truman but also loves him _ like a
god. Truman's deity is literally TV. He is Job, enduring anything
and everything for the God of Give the People What They Want. He's
the opposite of Chauncey Gardener in ``Being There.'' Gardener was
perfect for the 1970s: Reality was too much, so he became
television. For Truman in 1998, television is now the standard _
the default _ and reality is the goal.
	   But Truman (``True Man'') Burbank (the city in California where
many TV shows are taped), trying to escape a patterned existence,
neglects the ultimate solution: simply sitting around and doing
utterly nothing. No audience would stand for that.
	   Consider two final thoughts. The first is, once again, from
Christof. ``I have given Truman the chance to lead a normal life.
The world _ the place YOU live in _ is the sick place,'' he says in
the film. ``Ultimately, Truman prefers his cell.''
	   Now listen to Debbie Zanbrano, a Pennsylvania resident whose
town was struck by a particularly violent storm a few days ago. She
was watching CBS-TV's ``Touched by an Angel'' when the town's fire
whistle blew.
	   ``I thought, `This is like TV,''' she said. ``Then the winds
woke me up and got me to move.''
	   So maybe that ``Truman Show'' world isn't so far away.
Television is our frame of reference to reality, and now reality is
becoming our programming staple. We're filming our lives, raw and
self-aware, and we're putting them on television. We like our cell,
and we're decorating it to fit our needs.
	   But in the end, in many ways, it's still a locked room.
</TEXT>
