<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Audio Reviews,0541 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sound Bites: Audio Reviews SOUND BITES 
</HEADLINE>
By ERIC FIDLER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ``Twistin' in the Wind'' (MCA) _ Joe Ely
	   ``Twistin' in the Wind'' opens with a great dramatic flourish,
``Up on the Ridge,'' a tremendous song of epic scope and epic
guitar playing. Flamenco guitarist Teye gives it a sense of
melodrama, Jesse Taylor contributes stinging leads and Lloyd Maines
adds knifelike steel guitar. Ely is a Texan with a gift for story
songs and a flair for adding the flavors of the border to his
music, and like many other musicians from his state, he mixes
country with rock and Mexican influences into a rich, rootsy blend.
	   All those strains are apparent on ``Twistin' in the Wind,'' from
the Spanish-tinged ``Queen of Heaven'' to the rollicking ``Nacho
Mama.'' The guitars that mark ``Up on the Ridge'' keep up the
joyful noise throughout, with Mitch Watkins and David Grissom also
getting in on the fun. Ely is making some noise this summer with
the reunion of the Flatlanders, his old band with Butch Hancock and
Jimmie Dale Gilmore, but this terrific album shows just how
powerful he is on his own.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ``Far From Perfect'' (Watermelon) _ Duane Jarvis
	   This unassuming little disc has enough grit and soul to restore
your faith in rock 'n' roll. Duane Jarvis drapes a pop veneer atop
a rootsy, twangy core on ``Far From Perfect,'' ending up with the
kind of album the Rolling Stones might have made before they
started to stink.
	   Jarvis, who has played guitar with such luminaries as John Prine
and Lucinda Williams, shows himself an able songwriter as well as a
deft guitarist, creating a dozen fine, rockin' tunes for ``Far From
Perfect.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ``Flores'' (Xenophile/Green Linnet) _ Conjunto Cespedes
	   Propulsive rhythms, stirring horns, churning percusson and the
glorious vocals of Bobi Cespedes make ``Flores'' a dazzling album
of Afro-Cuban music. If you can sit still during this, consult a
physician. Sensual and funky, earthy and exotic, ``Flores'' is a
find.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ``One Shoe Left'' (Snake River) _ Ben Winship
	   About the only thing separating Ben Winship from the rest of
acoustic music's royalty is geography. He's in Idaho, which is
pretty far off the Austin-Nashville axis. But Winship's deft
mandolin playing and solid songwriting make him an
off-the-beaten-track sparkler. ``One Shoe Left'' is a relaxed
album, the kind of music a bunch of talented friends sitting around
the porch might make. Luckily for us, they had the tape rolling.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ``The Ex-Husbands'' (Tar Hut) _ The Ex-Husbands
	   Some alternate-country bands seem to be longing for a bucolic
time that never was. The Ex-Husbands seem to be longing for the
honky tonk of their dreams. There's ``I Have a Ball,'' about
falling off the wagon, ``Tequila, Salt and Lime'' and ``Country
Speed,'' which would be a hit on radio if radio played good music.
	   The Ex-Husbands rock like cowpunks, but seem a little more
country-oriented than some of their alternative country colleagues.
Anders Thomsen shows he can write about more than just booze, too,
making this debut, which just snagged national distribution, worth
seeking out.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
