<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 23:49:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1033 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-FilmReview-Perfe     06-06 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Film Review-Perfect Murder,0514 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At the Movies: `A Perfect Murder' 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: movie opened Friday
By BOB THOMAS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ In their classic book of conversations,
Alfred Hitchcock told Francois Truffaut that he accepted the
assignment to film the hit play ``Dial M for Murder'' because
``that was coasting, playing it safe.'' That meant there was a
ready-made plot instead of his usual development of an original.
	   The movie, starring Grace Kelly and Ray Milland, was shot in 36
days in 3-D. Instead of ``opening up'' the play with outdoor
scenes, Hitchcock filmed most of it in a living room, digging holes
in the stage for floor-level views. Not one of his classics, ``Dial
M for Murder'' was nevertheless a success.
	   Now the Frederick Knott play emerges from a new generation of
filmmakers under the title ``A Perfect Murder'' (the Hitchcock film
is not credited as a source). Andrew Davis (``The Fugitive'')
directed newcomer Patrick Smith Kelly's screenplay.
	   Michael Douglas, who seems to specialize in domestic calamities,
portrays Steven Taylor, a high-powered commodities trader with a
beautiful young wife Emily (Gwyneth Paltrow). She is a U.N.
translator and aide to the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
She also is conducting a highly charged affair with a painter,
David Shaw (Viggo Mortensen).
	   When Taylor learns of the affair, he is shaken to the core of
his male ego. Emily has been one of his prize possessions, along
with the art collection and his investment portfolio. Besides, he
loved her.
	   But he loved money more. He has been playing the commodities on
margin, and a market shift threatens to wipe him out. Now, if his
wife were dead, his problems would be solved. She is worth dlrs 200
million through her wealthy family.
	   Taylor devises an ingenious plan _ perfect, he believes. But he
encounters some problems along the way.
	   Davis knows how to build suspense, and he punctuates the shocks
with blasts of sound effects and music (James Newton Howard's score
supplements the mood from the beginning). Kelly's script provides
clever twists that weren't in the play or Hitchcock's film.
	   Despite the gloss of upper-class Manhattan and superior acting,
the film seems formulaic and uninvolving. Like most suspense movies
nowadays, it relies too strongly on cell phones and answering
machines to further the plot.
	   Also disappointing is the role given the fine English actor
David Suchet. As the investigating detective, he becomes a minor
figure. It would have been fascinating to see TV's Hercule Poirot
solve a present-day American murder.
	   Douglas, in his ``Wall Street'' mode, is ideal as the scheming
husband, and Miss Paltrow brings intelligence and beauty to her
role as his intended victim. Mortensen, the artist with a
questionable past, brings underlying power to the other side of the
triangle.
	   The Warner Bros. release was produced by Arnold and Anne
Kopelson, Christopher Mankiewicz and Peter Macgregor-Scott. Running
time: 104 minutes.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-Film Review-Perfect Murder; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
